<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / International Capital Markets: DTB gives Globex vote of
confidence
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONIA SHARPE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DTB, Germany's financial futures exchange, said yesterday it intends to join
Globex, the electronic futures trading system developed and operated by
Reuters, the financial information and news group.
DTB's decision gives a badly-needed vote of confidence to Globex, which has
been rejected by two leading futures exchanges in the past month.
On Tuesday, Liffe, the London futures and options exchange, decided against
joining the system, blaming in part the terms which Globex had laid down.
Last month, the Chicago Board of Trade said it was pulling out of Globex
despite a new two-year agreement designed to give exchanges more
flexibility.
DTB is the third exchange to join Globex, along with the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange and Matif, the French futures exchange. Ms Rosalyn Wilton, Reuters'
managing director for transaction products, said an agreement between Globex
and DTB would be signed 'quite soon' and that its products would be listed
on the system shortly thereafter.
DTB said one of the main attractions of joining Globex was the access it
would provide to the US market. The most likely DTB products to be traded on
Globex would be its futures contracts in five-year and 10-year German
government bonds (bobls and bunds) and the corresponding options.
Futures industry observers said that since DTB did not have after-hours
trading, it should be able to mirror the success Matif has found on Globex.
Matif closed down its after-hours trading system when it joined and its
products now account for 80 per cent of volume on the system.
'Our decision forced an initial liquidity into the system because people had
no choice,' said a Matif spokeswoman. However, most of Matif's volume on
Globex is generated between 4pm and 9pm Paris time and there is virtually no
trading during the night, she said. Cross-exchange trading has also failed
to meet its goal, accounting for only 3 per cent of volume.
DTB's hopes to increase volume in its contracts through Globex could be
dashed by counter-moves at Liffe, which is keen to protect its 70 per cent
share of the market in German government bond contracts.
Mr Nick Durlacher, Liffe's chairman, said earlier this week that Liffe's
after-pit trading could easily be extended by two hours, thus taking it to
the end of the Chicago morning trading session which ends at 2pm Chicago
time. Liffe may also extend its network overseas, following the successful
installation of Liffe screens in New York.
</TEXT>
