<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / International Company News: Top trading houses hit by strong
yen and slow sales - Japanese Results
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GERARD BAKER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The combination of a harsh economic climate at home, and a surging yen
abroad produced another difficult year for Japan's five largest trading
companies. In the year ended March, four of the five groups saw profits
tumble.
The trading houses' core activities depend heavily on the flow of goods and
services in the domestic and international economy. Continuing weakness at
home was reflected in their domestic results.
Although some achieved small increases in sales, thanks largely to an
improving market in metal products, most companies reported weakness in the
large industrial sectors. Sluggish domestic demand also reduced revenues
from imports. However, for most companies, the tightest squeeze on sales
came from the exchange rate. The yen's sharp appreciation in the last year
cut exports, with car sales to the US particularly affected. Sumitomo
reported exports down by more than 20 per cent.
All five companies continued to suffer the painful consequences of
ill-starred ventures into financial products in the late 1980s. The
unwinding of these investments reduced profits further last year.
The worst performer was Itochu, which saw pre-tax profits fall by 38 per
cent. Most of the decline was the result of the liquidation of loss-ridden
financial investment schemes, and the disposal of tokkin, or specified money
trusts, worth Y110bn (Dollars 1.1bn).
These funds have left the trading companies heavily exposed since the stock
market began its precipitous decline four years ago.
Itochu has now reduced its outstanding tokkin accounts to Y97bn, against
Y566bn in 1990.
The five big groups managed to maintain the pace of cost-cutting.
Despite a fall in turnover, Marubeni reported a slight increase in pre-tax
profits as a result of deep cuts in administrative and sales costs.
Most companies forecast a rise in current year profits but remained
cautious. They expect only a gradual recovery in the Japanese economy, and
few are banking on any help from a weakening yen.
 -----------------------------------------------------------
            JAPANESE TRADING HOUSE RESULTS (Y bn)
 -----------------------------------------------------------
                   Pre-tax profit               Sales
              1993-94         1992-93   1993-94      1992-93
 -----------------------------------------------------------
Itochu          30.8            49.8     16,135     19,277.7
Mitsui          46.5            54.6   15,862.8       15,496
Marubeni        37.4            41.1     15,156       16,864
Sumitomo        35.5            41.0     15,033       16,530
Mitsubishi      50.3            74.5     14,123       14,997
 -----------------------------------------------------------
</TEXT>
