<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / International Company News: NEC to open Europe R&amp;D centre
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NEC Corporation, the large Japanese electronics group, is to open its first
European research centre in Bonn, Germany, in September. The company has
nine laboratories and three research and development centres in Japan, but
its only overseas research centres are in New Jersey in the US.
NEC said yesterday the new centre would enable the company to build closer
ties with research centres in Europe as well as helping to underpin
research, manufacturing and product sales. The initial investments will be
modest: about Y100m (Dollars 920,000) a year to support six staff. However,
there are plans to grow to a staff of 20. A director for the centre has yet
to be named.
The centre, to be sited in the German National Information Processing Centre
Technopark (GMD) in the Bonn suburbs will investigate problems associated
with advanced computing and multimedia communications systems. It will
include joint research with GMD using NEC's parallel processing
supercomputer, Cenju-3.
NEC said it believed the GMD was the leading institute in Europe for
parallel computing, distributed processing and multimedia. The Bonn location
made for easy interchange with other Europe institutes.
NEC is the second Japanese company this week to announce a European R&amp;D
initiative. On Monday, Hitachi said it was establishing a wholly-owned
semiconductor design operation in the UK to service European customers.
</TEXT>
