FT  20 MAY 94 / International Company News: Banks clear way for Euro Disney
rescue
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
All of Euro Disney's 61 creditor banks have accepted a financial
restructuring package for the troubled leisure group, Banque Nationale de
Paris and Banque Indosuez, the joint heads of the banks' steering committee,
announced yesterday.
The unanimous agreement, which ended resistance from a few of the group's
smaller creditor banks, clears the way for the final phase of the leisure
company's FFr13bn (Dollars 2.3bn) emergency restructuring.
Euro Disney shareholders must now be asked at an extraordinary meeting to
endorse proposals for a FFr6bn rights issue, which forms the core of the
restructuring package.
The meeting, expected to be announced imminently, should take place in about
a month. Details of the share issue are expected to be announced a few days
after the meeting, with the aim of completing the restructuring before the
August summer holidays.
Walt Disney, the US entertainment group which holds 49 per cent of Euro
Disney, has promised to take up its full entitlement of the rights issue.
The banks will underwrite the remaining 51 per cent.
Yesterday's announcement of a green light from all the banks coincided with
the inauguration of a high-speed rail link for the EuroDisneyland theme
park.
Mr Philippe Bourguignon, Euro Disney chairman, said the new terminus at the
theme park, connecting the Paris-Lille and the Paris-Lyon high-speed railway
lines, would improve access to EuroDisneyland. 'New horizons are opening to
us,' Mr Bourguignon said.
</TEXT>
