<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / International Company News: Hanson to step down as chief at
Calpers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Dale Hanson, one of the leading figures in the movement to strengthen
shareholder rights, is to step down as chief executive of the California
Public Employees' Retirement System (Calpers), the largest public pension
fund in the US.
Under Mr Hanson, Calpers has become one of the most aggressive - and because
of its size, influential - members of the shareholder rights movement, which
seeks to make companies more accountable to investors by improving their
corporate governance.
Mr Hanson, 51, became chief executive of the California fund in 1987. He was
expected to announce his plans at a press conference at Calpers'
headquarters in Sacramento yesterday.
Mr Hanson played an important role in encouraging the nascent shareholder
rights movement to focus on companies' poor financial performance and
agitate for change, rather than limiting its activism to issues such as
anti-takeover poison pills. He pushed hard for executive pay to be more
closely linked to financial results.
A study by Wilshire Associates, the pension consulting firm, suggested his
approach had produced positive results: the shares of companies targetted by
Calpers between 1990 and 1992 had outperformed the Standard &amp; Poor's 500
index of leading stocks.
However, his forthright criticism of corporate under-performers made him
unpopular with some pro-business Californian politicians, and he came under
pressure from Calpers' board to cut back on high-profile corporate
governance work in favour of more mundane fund administration.
His departure leaves uncertainty over Calpers' corporate governance
strategy. Mr DeWitt Bowman, Calpers chief investment officer, left the fund
recently. He has been replaced by Ms Sheryl Pressler, a former McDonnell
Douglas employee benefits fund manager.
</TEXT>
