<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / International Company News: Woolworth inquiry finds cover-up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Employees of Woolworth, the US retailer, falsified the company's financial
results in the first two quarters of last year because they believed they
were acting under orders to show a profit, an internal investigation has
found.
In spite of a conclusion that wrong-doing occurred within the company, the
report stops short of pinpointing blame. 'Recollections clashed sharply and
the evidence is in conflict,' it said.
However, Mr Charles Young, the chief financial officer, has resigned and Mr
William Lavin, chairman and chief executive officer, has been stripped of
his chairmanship. He will become vice-chairman
Woolworth's board launched the investigation in March after realising that,
although the previous year's annual results were correct, the quarterly
results were wrong. Profits had been reported in the first two quarters when
the company had in reality incurred losses.
Employees tried to conceal losses by deferring costs till later in the year,
when the financial position was expected to improve. The plan went wrong
when the company stayed in losses for the third and fourth quarters.
The report, released late Wednesday after the stock market closed, presents
a picture of management and employees contradicting each other over who was
to blame.
It says a large number of employees interviewed commented on 'a reporting
environment at the company that placed extreme emphasis on maintaining
quarterly earnings, and more specifically, reporting quarterly financial
results consistent with budget projections.'
Mr Selig Adler, chief financial officer of Woolworth's Kinney Shoe
Corporation subsidiary, told the board that Mr Young, the parent company's
chief financial officer, had instructed him to report inaccurate quarterly
results 'so as to inflate the company's publicly reported profits'.
Mr Young conceded he might have described some preliminary results as
'unacceptable' but said he had never asked anyone, directly or indirectly,
to report inaccurate figures.
An employee of Woolworth's Canadian subsidiary told the investigators he had
been directed by Mr E. Ronald Gamble, the unit's chief financial officer, to
report monthly financial results 'that differed from the numbers contained
in the general ledger, thereby overstating Canada's interim operating
results'.
Mr Gamble confirmed this but said he had been directed by the then chief
executive of Woolworth Canada and Mr Young to report different numbers. The
former Woolworth Canada chief executive and Mr Young denied the allegation.
Mr Lavin, group chief executive, conceded in interviews with the
investigators he had pushed employees hard to verify earnings numbers. 'It
is conceivable that because of my position and forcefulness, subordinates
could feel pressure and misperceive my intentions.' But he added: 'I
certainly did not intend my remarks to be construed as encouragement to
report other than truthful numbers.'
Mr Young, resigning as chief financial officer, denied any misconduct. But
in his resignation letter dated May 17, he said conditions had so changed he
could no longer effectively discharge his duties.
Mr Lavin and Mr Young stepped aside during the investigation. Mr Young will
be replaced by Mr Andrew Hines, earlier appointed his temporary replacement,
while the new non-executive chairman will be Mr John Adams, the outside
director who headed the investigation.
A criminal investigation appears unlikely, but the Securities and Exchange
Commission has launched an inquiry into the accounting irregularities. The
company remains the target of shareholder lawsuits.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Woolworth Corp.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
