<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / UK Company News: NSM returns to the black and launches
Pounds 40m rights
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WIGHTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NSM, the debt-laden international coal mining group, is more than trebling
its equity with a heavily discounted rights issue to raise Pounds 40m.
The cash call was accompanied by figures showing a recovery to pre-tax
profits of Pounds 2.1m for the year to March 31 compared with losses of
Pounds 9.8m.
Mr John Jermine, executive chairman, said an injection of equity was
required to complete the restructuring started three years ago which
reversed the diversifications of the late 1980s. 'The refinancing will
provide NSM with sufficient facilities to continue to develop its businesses
and to assess the opportunities presented by the privatisation of British
Coal.'
NSM, which produced 1.6m tonnes of coal from opencast mines in the UK last
year, might be interested in individual British Coal assets but is unlikely
to venture outside its opencast expertise. Mr Jermine stressed: 'Any
acquisitions will be bolt-on and we would not do anything that was not
earnings enhancing.'
Alongside the rights issue, which would reduce pro forma gearing from 158
per cent to 52 per cent at March 31, NSM's banks, led by Bank of Scotland,
have agreed to provide 'substantial' new facilities.
The terms of the rights issue are 5-for-2 at 100p compared with a market
price of 174p, down 43p yesterday. Institutions accounting for 57 per cent
of the shares are committed to taking up their rights with the remainder
underwritten by Noble Grossart and Cazenove.
Mr Jermine said the deep discount reflected the size of the issue, the
company's 'difficult' history and the uncertain future facing the coal
industry. But changes in the UK industry would also produce a 'lot of
opportunities which have not crystallised yet'.
Although NSM's UK tonnage dropped from 2m last year, the proportion sold
direct to generators rose to a quarter as less lucrative contracts with
British Coal declined.
Sales from continuing operations slipped to Pounds 111.9m (Pounds 114.1m)
producing operating profits before interest of Pounds 9.54m (Pounds 7.04m).
Earnings per share were 12.3p (59.1p losses).
COMMENT
The rights issue will merely restore NSM's balance sheet to reasonable
health rather than give it the muscle to take on allcomers in the break up
of British Coal. For now the main strategy is to concentrate on reducing
costs per tonne on both sides of the Atlantic. In the UK it should be helped
by relaxation of restrictions on private operators - notably in the size of
opencast sites - and in the US by recent capital investment in new reserves
and drift mines. Thanks to the interest saving from the rights issue profits
should top Pounds 6m this year. At the notional ex-rights price the shares
are on a prospective multiple of about 14, reflecting the balance of
opportunities and uncertainties.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>NSM.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P1221 Bituminous Coal and Lignite-Surface.
    P1222 Bituminous Coal-Underground.
</IN>
