<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / UK Company News: Conrad Black cuts his stake in The
Telegraph
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Hollinger, the Canadian publishing group controlled by Mr Conrad Black, has
cut its stake in The Telegraph, holding company of The Daily Telegraph, from
66.2 per cent to 57 per cent.
However, Hollinger indicated that it was committed to retaining control of
The Telegraph and had no further plans at this stage to reduce its stake
further.
With the proceeds from this sale, totalling about CDollars 152m (Pounds
73m), Hollinger has more than recouped its entire CDollars 314m investment
in The Telegraph over the past nine years, as well as having earned a
sizeable rate of return.
The company realised CDollars 187m from a portion of its Telegraph shares
when the UK company made a public offering in 1992, and raised another
CDollars 17m late last year.
Hollinger said there was no particular significance in the timing of the
sale, except that it had planned for some time to get back the money it had
ploughed into The Telegraph as a form of 'discipline' in its investment
strategy.
The sale involves 12.5m shares, which were sold at 587p each to Goldman
Sachs and Cazenove.
Shares in The Telegraph closed yesterday down 20p at 600p.
Mr Black paid 100p per Telegraph share when he made his initial investment
in 1985. A year later, Hollinger paid 50p per share to bring its investment
in The Telegraph up to 50 per cent.
Hollinger said the proceeds of the latest sale would be used for general
corporate purposes. It added that the transaction was unrelated to its
recent purchase of the Chicago Sun-Times, or the withdrawal of a small
public offering planned by UniMedia, a wholly owned Canadian newspaper
group.
See Market Report
</TEXT>
