<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / UK Company News: Wheels offshoot sold as AAF losses rise to
Pounds 34m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BLACKWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AAF Industries, the building systems company, yesterday said it was selling
Alloy Wheels International and its 49 per cent stake in Kent Properties for
Pounds 19m to Murray &amp; Roberts Engineering of South Africa.
It also announced a pre-tax loss of Pounds 33.7m for 1993 on total turnover
of Pounds 78.8m. It compares with a pre-tax profit of Pounds 4.76m on
turnover of Pounds 72m.
AWI, the biggest aluminium alloy wheel maker in the UK, will retain its
borrowings of Pounds 10.2m.
The disposal leaves AAF with pro forma net worth of Pounds 21m, compared
with Pounds 35m at the end of 1992. Without the proceeds, which will be used
to pay off Pounds 6.7m of debt and provide working capital, net worth would
be Pounds 15.4m.
AWI, which was bought by AAF for Pounds 13.2m three years ago, made profits
of Pounds 722,000 on turnover of Pounds 31.8m last year. It had net assets
of Pounds 12.3m at December 31.
Mr Alex Brown, who took over as chief executive last summer, said yesterday
that the group would have considered selling at the Pounds 19m offer price
whatever the financial circumstances. As it was, AAF could now stop
negotiating with its banks and get on with running the remaining business.
The group's problems stemmed from the expansion of its prefabricated
building manufacturing business in Blackburn into an on-site contractor.
Mr Brown said sorting out the problems had proved 'a painful and difficult
exercise'. The site was now closed.
The closure and other reorganisation costs accounted for Pounds 24.5m of the
latest loss, including a total of Pounds 4.9m of goodwill written off. A
further Pounds 1.5m of goodwill was written off on the disposal of Diamond,
its US modular building subsidiary, for Dollars 33.3m (Pounds 22.2m) last
November.
The group has also written down by Pounds 3.5m its operating assets of the
hire and site services business.
Net interest payable was Pounds 3.31m (Pounds 2.1m).
Losses per share were 157p, compared with earnings of 24p last year. The
board is not recommending a final dividend.
</TEXT>
