<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / UK Company News: Denby coming to market with Pounds 43m tag
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Denby Group, the stoneware pottery maker, yesterday announced the final
details of its flotation with a share price of 130p, which values the
company at Pounds 43.3m.
Based on this share price, and forecast pre-tax profits of Pounds 4.1m for
the year to September 30, the group is coming to the market on a prospective
multiple of 14.
This compares with about 17.5 for Portmeirion Potteries, which has been
cited as its closest comparison in the sector.
Denby also forecast a final dividend of at least 1.4p for the year to
September 30 and earnings of 9.2p. Based on the pre-tax forecast, the
notional full year dividend would have been 3.1p, with a yield of 3 per
cent.
Denby, which is returning to the market after a 13 year absence, is issuing
20.4m shares through a placing and open offer to raise Pounds 8.5m net for
the company. Some 15.3m shares are being placed with institutions. The
balance will also be placed, although subject to a clawback depending on the
public demand for shares.
Mr Stephen Riley, managing director, has said the group intends to use the
proceeds to pay off the debt incurred in the Pounds 5m venture
capital-backed management buy-out in 1990. The board will retain 22 per cent
of the enlarged company, with existing shareholders owning a further 17 per
cent.
The group has spent the last four years recovering from mishaps which began
with an ill-fated diversification in the US in the 1970s.
Heavy losses led to a takeover by Crown House in 1981, and eventually
Coloroll, which collapsed in 1990. Since Denby's management bought the
company pre-tax profits have risen from Pounds 724,000 in the 18 months to
September 30 1991.
COMMENT
The glut of flotations left Denby coming to the market with a price lower
than many existing shareholders might have wished. The rating seems about
right, however, given the difficulties which many are facing in getting new
issues away. Investors can look forward to substantial growth abroad, and
might want to study Portmeirion's experience in the US for future potential.
</TEXT>
<XX>
