<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / UK Company News: Flotation values ICG at Pounds 105m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD GOURLAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Shares in Intermediate Capital Group, the specialist provider of mezzanine
finance to unlisted companies, were priced at 225p yesterday, valuing the
group at Pounds 105m.
The issue is fully underwritten by Lazard Brothers and will be placed with
institutional and other investors. There is also a clawback to meet demand
from an intermediaries offer.
The notional gross dividend yield for the year ended January 1994 is 5.5 per
cent. Since it was formed in 1989, ICG has carved out a niche providing
loans to fund management buy-outs and buy-ins, acqu-isitions and development
cap-ital.
The group enhances returns by receiving warrants or a redemption premium
when the investment is realised.
COMMENT
Niche lender, Intermediate Capital Group, is a strange animal. Part bank and
part investor in unquoted companies, it is both an operating company that
lends and an investment trust with a portfolio of equity stakes. Judging by
the pricing, the company's advisers are confident institutions agree ICG
should not be valued as an investment trust - Pounds 105m values the group
at a 19 per cent premium to net asset value. Viewed as a specialist lender,
however, ICG's notional gross dividend of 5.5 per cent is only just covered
by earnings from core interest income, dividends and management fees. Hardly
comfortable cover in conventional terms. But then the group hopes to
continue to realise capital gains through further sales of equity. ICG is
not a stock for risk-averse investors. It is a growth stock underpinned by
an unusually high yield. But for investors who believe ICG can maintain its
healthy, if short, record of realising capital gains, the shares have some
attractions.
</TEXT>
