<PROFILE>_AN-EETCSAEIFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940520
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / British Gas feels pain of regulation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT CORZINE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The steady erosion of British Gas's profitability through growing
competition and regulatory pressure was underlined yesterday when the
company reported first-quarter historical cost profits of Pounds 634m, down
from Pounds 650m.
Mr Richard Giordano, chairman, repeated a warning that full-year results
were likely to be below 1993. He added that uncertainty over the regulatory
environment made it 'inappropriate to comment on dividend prospects.'
British Gas shares, however, closed up 4 1/2 p at 284p.
First-quarter earnings per share were 14.6p, against 15.1p.
The drop in earnings would have been steeper without particularly cold
weather in what is the company's most important quarter. Increased volumes
were reflected in higher turnover of Pounds 3.67bn (Pounds 3.61bn) and a
Pounds 30m rise in operating profits from UK gas supply to Pounds 773m.
But Mr Giordano said the 'underlying trend of profits in that business
remains downwards due to regulatory pressure on prices in the tariff sector
and loss of market share, mainly in the firm contract market'.
Ofgas, the industry regulator, yesterday published a consultation paper that
could lead to the removal of some of that pressure.
Ms Clare Spottiswoode, Ofgas director general, said it was time to decide
whether it was still 'appropriate' to maintain constraints imposed on
British Gas as part of the government's efforts to open up the firm contract
market, mainly for industrial and large commercial users.
These require British Gas to sell gas only on the basis of published and
non-discriminatory tariffs. It must also reduce its share of the market
above 2,500 therms a year to 55 per cent by 1995, a level which British Gas
says was reached at the end of last month. 'Unless the constraints on our
ability to compete are lifted soon, our market share will continue to fall,'
Mr Giordano said yesterday.
Mr Cedric Brown, chief executive, welcomed the Ofgas proposal, which he said
was 'long overdue.' But even if the restrictions were lifted, there would be
little positive impact on the company's performance this year.
Mr Brown noted that there was still 'massive uncertainty' over the impact of
future regulations. Consultation on how the domestic market will be opened
to competition is taking place. And an Ofgas document is due shortly on the
pricing formula for use of British Gas's transportation and storage network.
</TEXT>
