<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / Deutsche makes DM500m provision for Schneider loans
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DUSSELDORF
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Deutsche Bank will have to make provisions of DM500m (Pounds 200m) against
its exposure to the collapsed Jurgen Schneider property group, the bank's
chief executive said yesterday. This is about 40 per cent of the bank's
total DM1.2bn loans to Schneider.
The bank had previously insisted that its loans to finance eight of
Schneider's property developments were well secured, although it had hinted
that provisions would amount to several hundred million D-Marks. Analysts
had estimated that the bank would have to make provisions of DM300m. The
Schneider group's collapse last month was the biggest in Germany's property
sector since the second world war.
Mr Hilmar Kopper and his boardroom colleagues faced intense shareholder
criticism over the Schneider affair, at the bank's annual meeting in
Dusseldorf yesterday.
Last month he dismissed the DM50m owing to trade creditors as 'peanuts', but
yesterday he was apologetic about the bank's role and for this particular
comment. 'Mistakes of professional judgment were certainly made,' he
conceded.
He added that loans to Schneider were made in at least one case on the basis
of manipulated documentation, for example forged rental agreements which
gave rise to fraudulent property valuations.
Mr Kopper told shareholders that despite the Schneider affair the level of
provisioning against bad and doubtful debts would actually fall at the bank
this year, reflecting recovery in the German economy. However, he said the
bank's record profits in 1993 could not be matched this year. Group
operating profit, after risk provisioning, was down more than 10 per cent in
the first four months, against the comparable period in 1993.
The interest margin showed signs of narrowing, Mr Kopper said, and profits
from the bank's own account trading activities would be down from last
year's spectacular levels. Last year group operating profits rose 16 per
cent to DM5.3bn, after taking account of a DM1.4bn increase in risk
provisioning to DM3.3bn.
Lex, Page 18
