<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / Thomson Directories bought by US West
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
US West, the regional telecoms company covering 14 midwestern US states, is
increasing its stake in the highly competitive UK telecoms market with the
purchase of Thomson Directories for about Pounds 70m.
The move pitches US West into competition with British Telecommunications
for UK business directory services, which it believes are underdeveloped.
It views the purchase as an important means of gaining access to businesses
for the development of multi-media services.
US West's international strategy centres on mobile communications and
combined cable television and telephone networks, which it plans to develop
for inter-active services. In the UK it has a 50 per cent stake in Mercury
One-2-One, a cellular mobile network, and a similar stake in TeleWest, a
cable company claiming more than 150,000 telephone subscribers.
Thomson Directories, which publishes 155 business directories in the UK
serving 1.6m businesses, is owned by the Thomson Corporation, the Canadian
publishing and travel group, and Dun &amp; Bradstreet, the US information
products and services company.
It started life in 1966 publishing Yellow Pages for the Post Office under
contract. Since going it alone it has engaged in protracted disputes with BT
over access to BT's numbering database. Mr Alain Treille, US West director
of international marketing, said the dispute had now been 'resolved
satisfactorily'.
BT has about 85 per cent of the directory advertising market with its Yellow
Pages division, and has been diversifying with products such as Talking
Pages.
US West said it saw 'massive potential' for developing the European
directory business, still largely in the hands of state-owned telecoms
operators. The company also has a business directory concern in Poland, and
is looking to expand in the directory market across Europe.
In the US, moves are advanced to extend the Yellow Pages concept to other
media. Last December Nynex, the Baby Bell company serving the north-east,
announced a partnership with Prodigy, a national computer information
network owned by IBM and Sears, to introduce a Yellow Pages service for
personal computers.
