<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / Heseltine concedes ground on Post Office sell-off
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government is to test public opinion over its plans to privatise the
Post Office by publishing a green paper containing its favoured option of
selling 51 per cent of the Royal Mail and Parcelforce.
But in issuing a consultative document ministers were acknowledging that
they may have to dilute their preferred sell-off option or even drop it.
Backbenchers opposed to privatisation said they would use the 'breathing
space' to try to persuade the government to abandon the flotation plan, or
to stop it from selling a majority stake.
The cabinet's so-called consolidators, who oppose further radical
legislation, are understood to have won important concessions from Mr
Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary.
Mr Heseltine had wanted to privatise the whole of the Royal Mail and
Parcelforce. But the consolidators made it clear they would only give the
go-ahead to privatisation if the government continued to hold at least 49
per cent of the shares and allowed a further period of consultation.
Mr Heseltine said the green paper would be published within weeks. He is
still confident of bringing forward a bill in November to privatise the
Royal Mail and Parcelforce after a consultation period of several months.
In a bid to allay backbenchers' fears, he committed the government to a
universal tariff and said stamps would continue to be exempt from value
added tax.
The government also obtained the Queen's permission for the depiction of her
head on postage stamps, the use of Royal emblems and permission to register
a privatised Royal Mail at Companies House.
The green paper is likely to spell out the government's desire to give
employees 'a significant holding of shares', which one minister said could
be as much as 15 per cent.
Post Office Counters has secured the freedom it wanted to increase the scale
of its activities.
The Treasury has agreed that rural post offices will continue to be
subsidised by about Pounds 25m. Only a quarter of Counters' turnover comes
from the Royal Mail, but the government would still require the letters
division to continue to use post offices.
However, backbenchers continue to oppose the privatisation.
Mr Patrick Cormack, Conservative MP for Staffordshire South, said: 'There
are many old fashioned Tories, of whom I am proud to be one, who view the
prospect of Royal Mail plc about as favourably as they would view your old
regiment being replaced by Group 4 at Buckingham Palace.'
Postal lobbyists' first-class service, Page 10
