<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / The Lex Column: Deutsche Bank
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
It is easy to dismiss Deutsche Bank's DM500m loss provisions in connection
with the Schneider affair as trivial in the broader sweep of events. The
figure compares with total group provisions of DM3.3bn last year; even after
the Schneider charge, provisions will be down in 1994. It is harder to
dismiss the impact on Deutsche's image. Together the Schneider and
Metallgesellschaft cases have revealed it to be less conservative than many
of its admirers thought. At yesterday's annual meeting Mr Hilmar Kopper,
Deutsche's management board spokesman, was reluctant to point fingers while
official inquiries are still under way. At some stage, though, the bank will
have to demonstrate clearly that it has put its house in order. One danger,
if it does not, is that its share rating will suffer because its business is
perceived as riskier. In the short term, though, the main concern is
operating profit. During the first four months profits were running more
than 10 per cent below the average rate for 1993 as a whole. The comparison
may not be entirely fair for seasonal reasons, but the shortfall in trading
income is clearly having a significant impact, while Mr Kopper said interest
margins have narrowed further. His comments only serve to reinforce the view
that Deutsche, like other German financial stocks, is less likely to
out-perform now that interest rates must be coming within sight of their
floor. Industrial stocks should show more impressive earnings performance as
corporate restructuring and, eventually, economic recovery take hold.
</TEXT>
