<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / Leading Article: Sickly steel
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Karel van Miert, Europe's competition commissioner, may have been a shade
premature yesterday in announcing the death of his 15-month-old plan to cut
excess capacity in the European steel industry. Though the plan looks
increasingly fragile, its condition need not be terminal. On balance, it is
probably still just worth trying to revive it.
The latest complications are, for once, not due to resistance by EU
governments or steelmakers. Indeed, Brussels finally seems to be making
headway in persuading unsubsidised producers to offer production cuts needed
to complete the package by the end of this year. Rather, the cause is an
unexpected decision by Mr van Miert's fellow commissioners to veto a
proposed revision of the plan's terms to cover small steelmakers in northern
Italy. Since the issue turns on legal technicalities, and not on principle,
it ought to be soluble.
It cannot seriously be argued that the plan deserves to survive because it
is perfect. It manifestly is not. The child of political compromise, it
calls on efficient, unsubsidised steelmakers to shoulder too much of the
adjustment and requires too little of flabby state-owned producers. These
had to be bribed into co-operation with promises of still further subsidies.
Furthermore, some of their proposed capacity cuts look bogus.
The strongest case for the plan is that the alternatives look even worse.
Scuttling it would be unlikely to encourage healthy rationalisation. The
more probable result would be another subsidy race which would penalise
efficient producers and invite fresh US trade sanctions against European
steel exports. The Commission's other option would be to declare a 'manifest
crisis', empowering it to impose cuts and fix prices. That failed abysmally
when tried in the 1980s.
The commissioners should try again to settle their differences. That is far
from an ideal outcome. But while European governments refuse to let the
market solve industrial problems for which their past policies were largely
responsible, it looks the least bad course available.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>BEZ  Belgium, EC.
    QRZ  European Economic Community (EC).
</CN>
<XX>
