<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / Observer: British reserve
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The Chartered Institute of Bankers deserves a prize. After 116 years it has
elected a non-Brit as president - Andreas Prindl, a fiercely well-educated
American who works for a Japanese bank.
Not before time, since a quarter of the institute's members are non-Brits.
Let's hope the open-door policy catches on. The London Investment Banking
Association, the grandchild of the old Accepting Houses Committee, has
already picked a Brit as its next president - Flemings' John Manser. But
next time round it might pluck up courage and choose a foreigner, such as
Union Bank of Switzerland's Rudi Mueller.
At least it has dropped the British from its title - unlike the British
Bankers Association. It has never had a non-Brit as president in its 75-year
history. Given that the BBA represents over 300 banks from more than 60
countries which happen to operate in Britain it could make a start by
renaming itself.
</TEXT>
<XX>
