<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / A season for sacrifices: John Murray Brown examines Turkey's
economic crisis
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MURRAY BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
As Turks prepare for tomorrow's festival of the Sacrifice of Abraham, a
gloomy mood pervades the capital Ankara. For this year's Bayram (Eid
al-Adha), which families traditionally celebrate by exchanging gifts and
slaughtering their favourite sheep, finds Turkey in the middle of its worst
economic crisis in a decade.
The sacrifice most Turks will make this year will be an economic one. For
the government is steeling its political nerve to implement a set of
measures which even the International Monetary Fund is concerned may prove
overambitious.
The prime minister Mrs Tansu Ciller is invoking the spirit of the war of
independence against Greek and other forces in the 1920s in a bid to muster
public support for her plan for national revival.
Most bankers and economists, and some government officials, believe Turkey
cannot get through the crisis alone. Much hangs on an IMF agreement. An IMF
mission left Ankara on Wednesday after two weeks of negotiations on the
austerity programme announced by Mrs Ciller on April 5. Turkey is seeking a
one-year standby loan of about Dollars 450m to support its balance of
payments, half of which could be immediately disbursed.
Turkey will need the understanding of its foreign bankers if it is to escape
a debt rescheduling. With about Dollars 4.7bn of medium- and long-term
principal to be repaid this year, the government is also relying on measures
from creditors such as the European Union and Japan to refinance this
amount.
Turkey's request for a standby loan is to be presented to the IMF board in
July. The fund's approval would send a signal that international confidence
in Turkey was rising.
Until then, Mrs Ciller has to keep her adjustment measure on track, holding
the line on wages in the current biannual talks with civil servants and
public sector workers, and meeting repayments on Turkey's Dollars 66bn
foreign debt, of which about Dollars 1.3bn is due at the end of June.
Even if a standby agreement is concluded, funds would be frozen if Turkey
slipped up on what are likely to be extremely strict performance targets set
by the IMF. Moreover, any World Bank structural adjustment loans, also under
negotiation in parallel with the IMF deal, would be put on hold. Turkey's
foreign bankers may also consider cutting their lines of credit. This could
lead to a balance of payments crisis, forcing Turkey to a full debt
rescheduling with both the Paris and London clubs of creditors. Such a
development would put Mrs Ciller's political survival at serious risk.
Turkey's economic ills can only in part be laid at Mrs Ciller's door. The
main reason is the refusal of successive governments to tackle growing
fiscal deficits, the root cause of Turkey's persistently high inflation
rate, which last month rose to an annualised 107 per cent. Second, the
impact of new financial instruments such as asset-backed securities, has
undermined the ability of Turkey's central bank to control the money supply.
Third, Mrs Ciller last year launched an unsuccessful attempt to push down
interest rates on government paper in a bid to reduce budget costs.
In the first quarter of this year, without being able to borrow domestically
and with the international debt markets closed off after a series of credit
downgradings by the agencies Moody's and Standard &amp; Poor's, the government
was forced to go to the central bank for short-term advances to finance the
budget. The resulting increase in money supply set in train a run on the
Turkish lira. The lira has fallen in value by 50 per cent against the US
dollar since January.
Nevertheless, there are signs that confidence is slowly returning. Earlier
this month, for the first time this year, the government sold Treasury bills
at auction, albeit in relatively small volumes. Interest rates, having been
as high as 400-500 per cent over the past three months, are edging down and
the exchange rate appears to be stabilising at about TL33,000 to the dollar,
compared with a low of TL41,000 in mid-April. Central bank reserves are
recovering slightly, although at Dollars 3bn, they are at half the levels of
1993.
The fiscal adjustment plan comprises both short-term stabilisation measures
and longer-term structural reforms. It envisages halving the projected
deficit to Dollars 2.8bn by the end of the year and slashing the public
sector borrowing requirement from 17 per cent to 10 per cent of gross
national product, through a Dollars 2.1bn one-off wealth tax, a 15 per cent
real wage cut in the public sector, laying off 30,000 state workers, and
speedier privatisation.
Pain is being felt across the economy. Business people think the government
is leaving companies to fend for themselves in an officially engineered
recession, while calling on the private sector to make new tax
contributions.
Three banks have already been closed by the Treasury. The authorities
recently introduced unlimited deposit insurance to stem the haemorrhaging of
savings from the banking sector. The policy appears to have worked, although
over the longer term, it could encourage banks to pursue imprudent
practices.
The State Planning Organisation is projecting a fall of 4 per cent in
consumer demand this year, compared with growth in consumption of 13 per
cent last year. On one day last week, for the first time, Turkey's car
industry failed to sell a single vehicle.
Imports have been hit hard in the wake of the lira's devaluation. According
to Mr Cumhur Atilgan, of the International Transporters Association, more
than half Turkey's truck fleet is stranded in Europe, unable to find a load
for the return leg. But as a result of slower imports, officials say the
current account should come back into balance or perhaps a small surplus
this year, compared with a Dollars 6.4bn deficit in 1993.
The real challenge for the government is to curb its own finances.
Economists criticise the programme for relying too much on one-off measures
such as tax charges on the rich, without proposing more sustainable sources
of revenue.
Mrs Ciller seems to be hostage to her own bold proposals. Having announced
them with such a fanfare on April 5, she is reluctant to change course. In
rejecting the IMF's suggestion to adopt a two- or three-year adjustment
period, she may have one eye on her electoral calendar, aware that a general
election has to be held before the end of 1996.
Western diplomats are doubtful whether Mrs Ciller has the political
authority to push the programme through. They point out that it is central
government, over which she has direct control, which has taken the main
brunt of the spending cuts. State enterprises run by ministries, where there
is excess labour, have escaped relatively unscathed.
For her programme to succeed, Mrs Ciller must keep wages down. But first she
must convince workers that she is winning the battle against inflation. On
this, the jury is out.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>TRZ  Turkey, Middle East.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
