<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / Letters to the Editor: Channel 5 essential for regional
network growth
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Viscount LEWISHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, It is disappointing that once again the government is delaying a
decision on the re-advertisement of Channel 5 ('Brooke delays Channel 5
further', May 10).
The recent wave of takeovers against the ITV Channel 3 companies might well
establish competitors with the 'skyscraper' potential to improve our
position in the world markets.
But, alas, this feeding frenzy has, as a by-product, accelerated the shift
in programme making to London. It is worth noting that the holding companies
of four out of the 'Big 5' ITV companies are headquartered in the capital.
The consequence of this is that creative talent in the regions has suffered
and will continue to suffer to the point of elimination.
Channel 5, with its network of local city stations, will quickly restore the
balance, providing creative and technical jobs in the regions - as well as
extending consumer choice at no cost to the viewer or taxpayer and to the
benefit of the Exchequer.
If this government is genuine in its stated desire to encourage competition
and to foster enterprise, it will release the appropriate frequencies to
allow the ITC to readvertise Channel 5.
William Lewisham,
White Rose Television,
41 Park Square,
Leeds,
West Yorkshire LS1 2NS
