<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
There is a treat in store for those with nearly four hours to spare:
starting at 6.55 Radio 3 is relaying Carmen from Covent Garden with Placido
Domingo in the role of Don Jose for the first time at the Royal Opera House
for more than 20 years. The title role is taken by American soprano Denyce
Graves and Barseg Tumanyan sings the toreador Escamillo. In his seminal
work, 'The Complete Opera Book', Gustave Kobbe states that the character of
Carmen 'is, of course, the creation of the novelist' Merimee. But tonight in
an interval talk between Acts 1 and 2, Tony Briggs suggests that the true
model for Bizet's gypsy heroine was Pushkin's Zemfira. If opera is not to
your taste there is a mass of other music on radio to choose from. At 8.00
the Classic FM Evening Concert consists of early music including the
oratorio 'San Giovanni Battista' by the mysterious Italian composer
Alessandro Stradella, conducted by Marc Minkowski. Or how about highlights
from the recent European Brass Band Championships in Montreux, which can be
heard in Listen To The Band (9.00 Radio 2).
</TEXT>
