<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / Arts: Mummenschanz - Mime
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SOPHIE CONSTANTI
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
After 25 years of hiding inside roles of flexi-tubing, air-filled packaging
and moulded foam, the three members of Swiss Mime-theatre troupe,
Mummenschanz, have decided to call it a day, having accepted that the number
of facial expressions one can pull while sporting a malleable, doughy head
is limited.
Parade, the company's swan song at Sadler's Wells, is fashioned as a
collection of greatest hits but, four tracks into the show one realises that
Mummenschanz is a one-hit wonder and that the 'parade' denotes a tired,
conveyor-belt selection of inhabitable or manipulable props through which
the two-men, one woman team conjure up the same few sketches over and over
again.
Boy meets girls is the most familiar theme - and one which Mummenschanz
seems incapable of visualising as anything other than coy declarations of
physical attraction between a couple of over-excited yet asexual figures,
sheathed in black from head to toe.
Everything in Parade belongs to this tedious, mass appeal 'naughty but nice'
mentality and, as one might expect, it is all kept above the belt. In one
such 'headpiece' encounter, a male plug and female socket make contact and,
even after they have exited together, lights continue to flash; in another,
a pair of huge, empty, gossamer-fine condom faces billow in erect
anticipation and crumple in flaccid disappointment by turns as their owners
dash back and forth across the stage, unable to unite.
Watching these vignettes, one sees the weakness of Mummenschanz's art: it
has become a series of visual gags which have run their course. And the
theatrical notion which informs them - that is, the transformation of human
bodies into amorphous, inanimate objects, only to attempt to breathe life
into them again - amounts, on stage, to little more than perverse gimmickry.
The performer as breeze block or cylindrical roly-poly is not a new idea:
during the Bauhaus period, Oskar Schlemmer created various assemblages of
moving objects and puppet figures in his Mechanical and Triadic Ballets. At
that time, Schlemmer's pared-down physical theatre constituted a radical
departure from Expressionism. Watching Mummenschanz, however, throws one
back to a far less fertile era of performance - an era of black light mime
theatre, full of wacky tricks and cutesy, applause-milking turns.
At Sadler's Wells until May 21 (071-278-8916)
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
