<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / Arts: Uncle Silas - Theatre
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN HOYLE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
How 'richly compostly loamishly sad were those Victorian days,' wrote Stevie
Smith in Novel on Yellow Paper '. . . always someone dies, someone weeps, in
tune with the laurels dripping . . . and the dim gas flickering greenly in
the damp conservatory.'
Mike Alfreds' production of Uncle Silas for the Cambridge Theatre Company,
currently at the Lyric, Hammersmith, understands not just the eerieness of
something nasty in the shrubbery but the melancholy as well; not just death
stalking the over-upholstered drawing-rooms, honoured with cultish ritual
and jet trimmings, but that house-guest the Victorians preferred not to
acknowledge: sex. Sheridan Le Fanu's novel belongs, like Wilkie Collins' The
Woman in White, to the genre of the abused and deluded heiress driven almost
mad with terror before being rescued from nefarious plotters.
Alfreds is fond of the Gothic tale, as witness his National Theatre
production of that old chiller, The Wandering Jew. Paul Dart's designs, all
black foliage and sable swags on walls that slide silently into place,
evokes the requisite spookiness. Other elements include the grotesque menace
of the sinister French governess: Sam Cox plays her with unabashed,
raw-boned masculinity and an accent that verges on parody ('eet ees your
turn to suffair'). The production shows the affectionate mockery of style
characteristic of confident story-tellers, combined with absolute respect
for the substance.
But if the style looks back to Struwwelpeter's eruption of the nightmarish
into the almost comically prosaic, it also looks forward: to the thriller of
atmosphere, unvoiced suspicion, half-understood fears, as cumulative as a
Hitchcock film, as internalised as Henry James' Turn of the Screw, where the
reader is unsure whether the ghosts are real or products of hysteria. Did
James unconsciously remember Silas's maid Mary Quince when he created the
spectral manservant, Peter Quint?.
Here the production's bumpiness tells against the smooth spinning of a mood
of ambiguity. As practically nothing really frightening happens before the
interval, mood is all-important. The director's own adaptation pares the
narration down to a series of short, sometimes elliptical scenes. One feels
something is missing. Once the orphaned Maud (Anne Marie Duff, looking every
inch the tremulously courageous - and foolish - Victorian heroine) has taken
up residence with her mysterious Uncle Silas (Terence Wilton in a white
mane, looking like Liszt) the yarn is spun more clearly but also more
slowly.
If the pace and rhythm can be evened out there will be much to enjoy,
including often ingenious doubling. Sam Cox abandons his Gallic governess
for a brutal northern peasant; Mary Roscoe has the Dickensian gift of being
funny and touching; and Carolyn Jones splendidly differentiates between a
snarling crone below-stairs and the natural good-heartedness of the British
aristocracy. The production unwaveringly captures the sense of cruelty and
danger that a child sometimes feels when regarding the incomprehensible
world which, in this respect at least, resembles the grimmest of
fairy-tales.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P7922 Theatrical Producers and Services.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
