<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / Technology (Worth Watching): Drink, drugs, rock and roll
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW FISHER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
It sounds like an invitation to crime. The UK's Transport Research
Laboratory intends to ply drivers with alcohol and drugs and see how they
perform behind the wheel. But this will take place in a safe environment -
in TRL's new car simulator. Only the drink and drugs will be real.
TRL, part of the Department of Transport, developed the simulator with the
help of Silicon Graphics of the US. It uses technology previously associated
with complex applications such as flight simulation. Designed and built by
Maritime Dynamics of the UK, it contains a standard saloon car, modified to
provide realistic motion and operation.
Four screens surrounding the car will show realistic scenes and the sounds
of the engine and starter motor will also be simulated. 'The driver had to
be completely convinced that the car was moving, so the images had to be
totally realistic and generated instantaneously,' says Robert Sharples,
Maritime Dynamics' software manager.
Silicon Graphics: UK, 0734 257500
</TEXT>
