<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / Technology (Worth Watching): Apple peps up its Powerbooks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW FISHER and LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Apple Computer rejuvenated its line of Powerbook portable notebook computers
this week with the launch of six 'new and improved' models, writes Louise
Kehoe.
The Powerbook 500 series features a new type of cursor control device,
replacing the built-in trackball with a touch sensitive pad. By moving a
finger tip across the pad, or tapping it, the user controls the movements of
the cursor on the computer screen. Other innovations include 'intelligent
batteries', that enable users to monitor battery life accurately, and
CD-quality stereo sound capabilities for multimedia applications.
Apple also introduced two new 'sub-notebook' computers, including the first
with an active matrix colour display. They will be upgradable to the new
PowerPC chip at the heart of Apple's latest desktop Macintosh computers when
a low-power version of that chip becomes available.
By promising upgradability, Apple hopes to encourage buyers to act now
rather than wait for the PowerPC notebooks expected later this year. US
prices range from Dollars 2,269 for a Powerbook 520 with 4MB of memory,
160MB hard disk and monochrome display to Dollars 5,539 for the Powerbook
540c with 12MB of memory, 320MB hard disk, built-in modem and colour screen.
Apple Computer: US, 408-996-1010
