<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / People: CIB's cosmopolitan flavour
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The Chartered Institute of Bankers has picked a foreign banker as president
for the first time in its 116-year history. Andreas Prindl, 54, an American
who lives in London and works for a Japanese bank, has taken over from Sir
Brian Pearse as president of the main professional body for Britain's
bankers.
Prindl (right), who has been a member of the institute since 1970, began his
banking career with New York's Morgan Guaranty Trust in 1964. After stints
in Europe and Tokyo, he was seconded as chief executive of Saudi
International Bank in London. In 1984 he joined Nomura International and two
years later helped found Nomura Bank International, of which he remains
chairman.
In the past the president's job has tended to be given to senior British
clearing bankers as a mark of recognition at the end of their banking
careers. As well as Sir Brian, who stepped down as Midland Bank's chief
executive earlier this year, the post has been held recently by people like
Sir Jeremy Morse, the ex-chairman of Lloyds Bank, and Sir John Quinton, the
former chairman of Barclays Bank.
Prindl, who has a doctorate in international economics, says that the
institute faces a number of challenges 'ranging from the acceptability and
validity of its qualifications, its international commitments and the
structure of its membership, to its relationships with other institutes in
the City'. As competition in the financial services industry has grown in
recent years it has been rumoured that the Institute of Bankers might merge
with other bodies such as the Insurance Institute or the Building Societies
Association.
Prindl is not the only foreign face at the institute. Gavin Shreeve, 47, who
was educated in South Africa, is taking over as secretary-general from Eric
Glover, who is retiring after 31 years with the institute. Shreeve is a
former editor of The Banker which is owned by the Financial Times.
John Melborn, 56, deputy chief executive of National Westminster Bank, has
been elected as deputy chairman of the institute, which means that on past
form he will take over as president after Prindl has served his turn. (See
Observer)
</TEXT>
