<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / People: Fitch
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Fitch, one of the world's largest design consultancies famous for its shop
interiors, announced yesterday that its founder, Rodney Fitch, was resigning
as chairman and director of the company.
Martin Beck, group chief executive, who is based in the US, takes on the
additional role of chairman, while Jean-Francois Bentz becomes managing
director of the London office.
The announcement ends months of speculation in the trade press about Fitch's
departure from the company. It has been suggested that Fitch has had an
uneasy relationship with the firm's French partners.
The company - which has a December year-end, but has yet to announce its
preliminary results - was rescued in 1992 by a refinancing. It announced
interim pre-tax losses for the first half of the year of Pounds 381,000,
down from Pounds 1.8m the previous year.
It is believed that the company will soon announce the sale of its
headquarters, which were expensively refurbished but have slumped in value.
