<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / Management: Technology demands a more balanced view
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER LORENZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Technology tends either to daunt top managers or to dazzle them. Outside the
confines of high-technology industries such as electronics,
telecommunications and pharmaceuticals, few US and European chairmen or
chief executives have a balanced grasp of what product or process technology
can do for their company - and where the limits are. As a result they tend
to veer between suspicion of technology and over-enthusiasm for it.
The problem is particularly acute in the US and Britain, where only a
handful of top managers outside high-tech industries have a technical
background. It is aggravated further in companies which have a passion for
one-off managerial 'flavours of the month'.
Such naifs lurch constantly and dangerously between the latest
one-dimensional 'best way' of revitalising their business, and the next one.
Total quality management is overtaken by customer service, which then gives
way to 're-engineering', and so on.
Until the early 1980s the general executive attitude to technology was one
of suspicion. Studies at that time showed that, even where a company had
appointed a 'chief technology officer' or 'technical director', he was
seldom ranked by the chief executive as a core part of his team. Research
also showed that most companies' corporate and technology strategies were
developed in isolation from each other.
The arrival of microelectronics, new materials and powerful information
technology appeared to change all that, even in relatively mundane
industries such as motor vehicles and food.
But more top managements were attracted to new process technology than to
products, in part because it seemed less risky. Consultants advised them
that the quickening pace of innovation around the world was making it harder
to sustain a competitive edge through new products alone.
The process mania drew many converts. As with any new religion, the most
extreme were in the US. Deere &amp; Co, the conservative tractor maker, became
almost as carried away by factory automation as General Electric and General
Motors, which made expensive investments in the field but then proceeded to
burn their fingers badly, both as makers and users.
After several years of travail, GE, GM and Deere saw the light and pulled
back, relegating automation technology to its rightful place as part of a
wide spectrum of instruments - most of which are human and organisational,
not technological - for improving quality, flexibility, productivity and
cost-effectiveness.
But GM's new-found technomania also led it up another garden path: the idea
that IT would affect its industry so radically that it needed to own a
computer services company. It chose fast-growing Electronic Data Systems
(EDS).
This week it emerged that GM is at last planning to sell EDS. It has
recognised what common sense could have told it a decade ago: it can only
revive its fortunes by focusing all its attention on becoming a better motor
company.
In less spectacular fashion, other companies saw the IT light several years
ago. In the mid-1980s they had been dazzled by its promise, giving IT tsars
big salaries, vast budgets, and a status in the corporate hierarchy which
often outranked all other types of technology executive. But within a few
years they ran into the now familiar corporate IT pattern of overspend and
under-performance.
Richard Heygate, a McKinsey director who specialises in IT, told a
conference last week that the failure of computer technology to deliver
'bottom line value' over the past 20 years has made top executives search
for almost any method of managing change that does not rely on technology.
Technomania has given way to the old technophobia again.
This lurch in attitude is blinding top executives to the much more flexible
and cost-effective ways in which IT systems are now being designed and
applied. It is also deterring them from using intelligent technology to
reconfigure the way in which they do business, thereby stealing a
considerable march on their rivals. Benetton did that in clothing and
retailing, as have various mail order houses. First Direct has followed suit
in UK banking, and Direct Line in insurance.
In some companies, IT's plunge from grace has harmed the perception of
technology as a whole. But in others the status of research and development
has risen, as top management has realised that its consultants were wrong to
downplay the importance of product innovation. R&amp;D spending has held up
surprisingly well in the US over the last few years. In Europe, some
companies now pay their R&amp;D chief as much as his finance colleague.
But these are in the minority. In a recent study of high R&amp;D spenders, PA
Consulting and the Massachusetts Institute of Technology found that the
chief technology officer (or equivalent) was a member of the top
strategy-setting team of almost every company in Japan, but of under 60 per
cent in Europe, and of just 20 per cent in the US. Only 34 per cent of US
chief executives, and 37 per cent of the Europeans, were highly involved in
developing the company's technology strategy, compared with 46 per cent in
Japan.
In other words, most western top managers still distrust technology, and
keep it at arm's length. It is high time they made more of an effort to
understand it, and put it on an equal
footing with marketing, finance, and all the other inter-linked essentials
of the modern business system.
</TEXT>
<XX>
