<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / Painful choices on disabled bill: Concern over the cost of
compliance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART and LISA WOOD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The prime minister yesterday spelt out to the House of Commons the hard
economics which lie behind the political furore over the Civil Rights
(Disabled Persons) Bill.
Mr Major cited the official estimate of Pounds 17bn in non-recurring costs
(plus Pounds 1bn a year in subsequent costs) and the potential bill from
litigation as reasons for the government's opposition to the private
member's bill.
But are these cost figures realistic? The Confederation of British Industry
and the Institute of Directors, which have been lobbying effectively against
the bill, believe that they are. Disability lobbyists say they are not.
The institute argues that the bill is loosely drafted and does not properly
address the issue of who pays. It says that the cost of compliance could
close thousands of small businesses across the country, and even interfere
with the privatisation of British Rail (the government estimate of the costs
to the rail system is Pounds 2.85bn).
Mr Ira Chalphin, a re-searcher with the IoD, points to the dangers of
following the US experience.
He says that the Americans with Disabilities Act 1990 will turn out to be
the second most costly piece of business legislation to be enacted in the
country, after the Clean Air Act.
Both the CBI and the IoD stress that they are not opposed to
anti-discrimination legislation for the disabled, and accept that business
will have to bear some of the cost.
The CBI says, however, that this should happen through the 'normal
legislative channels' after full consultation with business.
The government has been encouraging business lobbyists to make public their
arguments and its own cost estimates. But the figure of Pounds 17bn is more
than double the true cost, according to Ms Victoria Scott, the disability
lobbyist and daughter of Mr Nicholas Scott, the minister responsible for the
disabled.
Dr Roger Berry, the Labour MP who introduced the bill, says the figure is
'absurd' and takes no account of the cost savings from employing more
disabled people.
Dr Berry, who has made no estimates of his own, says several government
departments have produced summaries of costs which include a large number of
'guesstimates' as well as being based on the recommendations being
introduced within five years.
Dr Berry said: 'The bill as amended says that the timescale would be subject
to the decisions of the secretary of state. So the government could control
the costs.'
The heaviest costs, according to the government estimate, would be incurred
by improving access to and within non-domestic buildings, including state
schools, shops and business premises.
Here the cost 'guesstimate' for the private sector alone is around Pounds
10bn.
The next heaviest bill falls on the transport industry, with changes to
land-based vehicles estimated to cost Pounds 5.5bn-Pounds 6.2bn. The
Department of Transport says that for a typical bus operator the proposed
changes would cost about Pounds 20m.
But the operators of rail services would face the heaviest cost burden.
While only 712 of the 2,796 trains on the heavy rail network remain
inaccessible to wheelchair users, the replacement costs for them would be
Pounds 2.85bn.
Changes to airlines are not included in the estimates but the department
says costs would vary greatly. One main schedule operator calculated
non-recurring costs of Pounds 2m while a charter operator suggested improved
access to 10 aircraft would cost around Pounds 16m.
</TEXT>
