<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / Ofwat outlines flow of price increases: The water industry's
likely battleground
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER and BRONWEN MADDOX
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Ofwat, the water industry regulator, will today tell the 31 water and
sewerage companies in England and Wales how quickly it thinks water bills
should rise in the next 10 years.
During the next 10 weeks the water companies have a chance to respond to the
proposed K factors - the rate above inflation at which prices may rise.
The final K factors, which Ofwat will set at the end of July, will have more
implications for the industry's structure and investment than any policy
decision since privatisation in 1989.
The difficulty for Ofwat is that the companies have embarked on huge
investment programmes - which could reach a total of Pounds 40bn this decade
 -to compensate for years of under-investment and to comply with European
environmental directives.
However, public concern about water bills, which have been rising faster
than inflation to pay for the spending, has been growing.
Mr Ian Byatt, director-general of Ofwat, has been under pressure from
consumers and the government not to allow further high price increases. He
is clearly sympathetic to that concern.
As a result some expect Ofwat to issue K factors of up to 70 per cent less
than that requested by some companies.
The water companies, however, have been stressing that if Ks are set too
low, customers will still suffer. Although customers judge drinking-water
quality primarily on colour, taste and smell, such spending might be
sacrificed to pay for legal obligations, one water industry executive said.
The tussle between the industry and Ofwat will turn on the complex detail of
the calculations. Companies have made it clear that they disagree with the
regulator over some of its assumptions.
In particular they have clashed on the method of valuing companies' assets,
and on the rate of return companies should be allowed to earn on that
capital.
In their detailed submissions to Ofwat this year, setting out the Ks they
want, many companies will have used their own valuation principles.
'The factors (such as rate of return) the companies will have put into their
version of the models will certainly be higher (than Ofwat's),' said one
water executive. 'They will not want to give away the arguments on cost of
capital, for example.'
Mr Byatt has said that he is determined to avoid 'horse-trading', and the
next 10 weeks will allow companies to point out mistakes or oversights.
However, many in the industry assume that the eventual Ks could differ
greatly from the figures sent to companies today.
Some companies have taken a more aggressive approach. 'He has told us there
will not be any negotiation, so we have prepared our submission in terms of
what we can defend at the Monopolies and Mergers Commission,' says one water
executive.
Analysts believe Ofwat's aim is to secure an overall industry K of between
zero and 2 percentage points. They argue that because the industry's capital
spending is concentrated on the 10 water and sewerage companies, these will
attract the highest Ks at the 'expense' of the smaller ones, which could see
negative Ks - that is, rises below the rate of inflation.
The smaller companies argue they deserve a higher cost of capital because of
the greater financial risk of being smaller. They say they face the same
legal obligations on drinking-water standards as the bigger companies and
the same criminal sanctions if they do not comply.
In the end, it is likely that some companies will be forced to go to the
commission. Most analysts point to Northumbrian Water as a certainty.
Northumbrian, with most of its population based on the coast or estuaries,
is particularly vulnerable to the urban waste-water directive, which demands
greater treatment of organic sewage previously simply filtered and dumped
offshore.
Northumbrian could face almost doubled capital expenditure of up to Pounds
200m a year during the next five years as a result. Yet it is unlikely to
achieve anywhere near the K of seven it was given in the first price review.
Most speculate that at least two other companies could end up at the
commission. South West Water and Southern, like Northumbrian, are heavily
exposed to the high costs of legislation on coastal clean-ups.
Any more approaches to the commission could seriously undermine Mr Byatt's
findings.
It is a balancing act. 'If everybody goes then Byatt will be seen to have
failed,' said one director. 'If nobody goes then he will be attacked for
being too generous.'
</TEXT>
