<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / Date set for award of lottery licence
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The winner of the UK's National Lottery licence to run an operation that
will probably be the world's largest single lottery will be announced at
10am on Wednesday.
At 9.50am seven of the eight applicants will receive a fax informing them
that their bid has been unsuccessful. The eighth will get a press release
from Mr Peter Davis, director-general of the Office of the National Lottery,
due to be issued at 10am to the media and the Stock Exchange.
Mr Davis will then hold a press conference at the Institution of Civil
Engineers in Great George Street, Westminster.
At stake is the right to run a lottery that could be launched before the end
of this year and which many specialists believe could have revenues of
between Pounds 3bn and Pounds 4bn a year.
It is not inconceivable that as much as Pounds 1bn a year could be raised
for five 'good causes' - the arts, charities, a millennium fund, the
national heritage and sport.
Mr Davis is the only person who knows the outcome of the highly complex
bidding process and has been in purdah for the past few months. The fact
that he alone has had access to all information on the bids has made the
lottery decision leak-proof so far.
However, two groups have emerged as firm favourites through a mixture of
hunch, judgment and gossip: Camelot, a consortium including Cadbury
Schweppes, De La Rue and G-Tech; and Lotco, Rank Organisation's in-house
bid.
The UK Lottery Foundation - a bid put together by Mr Richard Branson and
Lord Young, the former trade and industry secretary - has emerged as the
bookmakers' favourite. But specialists are not so confident of its chances.
In the absence of hard information, few are prepared to rule out completely
bids from Games For Good Causes, which groups Ladbroke and MAI; The Great
British Lottery Company (Granada and Carlton Communications), or the
Rothschild Tattersalls Lottery Consortium.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P7999 Amusement and Recreation, NEC.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>TECH  Patents &amp; Licences.
</TP>
