<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / Sky steps up war against pirates
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
British Sky Broadcasting, the satellite television company which runs Sky
Television, has switched to a new subscription card in an attempt to beat
the growing threat from pirates selling unauthorised cards.
The cards are used by subscribers to decode the satellite broadcaster's
signals, which are scrambled for transmission. The cards were switched on
Wednesday.
For several weeks, in a multi-million-pound exercise, the satellite
broadcaster has been distributing new cards to the 3.3m homes that pay for
at least one of the its scrambled subscription services.
Sky said yesterday that the new cards would 'put all existing pirates out of
action'.
There has been evidence of a growing number of pirate cards becoming
available in the UK, many manufactured in Germany.
A year's subscription to all BSkyB's services costs Pounds 240 but some of
the pirate cards have been offered for as little as Pounds 40.
Some pirates have promised customers that for a small additional fee they
will send updated cards every time a signal or card software change is made
by BSkyB - a consortium in which Pearson, owner of the Financial Times, has
a significant stake.
One observer said that the pirates were already trying to make replicas of
the new card.
An indication of the potential scale of the problem came recently when a
German computer student grew frustrated that he could not subscribe to Sky
to watch Star Trek.
He set out on an international computer bulletin board - potentially
available to thousands of computer enthusiasts - details of how to break the
old Sky code by linking up a PC to a television set.
The student wrote: 'I don't want to cause any harm to Sky and I even asked
them for a regular subscription some time ago, but they refused to sell one
to Germany. So they have to live with the consequences of attracting the
interest of high-tech freaks to the technical details of their access
system.'
</TEXT>
