<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / Joker in the pack for Labour's contest / A look at the
impact union members not belonging to the party will have on the vote for
John Smith's successor - Leadership Contest
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
None of the postal workers questioned at London's Mount Pleasant sorting
office yesterday knew it, but they are about to have the chance of electing
the next leader of the Labour party. Their union - the Union of
Communication Workers - is affiliated to Labour and its members who pay the
political levy form part of the affiliated organisation section of the
electoral college that contains a third of the votes.
Only a few of the Mount Pleasant workers said they might vote if they
received a ballot paper from the union. Most were indifferent to the
suggestion. 'I doubt if one in 10 here will vote,' said one worker.
Another said he would vote but was not interested in actually joining the
Labour party. 'I like the idea of voting for the leader but I don't want to
get involved in party politics.' He added: 'I will back John Prescott. He's
a strong character. The Tories would blow Tony Blair away.'
It has been estimated there are up to 4.5m levy-payers in the 30 trade
unions affiliated to Labour who will be eligible to vote in the leadership
election. The overwhelming majority are manual workers. But private opinion
surveys carried out inside the unions suggest that while they may be
instinctively Labour supporters and even prepared to give money to the
party, they do not want to get involved in party activities.
'Our levy-payers are ordinary, decent people who think party political work
is done by eccentrics, extremists and the lonely,' said one union official.
Initially John Smith was sceptical as to whether it made sense to have such
a large input of votes into the leadership election, almost entirely from
people who did not belong to the Labour party.
But Mr John Edmonds, leader of the GMB general union, convinced him last
year that it would provide Labour with a splendid opportunity to mobilise
sympathisers to actually join the party.
'Our election would be like a US Democratic party primary,' enthused the
converted Mr Smith.
The logistics of the levy-payers' vote have not yet been finalised but union
leaders estimate it could cost them as much as Pounds 1.35m. The unions are
already holding postal ballots of their entire memberships this year as
required by law to secure agreement for their political funds. This has to
be kept as a separate exercise, not the least because having a political
fund is not the same as being affiliated to the Labour party. With 21 unions
not affiliated to Labour, about 1m political-fund contributors will not be
involved in the leadership election.
Labour's head office wants next Wednesday's National Executive Committee
meeting to endorse guidelines for the leadership contest which encourage
trade unions to delegate administration of the election to Unity Trust
Bank's electoral services to ensure efficiency and minimise costs.
The 30 unions involved will send out ballot papers (mostly by post, although
workplace ballots are acceptable) to their levy-payers whose names and
addresses they have at head office. Each will receive two papers.
The first will ask whether he or she is a Labour party sympathiser. If the
answer is yes, they can then fill in the second ballot paper on who they
want to elect as party leader in order of preference. The completed ballot
papers would then be returned to Unity Trust and a computer will be
programmed to distribute them under the single transferable vote principle.
One union official said: 'This is not going to be an election dominated by
the trade union barons but by the media barons. The levy-payers are going to
be swayed by what they read in the Daily Mirror or The Sun or what they see
on television, not what John Edmonds or Bill Morris (TGWU general secretary)
suggests they should do.'
Some unions are hopeful that 25 per cent to 30 per cent of levy-payers will
vote, drawing confidence from the political fund ballots. Privately many
union activists say they want either Mr Prescott or Mr Gordon Brown as
leader but they admit the outcome will be uncertain under the levy-paying
vote.
One thing is certain. The election is going to cost the trade unions a great
deal of money without much of an obvious dividend.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P8651 Political Organizations.
    P8631 Labor Organizations.
</IN>
