<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / World Trade News: Aviation talks resume despite US
opposition
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANCES WILLIAMS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GENEVA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Talks under the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade about a new
multilateral trade accord, governing civil aircraft, were resumed yesterday
despite opposition from the US and Canada.
Deep divisions remain between the US, which wants to limit the scope of any
new aircraft agreement, and the European Union, which is pressing for a
wide-ranging accord to discipline state supports.
The talks, originally designed to extend the 1992 bilateral deal between the
US and EU on state subsidies to the European Airbus, broke down last
December.
Just before the end of the Uruguay Round of global trade negotiations, the
US rejected a chairman's draft accepted by the other 20 or so governments
taking part in the aircraft talks.
The draft agreement, a revision of Gatt's existing civil aircraft code,
would have tightened controls on subsidies for all types of civil aircraft
and components, including subsidies via space and military contracts of the
type used by Washington. This has met vigorous opposition from the US
industry, especially engine manufacturers.
It was agreed in December that talks would resume, with a view to conclude
an accord by the end of this year. However, the US now argues that changes
should be confined to uncontentious amendments needed to bring the Gatt code
into line with other Uruguay Round agreements, such as that on dispute
settlement.
US officials said yesterday that the subsidies accord agreed to in the
Uruguay Round, and due to take effect next year, should be allowed to
operate before any decision to make specific subsidy provisions in the civil
aircraft code.
The EU argues that the subsidies agreement is inadequate and wants specific
provisions in the aircraft code, partly to put stricter controls on US
support for aircraft development, and partly to discipline aid by other
governments to their aircraft industries.
</TEXT>
<XX>
