<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / World Trade News: UK minister prepares Cuba mission
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEPHEN FIDLER, Latin America Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The first visit by a British government minister to Cuba since at least the
1970s is being planned for later this year, reflecting a warming of
relations between the UK and the government of President Fidel Castro.
The visit by Mr Patrick McLoughlin, parliamentary under-secretary of state
for trade and technology, is likely to go ahead in September.
It is a reflection of growing interest among British companies over
investment prospects in Cuba, a small market but one from which US companies
are excluded by the US embargo. It also indicates a Foreign Office
perception that the Castro government is not about to collapse, despite the
deep economic problems which the country has faced since the fall of the
Soviet Union.
A group of deputies from Cuba's National Assembly is also to visit the UK
next week. They are led by Mr Ricardo Alarcon, president of the assembly and
often described as Mr Castro's deputy, who will meet foreign office minister
David Heathcoat-Amory.
Mr McLoughlin, who may be accompanied by British businessmen, will aim, says
the Department of Trade and Industry, 'to develop trade and investment
opportunities' and may also sign an investment promotion and protection
agreement currently under negotiation. The US government has been informed
of the visit.
A number of unofficial British trade missions have already visited Cuba
under the auspices of the Caribbean Trade Advisory Group. Mr David Jessop,
Caritag director, said that 'a number of agreements are in the last stages
of negotiation' between British companies and the Cuban government.
He declined to be specific, although at least one investment ran into tens
of millions of pounds sterling. Some companies were trying to incorporate
debt owed to them by Cuba into their agreements, and there was a possibility
of debt-equity swaps being used.
</TEXT>
