<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / World Trade News: JM in Japanese joint venture
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KENNETH GOODING, mining correspondent
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Johnson Matthey, the UK-based precious metals technology group, has tackled
two key elements of its corporate strategy in a deal with Mitsubishi Kasei,
the Japanese chemical company, writes Kenneth Gooding, mining correspondent,
in London.
They are to set up a joint venture to supply sputtering targets to the
Japanese semiconductor industry.
Mr David Davies, JM's chairman, said yesterday the deal would enable JM
immediately to have profitable operations in Japan while at the same time
expanding its Electronic Materials business to become worldwide market
leader in sputtering targets.
Sputtering targets are made of very high purity metal - aluminium or
titanium - and used to deposit a thin film on semiconductor chips and
computer processors. The market is conservatively forecast by JM to grow
from Dollars 170m in 1992 to Dollars 200m by 1995 because the semiconductors
are used in the fast-growing personal computer and portable telephone
markets.
The partners will merge their existing Japanese operations into the new
joint company, Ryoka Matthey, which will continue to manufacture at a plant
in Noetsu. Ryoka Matthey is expected to employ 50, have sales of Dollars 18m
and net assets of about Dollars 15m.
</TEXT>
