FT  20 MAY 94 / World Trade News: Slow progress in Taiwan Gatt talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANCES WILLIAMS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GENEVA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Negotiations on Taiwan's application to join the General Agreement on
Tariffs and Trade are making slower progress than expected, virtually ruling
out the possibility of membership by the end of the year, writes Frances
Williams in Geneva. Talks in Geneva, which ended yesterday, failed to start
drafting detailed entry terms. No date has been set for the next meeting.
Taiwan's Gatt application was accepted in September 1992 on the
understanding that China would join first (even if only just before).
However, negotiations with China are also proceeding at a more sedate pace
than the Beijing government would like.
Mr Peter Sutherland, Gatt's director general, on a visit to Beijing last
week, said it would be 'extremely difficult' for China to join Gatt this
year. Negotiations are due to resume next month, after the decision by the
US on the renewal of China's Most Favoured Nation trading status.
