<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / World Trade News: Ex-colony preferences set to be wound down
 -A review of the aid and trade treaty between the EU and African, Caribbean
and Pacific countries
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CANUTE JAMES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
As ministers from European Union governments and the African, Caribbean and
Pacific (ACP) group meet in Swaziland today to review the Lome Convention,
they could be writing the first words of its epitaph. There is tacit
agreement on both sides that the trade and aid treaty, in its present form,
will be the last of its kind.
There is disagreement, however, on the nature and extent of changes to the
treaty, which expires at the end of the decade.
The Lome Convention was once hailed as a model for trade treaties: it was
negotiated, rather than being imposed by one side; and it was generous in
the opportunities it offered the ACP countries.
Its mid-term review comes at a time of increasing globalisation of world
trade. The EU says it wants changes to the treaty that fit in with the
redefined principles and patterns of commerce set out in the Uruguay Round
of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade. But ACP countries believe the
Lome Convention is not yet anachronistic and that some of the proposed
amendments are too radical.
ACP officials admit that for many of their economies, disengaging from Lome
in its present form would be painful. With the deregulation of international
trade, and with changes in the patterns of private investment flows and
official aid, guaranteed markets for commodity exports and development
finance through the treaty are invaluable.
While most agree that the crutch offered by preferences will go, they differ
on the timing. Economies are weaned on trade preferences ostensibly to
enable them to stand on their own. But senior officials at the European
Commission say the longer preferences are in place the less able recipients
are to stand unaided. And they argue that some countries have done better
without preferential treatment at all.
The EU wants to move away from considerations of special relationships based
on colonial ties to a less emotional foundation for trade. The 'real needs'
of developing countries are more important than their history, the EU
argues. Most ACP governments agree, but they do not fully accept the EU's
interpretation of the measures needed to meet those needs.
The EU also wants changes in the management of its development funds to
reduce delay, waste and corruption. It is seeking changes in the
administration of aid to support human rights, 'good governance' and
democracy, as reflected in more open government and increased
accountability. ACP states say they are in favour of all this, but they
question the EU's motive in introducing conditions which, they say, the
Union does not demand in its relations with other states.
There is concern in the ACP over what the EU would use as the final arbiter
and how these principles can be coherently defined when dealing with varying
political systems and cultures. ACP states want joint determination to avoid
the danger of discriminating against some countries.
Ministers will also argue over whether Brussels or the recipient states
should have greater control over the management of aid funds. EU officials
argue that countries should not expect continuing access to funds they fail
to take up, and that disbursements should be denied if it believes money has
been misspent.
ACP states say in response that recipient governments do not always have
complete control over the rate of spending and that the flow of funds often
depends on tortuous decision-making in Brussels. They add that changes to
control over aid could undermine relations between ACP states by provoking
arguments over limited resources.
ACP officials fear that some of what they consider the more pressing issues,
such as trade in sugar and bananas and in services, may get pushed into the
background.
</TEXT>
<XX>
