<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / Mexican opposition advances
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAMIAN FRASER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MEXICO CITY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mexico's centre-right opposition has been lifted greatly by the television
debate last week between the country's main presidential candidates and is
now leading the governing party in some opinion polls. The leftist
opposition has been relegated to third.
Mori of Mexico gives Mr Diego Fernandez de Cevallos of the National Action
Party (PAN) 25 per cent support, against 20 per cent for Mr Ernesto Zedillo
of the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI), with 41 per cent
undecided.
An internal poll for the PRI gives Mr Fernandez de Cevallos 40 per cent and
Mr Zedillo 39 per cent. Mr Cuauhtemoc Cardenas of the leftist Party of
Democratic Revolution (PRD) trailed with 12-13 per cent.
PRI officials expect the popularity of Mr Fernandez de Cevallos to decline
as the impact of the debate fades. They argue that the polls are biased in
his favour because they do not include the rural areas where his party has
little support. Even so, the PAN surge is causing anxiety in the governing
party and contributing to deep divisions in the PRD.
Mr Fernandez de Cevallos is less known than Mr Cardenas but the former's
party offers social conservatism and pro-business policies which may be more
palatable to many voters than the left-of-centre platform of Mr Cardenas,
and may make the PAN candidate a more credible alternative to the PRI. One
PRI official said: 'We now have to concentrate on winning the election, not
just on obtaining legitimacy for the result.'
Government officials say they much prefer to have Mr Fernandez de Cevallos,
rather than Mr Cardenas, as the principal opposition in the August
presidential election, in the belief this could make the post-electoral
situation more stable.
If Mr Cardenas does come third, officials reckon his capacity to organise
allegations of electoral fraud will be much reduced.
The PRI's aura of invincibility has been damaged by the televised debate, in
which Mr Fernandez de Cevallos was judged the clear winner. Mr Zedillo has
been criticised for failing to defend the policies of President Carlos
Salinas, for not mentioning his own party, and for mean-spiritedness during
much of his time on air.
Members of the PRD are increasingly frustrated at Mr Cardenas's lacklustre
campaign, encapsulated by his poor performance in the television debate.
Yesterday, the party leaders held an emergency meeting to resolve
differences between factions and refocus the campaign, according to press
reports.
</TEXT>
