<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / Bentsen argues for caution in drive to police derivatives
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Lloyd Bentsen, the US Treasury secretary, yesterday warned the US
Congress against 'interfering in markets in too heavy handed a way' in its
efforts to regulate more closely the risks posed by trading in financial
derivatives.
The warning came as congressional committees began to chew over the findings
of a report by the General Accounting Office, Congress's audit agency, which
warned of gaps in the supervision of derivatives dealing, especially by
securities business affiliates and insurance companies.
Mr Edward Markey, chairman of the House of Representatives subcommittee on
telecommunications and finance, said the GAO report had 'identified some
serious gaps in the current legal and regulatory structure relating to
derivatives,' and argued that regulatory and legislative reforms were needed
'to successfully avert the potential for a future derivatives Dunkirk.'
In the light of the findings, he said, 'I cannot agree with those who would
argue that the thousand points of light of industry volunteerism and a few
incremental changes by regulators can effectively address the risks posed by
exotic derivatives.'
Mr Henry Gonzalez, House banking committee chairman, said he saw 'eye-to-eye
with the GAO report on the need for increased disclosure, for improved
supervision and for stronger international co-operation on derivatives
regulation and supervision'
Mr Gonzalez said he planned soon to introduce derivatives legislation in
co-operation with Congressman Jim Leach, his Republican counterpart.
Republican members of Mr Markey's subcommittee yesterday took immediate aim
at some of the proposals in the GAO report, warning they ran the risk of
meddling in normal company decisions that were no business of government.
'In the process of protecting stockholders from the consequences of bad
business decisions in derivatives, we need to make sure that we don't drive
companies to foreign derivatives markets, said Congressman Dennis Hastert of
Illinois.
Even some Democrats feared they might end up mollycoddling multinational
companies well able to handle the complexities of derivatives.
</TEXT>
