campaign, encapsulated by his poor performance in the television debate.
Yesterday, the party leaders held an emergency meeting to resolve
differences between factions and refocus the campaign, according to press
reports.
Many of Mr Cardenas's problems seem of his own making. Last weekend he met
Sub-comandante Marcos, the rebel leader in the southern state of Chiapas,
and seemed to play into the hands of those who attack him for extremism. The
meeting turned into a fiasco as Marcos, rather than offer his support for Mr
Cardenas, criticised him for his failings.
The meeting conflicted with Mr Cardenas's recent move to the political
centre. Some government officials are worried that he may move back to the
left, in an effort to shore up support from the party faithful, if his
popularity ebbs away. A newly radicalised Mr Cardenas, even in third place,
could make the electoral process more tense.
</TEXT>
