<DATE>940520
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / Drugs liberalisation attacked: Colombian court decision
leads to defiance on streets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SARITA KENDALL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BOGOTA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The impact of the Colombian Supreme Court decision to decriminalise the
personal use of small amounts of drugs is already evident on the streets of
the country's capital, Bogota.
Social workers dealing with children and young prostitutes say drug
consumption has climbed since the first announcement of de-criminalisation
two weeks ago. More teenagers are trying out cocaine base (a low-grade form
of the drug), thinking: 'If it's legal it can't be bad for us'.
Critics of the court decision say this is evidence that such
decriminalisation opens the door to a massive increase in marijuana and
cocaine consumption, in a country where these drugs are cheap and readily
available.
A recent government survey found there were more than 500,000 regular drug
abusers among Colombia's 30m people, including 6,000 heroin addicts. Drug
abuse is an important factor in Colombian urban violence. The country has
highest murder rate in the world.
The court this week issued a lengthy statement in support of its decision,
but it has failed to still the controversy.
A majority of the justices decided it was unconstitutional to violate a
person's freedom to decide whether to use drugs. However, the court left
room for congressional legislation to limit drug use in schools and other
public places, and said that education, not repression, is the way to combat
consumption.
Four of the nine justices have stated they deplore the majority's ruling,
describing it as ingenuous and anachronistic, based on 19th century
liberalism, and doing 'incalculable harm to Colombian society.' The
government, presidential candidates (the election's first round is due on
May 29), church, business and education leaders have condemned the
decriminalisation.
President Cesar Gaviria said this week he would issue a decree to ban the
use of drugs in public places, as the first step to overturn the ruling. He
also announced moves towards a plebiscite to revoke the ruling and return
any kind of drug use to illegality. Opinion polls have all shown a large
majority for penalties against possession and consumption.
Critics of the court decision also see it as undermining the police and
other authorities fighting drug production and trafficking. Marijuana users
in the centre of Bogota are now taunting police by blowing smoke in their
faces.
By legalising the consumption part of the drug business, the critics
believe, the court is in danger of giving the illusion of legitimacy to
production. There may now be greater pressure in Colombia to realise a
proposal previously aired by Mr Gustavo de Greiff, the attorney-general, to
legalise the whole trade.
The decriminalisation will also damage Colombia's image abroad, even though
the US and other foreign governments recognise that the court's decision
does not reflect the Gaviria administration's stand against drugs. The US
has already suspended exchanges of evidence with the Colombian authorities
on the grounds that Mr de Greiff was too ready to reach plea-bargains with
drug traffickers.
</TEXT>
