<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / Wounded Maoists remain armed and dangerous: The Huallaga
valley, where the Peruvian armed forces are mounting an assault on Shining
Path guerrillas
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SALLY BOWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Fourteen years since the left-wing Shining Path (Sendero Luminoso) movement
erupted from clandestine political agitation into overt military action in
Peru, army chiefs and the pro-government press claim that the 'final
offensive' against the Maoists is under way.
The principal 'battle zone' is deep in the semi-tropical jungle, on the left
bank of the Huallaga river, 300 miles north-east of the capital and long
notorious as being near where most of Peru's coca leaf, the raw material for
cocaine, is grown.
Reports of hundreds of troops mobilised, of helicopter attacks against the
civilian population and of fleeing terrorists have dominated Peru's
newspapers for the past three weeks. Human rights organisations, meanwhile,
have presented testimony alleging rape, torture and summary execution of
civilians by government troops. Visits to the zone by journalists and the
Congressional commission forhuman rights have failed to clarify the picture.
In this inaccessible and lawless area, the truth is hard to discover. But
several facts do emerge: first, the military operation involves no more than
a couple of hundred soldiers, a similar number of guerrillas and a maximum
of two elderly helicopters; second, the combat area is sparsely populated,
making large-scale air attack impossible; third, there have been innocent
victims.
This is a low-technology conflict, largely entrusted to 16- and 17 year-old
recruits who must foot-slog through mud and dense undergrowth for perhaps a
week before encountering the enemy. In this terrain, which they have
controlled for a decade, Sendero guerrillas have the upper hand. Jungle
paths are mined and ambushes easily laid. The wounded must usually be
carried out on stretchers.
The left bank of the Huallaga is now one of the last real bastions for
Sendero, severely weakened since the capture in September 1992 of Abimael
Guzman, the movment's founder and leader, and the subsequent arrest of most
of its known, high-ranking leaders.
Along the Huallaga, Sendero has sustained a long and profitable co-operation
with drug traffickers and coca-growers, many of them migrants from the
impoverished Andean highlands.
Sendero's war chest, swollen with proceeds of protection rackets and landing
charges for drug traffickers' flights from small airstrips, has allowed the
guerrillas to acquire relatively sophisticated arms, including
rocket-propelled grenades and Soviet-made machine-guns.
Now, for the first time, the Peruvian government is making an attempt to
clear the area. Prior to operations, a massive propaganda campaign - via
leaflets dropped by helicopter, radio and television broadcasts - called on
subversives and sympathisers to 'repent'.
Many residents of the small, Sendero-controlled towns on the right bank of
the river saw the security forces regaining the upper hand and complied.
Entire villages have turned themselves in and been given a clean bill of
health by the army.
Much of this repentance, of course, is false. 'Sendero would come around
sometimes and demand food,' said one tearful local shopkeeper. 'You have to
help them or they kill you. But why should I have to repent for that?'
Repentance, and the safe-conduct pass which comes with it, helps the
security forces to distinguish friend from foe. But many locals say they are
'friends' from necessity, complaining meanwhile of widespread army abuses,
including petty theft, rape and other physical maltreatment.
Arrepentidos (those who have repented) with more clout get lenient treatment
in return for surrendering weapons and informing on former comrades-in-arms.
Some, though, like 17-year-old Comrade America - now a guide for the army at
Tingo Mara - seem genuinely disillusioned: 'It's an awful life with Sendero
 -you sleep in the undergrowth and eat like an animal. If you lapse from
party discipline three times, they kill you. They pull out your tongue with
pliers.'
Battles in the backlands of Peru against similar, well-established pockets
of resistance may be expected for some time.
At the national level, the government of President Alberto Fujimori can
point to numerous successes in counter-subversion. Statistics show that
political violence continues to decline. This year so far, both the number
of guerrilla attacks and the death toll have dropped to about a third of
last year's already reduced levels. Another indicator of enhanced security
is the number of foreign miners and geologists moving freely throughout
remote Andean areas considered no-go zones 18 months ago.
Some of this success is due to the creation of rondas, armed community
self-defence groups supported by, and sometimes directly under the control
of, the army.
The capture of Guzman, however, has not resulted in the hoped-for final
capitulation of Sendero. He has said he is ready to 'negotiate'; Mr Fujimori
has insisted on full surrender first.
Guzman clearly wields power over other imprisoned party leaders but no
longer controls those still at large. Recent Sendero documents show him
still revered as an ideologue but, as several sources underline, 'an
imprisoned Maoist is a dead Maoist'.
The mantle of logistical command has fallen to Oscar Ramrez Durand, known as
Comrade Feliciano. His faction, now widely called Red Sendero, seems
incapable of large-scale, co-ordinated action, but remains dangerous. (Black
Sendero is what they call the members in jail.)
The government and the armed forces stick to what Mr Fujimori calls 'the
radical change in counter-subversive strategy - winning over the
population'. According to the president, 'the war is not yet over (but) the
situation is under control'.
</TEXT>
<XX>
