<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / Top congressman hunts for way out of scandal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Lawyers for congressman Dan Rostenkowski were reported yesterday to be
trying to negotiate a legal bargain under which the powerful chairman of the
House ways and means committee might plead guilty to misdemeanour offences
relating to the House post office scandal unearthed in 1991.
Mr Robert Bennett, the congressman's lawyer who is also representing
President Bill Clinton in the civil sexual harassment suit brought by Ms
Paula Jones, declined to comment yesterday. So did Ms Janet Reno, the
attorney general.
The outcome of the legal bargaining could have a sizeable impact on the fate
of healthcare reform in Congress. Mr Rostenkowski's committee is an
important drafting panel and the chairman is committed to bringing a bill to
the floor of the House.
Were felony charges to be brought, Mr Rostenkowski would be forced, under
the rules of the House Democratic party caucus, to step aside as chairman
until the case is resolved. A misdemeanour indictment involves no such
automatic removal, although there would undoubtedly be calls for him to
resign his post.
Next in seniority on ways and means is congressman Sam Gibbons of Florida,
who believes in universal health insurance coverage, but along the lines of
the Canadian 'single payer' system which has been explicitly rejected by the
Clinton administration. He also has nothing like Mr Rostenkowski's legendary
powers of political persuasion.
At a session of the 39-member committee on Wednesday, Mr Rostenkowski
described his mission in typically blunt terms. 'I will do whatever I need
to to get at least 20 votes on this committee' - the minimum number needed
for a bill to reach the floor of the House.
Last month, Mr Eric Holder, the federal attorney in Washington, sent to the
justice department a draft indictment of Mr Rostenkowski.
Details of the proposed indictment have never been made public. But last
year Mr Robert Rota, the former House postmaster, pleaded guilty to
misdemeanour embezzlement charges and implicated Mr Rostenkowski in the
scheme to disguise theft by post office cashiers as payments for the
purchases of stamps by the congressman.
Since then, Mr Rosentowski's offices and campaign accounts in Washington and
his Chicago district have also been investigated. He has continued to insist
on his innocence of all charges.
</TEXT>
