<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / Business 'pulls aid strings'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANCES WILLIAMS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GENEVA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Business interests are increasingly shaping the content of official aid
programmes to the detriment of the poor, according to a report by aid
agencies from 22 donor nations.
The practice of tying aid to the purchase of goods and services in donor
countries is growing, obliging developing countries to pay more than
necessary for their supplies, it says. Tied aid also results in purchases of
inappropriate goods suited to the donor rather than the recipient and holds
back development of Third World industries debarred from competing for
aid-funded projects.
Tied aid has been running at about Dollars 15bn in each of the past five
years, rising to nearly Dollars 18bn in 1991, the report claims. It
estimates developing countries are paying on average 15 per cent more than
necessary for tied aid supplies, amounting to a subsidy to exporters in
donor nations of more than Dollars 2bn a year. This compares with total
development assistance by OECD countries of Dollars 60bn in 1992.
Governments tend to favour projects that serve the interests of their own
industries because they are visible, easy to administer and relatively quick
to implement. Projects designed to reduce poverty often centre on slowly
building up local capabilities, using local resources rather than importing
goods, services and know-how from outside.
The growing use of aid to promote enterprise and investment in developing
countries also appears to be driven more by the desire to give donor country
industries a toe hold in developing markets.
More broadly the rich industrial nations are sharply reducing development
assistance. Only about 10 per cent of aid goes directly on reducing poverty.
The reality of aid 1994; Actionaid, 3 Church Street, Frome, Somerset BA11
1PW, England, Tel 44373473128, Pounds 10.
</TEXT>
