<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / North Korea 'violating' nuclear pact
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK BLUM and MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS, UN correspondent
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   VIENNA, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The International Atomic Energy Agency last night called on North Korea
immediately to stop removing spent fuel rods from a reactor at its Yongbyon
nuclear complex, condemning its action as a 'serious violation' of an
agreement on nuclear safeguards.
The IAEA said it was reporting the violation to its board of governors and
to the United Nations Security Council.
An agency inspection team, currently in North Korea, provided the first
official confirmation that the North Koreans had started removing spent fuel
rods from the five-megawatt reactor in defiance of the IAEA. The US and the
IAEA have voiced fears that North Korea may extract plutonium from the spent
fuel to produce a nuclear bomb.
Washington has warned that extensive removal of the fuel rods would force it
to ask the UN to apply economic sanctions against North Korea. Earlier
yesterday President Clinton said it would be 'an error for North Korea to
continue to thwart these inspections ..'
On Wednesday Mr William Perry, US defence secretary, said the US would
increase the already high 'readiness level' of its troops in South Korea if
it proved necessary to seek sanctions against North Korea.
Pyongyang informed the IAEA it had started to refuel the reactor on May 12 -
an operation which requires replacing old fuel rods - in spite of earlier
requests by the agency not to undertake discharging the fuel without
enabling agency inspectors to take appropriate safeguards measures.
'As of today, it still seems possible to implement the required safeguards
measures,' the agency said. But to continue the discharge operation without
these measures, would result in 'irreparable loss of the agency's ability to
verify whether all nuclear material subject to safeguards in (North Korea)
is in fact under safeguards and that no such material has been diverted,' it
said.
Michael Littlejohns, UN correspondent, adds from New York: The controversy
presents difficult diplomatic problems for the UN Security Council.
While the US has threatened tough action against North Korea, any measures
proposed through the UN could be blocked by China, which has the right of
veto as a permanent member of the Security Council. Japan, too, is reluctant
to force the issue to a confrontation.
</TEXT>
