<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / Losses in Philippines securities scandal put at Dollars 23m:
Central bank has moved to allay public alarm
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOSE GALANG
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MANILA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Losses incurred by Philippine financial institutions from investments in
government securities placed through a collapsed investment company were
officially estimated yesterday at 938m pesos (Pounds 23m).
The country's monetary authorities announced the figure to allay fears of
severe damage from a scandal surrounding Bancapital Development Corporation,
which was little known in Manila's financial community until it closed last
month having failed to deliver large amounts of Treasury bills purchased by
banks and other financial institutions.
The affair became public this week following the death of an executive of
Bank of Commerce, a medium-sized commercial bank which is among those which
have suffered losses.
Bancapital, an unlicensed trader in the secondary market for government
securities, had lured investors with an offer of yields of up to 3
percentage points above market rates.
A special meeting yesterday of the monetary board, the policy-setting body
of Bangko Sentral, the central bank, decided to pursue investigations on
possible violations of bank internal controls in the acquisition of Treasury
bills.
The board said the estimated losses compared with total resources of 1,290bn
pesos held by banks and non-banks with quasi-banking functions at the end of
1993. The banking system, the board said, 'is stable and. . . . there is no
reason (for the public) to panic'.
A wave of deposit withdrawals was reported to have hit Bank of Commerce on
Wednesday, forcing it to seek emergency loans of up to 1bn pesos. Yesterday
the tension had apparently eased and no other banks reported unusual
activity.
Officials of Bankers' Association of the Philippines, which groups the
domestic private commercial banks, said Bancapital had been buying
securities in the secondary market and selling them 'more than once' to
other investors. Actual deliveries of the securities were not made and
instead 'custodial receipts' were given to investors.
Recent fluctuations in money market rates triggered the company's troubles,
according to bankers, who were surprised, however, at the investments made
by bigger financial institutions in Bancapital. Banks can participate in
weekly auctions of Treasury bills conducted by the central bank. The
Philippines' trade deficit was Dollars 1.13bn in the first two months of the
year, up by 54 per cent over the same period of 1993, according to the
central bank.
Exports rose 14 per cent to Dollars 1.87bn, and imports were up 26 per cent
to Dollars 2.99bn.
