<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / Ray of light on the road to Damascus / Review of US
torch-bearing efforts between Israel and Syria
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARK NICHOLSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
More than two and a half years after the Madrid conference began the present
Middle East process, Israel and Syria have finally reached a mutually
acceptable way of negotiating their track of a regional peace through the
Americans and, in particular, Mr Warren Christopher, the US secretary of
state.
Mr Christopher said before leaving the region on Wednesday that he would be
back if both sides felt it would be useful, and repeated the cautious
leitmotiv of his second shuttle within a fortnight, that talks were at an
'early stage'.
Few doubt he will be back within weeks or that what he is directing is the
start of finely detailed negotiation which both sides appear determined
should become a final agreement.
There remain, as the state-owned Syria Times emphasised yesterday, 'wide and
big' gaps between Israel which wants Syria to pledge a 'full peace' before
it will commit itself to withdrawing from the Golan Heights, and Syria,
which will do so only after an Israeli promise to pull its troops out from
'every inch' of the land it occupied in the 1967 Arab-Israeli war. Mr
Christopher's task is to produce the clever piece of diplomatic engineering
which will resolve this chicken-and-egg situation that has been at the heart
of the impasse from the outset.
The crude architecture of a deal has long been apparent. It will include
statements which each can interpret to their satisfaction: something from
Israel which Mr Hafez al-Assad, the Syrian president, can trumpet as a
commitment that Israel will return all of the Golan to Syrian sovreignty;
something from Syria which Mr Yitzhak Rabin, the Israeli prime minister, can
sell as the start of full diplomatic and economic relations.
Any withdrawal from the Golan would be phased - a concession Syria hinted it
is prepared to offer. Israel has offered an eight-year timetable, Syria
apparently wants three years at most. Israeli settlements on the Golan will
be dismantled, something Mr Rabin has already publicly addressed.
There will be a host of mutual security arrangements, including a US
monitoring force on the Golan to which Washington has in principle agreed.
US officers will likely staff early warning stations on the Golan. Both
sides are expected to create demilitarised zones either side of the Golan in
their own territory.
All this, of course, needs to be nailed down. But detailed work appears
already under way. Diplomats in Damascus say position papers exchanged by
the two sides this week already cover 'all the issues, addressed in a minute
manner.' It also appears that, unlike the Israel-PLO or Israel-Jordan talks,
there is no intention first to announce a 'declaration of principles' before
negotiating the final deal.
Syria, in particular, is deeply averse to discussing anything but a
finely-argued agreement, having watched with distaste the PLO's problems in
turning its vague declaration into an implementable agreement.
This is Mr Christopher's chief achievement. His tight-lipped shuttling
appears to have created a negotiating framework acceptable to both sides.
Israel has long sought high-level, secret talks with Syria, something Syria
has resisted because of distrustful fear of negotiating alone with the
Israelis. Mr Christopher's intervention thus reassures the Syrians that the
US will act as a guarantor, and perhaps arbiter, in any agreement.
His radio silence satisfies Israel's desire for secrecy. The fact he is
effectively conducting talks directly between Mr Assad and Mr Rabin answers
the call for high level negotiations.
Moreover, now that the Palestinians have gone it alone with Israel in
reaching their Gaza-Jericho deal, Mr Assad no longer feels he need tie
progress on his own negotiating track to progress in others - previously a
totem of his desire to be seen the Arab champion of a 'comprehensive' peace.
Indeed now, perversely, Mr Assad has some stake in seeing the PLO deal
succeed - whatever his conviction of its flaws - since its failure might
threaten Mr Rabin's ability to secure a separate peace with Damascus.
Mr Christopher appears thus to have broken the stalemate into which
bilateral Israeli-Syrian talks had lodged during the Washington peace talks.
But given the desire to maintain secrecy, progress in the private exchanges
is now more likely to be discernible through public signals than in
revelations of the contents of further rounds of US-mediated talks.
Mr Assad has already offered several peaceable gestures, including the issue
of exit visas for Syrian Jews shortly before January's Geneva summit with
President Bill Clinton. He co-operated with a US investigation into the fate
of Israel soldiers missing in Lebanon, and recently allowed a delegation of
Israeli Arabs to visit Syria. Further signs might include permission for a
delegation of Jewish Israelis to visit, or Syria's agreement to participate
in multilateral talks on regional issues which also began in Madrid.
Most observers in Damascus believe both Mr Rabin and Mr Assad know what they
need to deliver the other to achieve peace, however canny they are being in
public. Mr Christopher's willingness to devote such time and resources to
the talks, meanwhile, appears the clearest gauge of each sides' resolve to
achieve progress.
All three participants have good reason to press ahead. Mr Rabin must know
that his best chance of reaching an cast-iron deal lies in forging it with
Syria's present leadership. Mr Assad also knows the political climate may
never be more propitious for a deal to return the Golan - perhaps his single
greatest political ambition. He is also keen to reap the political and
economic rewards which the US might bestow if peace is agreed - not least in
removing Syria from the list of state sponsors of terrorism and perhaps
encouraging economic assistance.
For the US, there is the knowledge that real peace in the Middle East cannot
be accomplished without Syria, with the associated belief that bringing
Damascus on side will help further in its 'containment' of Iran. More to the
immediate political point, however, for an administration bogged in such
mires as Haiti and Bosnia, a Syrian-Israeli peace would be a rare foreign
policy victory. Which is one of the best reasons to expect Mr Christopher's
team to book two floors at the Damascus Sheraton before June is out.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>ILZ  Israel, Middle East.
    SYZ  Syria, Middle East.
</CN>
