<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / Pretoria seeks to calm fears on spending
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATTI WALDMEIR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PRETORIA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
South Africa's government of national unity yesterday sought to play down
fears of a sharp rise in public spending on socio-economic development, with
top finance officials promising to maintain fiscal discipline and fight
inflation.
Mr Jay Naidoo, the minister charged with implementing the reconstruction and
development programme, said in Pretoria that the government was aiming to
maintain macroeconomic balance and reduce public debt while improving the
delivery of public goods and services.
He was reacting to estimates released this week showing that the
reconstruction programme will cost R80bn-R90bn (Pounds 14.6bn-Pounds 16.5bn)
over five years, more than double the R39bn cost which the African National
Congress put on the programme during campaigning for the all-race elections
which it won last month.
Mr Naidoo stressed that the programme had to be funded, at least in its
early stages, from savings within the current budget rather than through
'add-on' expenditure. While he insisted that an adequate amount would be
available this year to kick-start the programme and to show that 'we will
visibly be able to deliver something to our people', most of the money would
come from redirecting spending and improving government efficiency.
This commitment to fiscal discipline is expected to be reflected in the
government's first budget, to be submitted to parliament on June 22. It is
understood that the budget will not deviate fundamentally from a 'mock
budget' released in March which provides for a real cut in government
expenditure and a budget deficit of 6.4 per cent of gross domestic product,
just below last year's 6.8 per cent figure.
Expenditure of R124.8bn would be just over 8 per cent more than last year's
R115.2bn, well below the inflation rate of nearly 10 per cent. No increase
in the general level of taxation is foreseen, though there could be rises in
so-called sin taxes on tobacco and alcohol, a new capital transfer tax and
possible changes to value added taxes to exempt basic foodstuffs but raise
taxes on luxury items.
Mr Derek Keys, the former industrialist who was reappointed finance minister
last week, is expected to present the budget plans to the cabinet on Monday.
President Nelson Mandela will give some details of economic policy when he
delivers his state of the nation address to parliament the following day.
Mr Keys' economic team includes Mr Naidoo as minister without portfolio and
Mr Alec Erwin as deputy finance minister. While both are ANC members and
former trade unionists, the team appears unanimous in endorsing the need for
fiscal discipline.
However, independent economists question whether sufficient savings can be
made to fund the programme as planned. Officials give no details of where
savings will be found, though it is understood that spending on security
forces will be targeted. At the same time, however, there will be pressure
on government spending from the creation of nine new regional bureaucracies,
as well as demands for affirmative action within the public service coupled
with pre-election commitments not to sack white civil servants.
Government spending will also be slightly increased because of the extra
costs of the recent election, which officials put at under R1bn.
</TEXT>
