<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / Spain tightens bank fraud law
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TOM BURNS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MADRID
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Spanish parliament yesterday approved legislation giving the Bank of
Spain a degree of Bundesbank-style autonomy, along with amendments
establishing strict rules to prevent illicit enrichment by the bank's
officials. The move reflected the intense public debate over the central
bank prompted by tax evasions and fraud allegations linked to the disgraced
former governor Mr Mariano Rubio who was freed on bail yesterday after two
weeks in prison. The law, first drafted in 1992, lays down that investments
by senior bank employees must be independently administered and closely
supervised by the market regulator, the National Securities Market
Commission.
Mr Rubio is being investigated in connection with tax evasion and falsifying
public documents when he was central bank governor in the late 1980s. The
law gives the Bank of Spain the responsibility of setting monetary policy
and prohibits it from financing the treasury and other public institutions.
The government, in consultation with the Bank of Spain, nevertheless retains
control over exchange rate policy.
</TEXT>
