FT  20 MAY 94 / PM's brother in graft probe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Paolo Berlusconi, younger brother of Italy's new prime minister, has
become implicated in a fourth corruption investigation by Milan magistrates.
According to press reports yesterday, Mr Paolo Berlusconi admitted two weeks
ago paying L800m (Pounds 334,000) in 1988 and 1989 to facilitate a
development project in the suburbs of Milan. The payments were allegedly
made by Edilnord, his construction group, to a local Socialist mayor and two
planning officers. Previously Mr Paolo Berlusconi has acknowledged another
L1bn payment by Edilnord for property developments in the Milan suburbs, but
said he was forced to pay the money. Until transferred to Mr Paolo
Berlusconi in 1992, Edilnord was part of the Fininvest empire controlled by
his elder brother, Silvio.
In another development yesterday the Milan public prosecutor demanded prison
sentences of four years eight months for two former Socialist mayors, Mr
Paolo Pillitteri and Mr Carlo Tognoli, for alleged corruption related to
contracts with Aem, the municipal energy company. The prosecution also
called for prison sentences of between two and three years for four former
politicians and six businessmen. Mr Pillitteri is a brother-in-law of Mr
Bettino Craxi, the former Socialist leader. Mr Craxi was yesterday reported
to be recovering in a Tunis clinic amid reports that Milan magistrates will
soon seek his arrest for alleged corruption.
