<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / More competition complaints
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LIONEL BARBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The European Commission is receiving more and more complaints about
restrictions on competition, its annual report on competition for 1993
reveals. Mr Karel Van Miert, competition commissioner, said complaints had
doubled since 1980, and the trend was likely to accelerate as companies
insist on a level playing field in the single market. In particular, the
commissioner took aim at restrictions in competition in Europe's energy
market. Mr Van Miert promised to press ahead with efforts to create a single
market in energy which was lagging behind telecoms liberalisation.
Commission officials hope that private sector complaints could be a tool for
attacking state monopolies, particularly powerful operators in the gas and
electricity industry.
In 1993, the Commission eliminated its backlog of old competition cases.
Some 1,250 cases involving cartels or abuse of a dominant position were
being examined on December 31, 1993, compared with a little under 1,700 a
year earlier. Mr Van Miert signalled that the Commission is examining how to
develop the idea of a common competition area extending to prospective EU
members in eastern Europe.
</TEXT>
