<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAY 94 / Lufthansa sell-off plan approved
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By QUENTIN PEEL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The German government yesterday approved plans for the progressive
privatisation of Lufthansa, the national airline, and promised to reduce its
stake in a first step from 51.4 to 38 per cent, by not participating in a
DM515m (Pounds 206m) rights issue.
The three-phase process of privatisation would be completed as rapidly as
the capital markets allowed, possibly by the end of 1995, said Mr Matthias
Wissmann, transport minister.
The agreement thrashed out by Lufthansa, the transport and finance
ministries, and the state pensions fund (VBL) was approved by the cabinet
yesterday, after winning the support of unions and employees at the airline.
Lufthansa shareholders will be asked to approve the first step of the
process, the capital increase of DM515m, as well as an unspecified number of
special shares for employees, on top of the existing DM1.52bn nominal
capital, at their annual meeting on July 6.
Mr Wissmann confirmed that the government hoped to encourage the widest
possible range of shareholders in the privatised airline, but precise
details had yet to be worked out. He declined to comment on whether or how
foreign ownership of shares might be restricted, except to confirm that the
matter was under discussion.
He said that after the capital increase, the government hoped to sell a
first tranche of its remaining shareholding before the end of the year. A
second tranche to dispose of the entire state shareholding could be sold
before the end of 1995.
Lufthansa announced on Monday it expected to return to profit this year, and
paid its first dividend to ordinary shareholders since 1989. The European
Court yesterday rejected an Air France appeal against a decision by Brussels
in 1992 to authorise the purchase by British Airways of 49.9 per cent of
Transport Aerien Transregional (TAT), a French airline. Air France had
claimed the acquisition could cause access problems on French air routes.
