<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / International Company News: Hungarian rescue costs WestLB
DM32m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NICHOLAS DENTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BUDAPEST
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Westdeutsche Landesbank (WestLB), the German bank, said yesterday its
investment in WestLB Hungaria had grown to DM72m (Dollars 42.3m) because of
the cost of bailing out its troubled Budapest-based subsidiary.
In addition to the DM40m purchase price paid in 1992, WestLB injected DM32m
into the bank in December, diluting minority shareholders and lifting
WestLB's stake to 96 per cent from 60 per cent.
This was necessary because provisioning for bad loans and investments
dragged WestLB Hungaria to a loss of Ft1.89bn (Dollars 19m) in 1993 and left
its capital adequacy well below the Ft1bn minimum set by Hungarian
regulators.
Mr Dieter Falke, board member of the Dusseldorf-based regional bank, denied
the investment in the bank was a mistake: 'We undoubtedly came two years
earlier than we should have.'
WestLB blamed last year's results on the hangover from its Hungarian unit's
earlier incarnation as Altalanos Vallalkozasi Bank (AVB), a joint venture
bank in which WestLB took a minority stake in 1992.
Hungary's state banking supervisor closed down AVB on discovering the bank
was unstable. WestLB rescued AVB, changed the bank's name and is turning it
into a subsidiary.
