<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / Speaker elected in Ukraine
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JILL BARSHAY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   KIEV
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Oleksandr Moroz was yesterday elected chairman of the new Ukrainian
parliament in a secret ballot. The selection of Mr Moroz, leader of the
Socialist party, is the first important decision taken by Ukraine's new
legislature, but its significance is unclear. On one hand, Mr Moroz's
election to one of the most powerful posts in the Ukrainian government
suggests that most MPs lean towards the Socialist party's anti-reform
platform and favour the restoration of closer ties with Russia. However,
Socialist MPs do not hold a majority of the seats in parliament.
Ukrainian observers have suggested that Mr Moroz, who is known to be a
Ukrainian patriot, may have entered into an unlikely alliance with Rukh, the
pro-reform, democratic nationalist faction in the legislature. No matter
which political line Mr Moroz eventually takes, it was apparent from his
acceptance speech that the new parliamentary chairman aims to continue the
heated constitutional battle in Ukraine. In a veiled attack on President
Leonid Kravchuk, who is struggling to retain his grip on the nation, Mr
Moroz said that the legislature, rather than the presidency, should be the
centre of governmental authority.
Ukraine still has no post-Soviet constitution and is ruled by a Soviet-era
document, amended so many times that it is unclear which branches have which
powers.
</TEXT>
