<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / Russia fails to persuade Nato
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRUCE CLARK
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Nato ambassadors yesterday rebuffed Moscow's demand for an alternative to
the Partnership for Peace arrangement, in a move that casts a shadow over
next week's visit to Brussels by General Pavel Grachev, the Russian defence
minister.
Gen Grachev has stated that Russia is not prepared simply to join the queue
of east European countries which are signing up to PFP, an arrangement that
provides for joint exercises and an exchange of military knowhow.
At a meeting in Brussels yesterday, the ambassadors said the most they could
promise was 'dialogue and co-operation' of a kind that reflected Russia's
importance in European security.
However, this dialogue would be in addition to Russian adherence to PFP, not
a substitute. An alliance spokesman said Nato 'looked forward' to Russia
subscribing to the partnership, which already has 18 members.
'We do not like the term special relationship,' said a Nato official, adding
that any links between Russia and the alliance must be transparent and stop
short of giving Moscow a veto over future decisions by the alliance.
The official said that there could be no question of Nato and Russia
exercising a condominium over the smaller states of central and eastern
Europe.
Mr Klaus Kinkel, the German foreign minister, is understood to be pressing
for some concession to Russian sensitivities. He was impressed by the
arguments put forward in Germany last week by President Boris Yeltsin, who
said he was under increasing pressure from hardliners.
Mr Volker Ruhe, Bonn's defence minister, is believed to be pressing a
tougher line, insisting that Russian objections should not be allowed to
obstruct the growing relationship between Germany and its neighbours to the
east.
This week's German-Dutch initiative to upgrade the 52-nation Conference on
Security and Co-operation in Europe - a move which Moscow will warmly
welcome - prompted speculation that Mr Yeltsin had negotiated some sort of
trade-off in Bonn.
However, the contrast between the stated positions of Nato and Russia
remained so wide after yesterday's meeting that considerable effort will be
needed to paper over the cracks. It is conceivable that the Russians will
present Nato's promise of an upgraded 'dialogue' as a concession to their
demands, and that some western countries will save Russia's face by publicly
concurring.
But the position sketched out by Nato ambassadors yesterday - which did not
amount to a formal decision - falls far short of meeting Russia's demand
that it become a co-designer of any co-operation efforts. Gen Grachev, a
former paratrooper who won prominence in the war in Afghanistan, is thought
to be a pragmatist in matters of links with Nato: keen to derive any
possible advantage if this can be done without exposing Russia to
humiliation.
The defence minister would not want to miss any opportunity to receive a
western blessing for its 'peace-keeping' forces in the smaller ex-Soviet
republics, where Russian influence remains strong.
Among the older generation of officers who continue to dominate Russia's
general staff, hostility to the Atlantic alliance, which they spent most of
their careers confronting, runs much deeper.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>RUZ  Russia, East Europe.
    BEZ  Belgium, EC.
