<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / Berlusconi narrowly wins vote in Senate
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Silvio Berlusconi, Italy's new prime minister, last night cleared a major
hurdle when his rightwing cabinet narrowly won a vote of confidence in the
Italian Senate.
Mr Berlusconi's Freedom Alliance lacked an absolute majority in the 326-seat
senate, and he was forced to rely on the absence of some senators and the
abstention of others during the motion, which he won by a handful of votes.
With the vote behind him, Mr Berlusconi can now begin to flesh out the
details of deregulating the economy, relaxing Italy's rigid labour laws and
reforming taxes which he announced earlier this week would be the
centrepiece of his first 100 days.
The closeness of the vote yesterday underlined the difficulties facing the
media magnate turned politician in sustaining his government in office over
the medium term.
The three-day debate in the senate showed many politicians were concerned
about the composition of the new government with its five ministers drawn
from the neo-fascist MSDI/ National Alliance and the presence of the
populist Northern League.
The small but influential group of senators belonging to centrist parties
spawned by the demise of the Christian Democrats were those most clearly
caught in a dilemma. They did not wish to be seen responsible for bringing
down the government before it started operating. Equally they did not wish
to be seen giving Mr Berlusconi a helping hand. It was thus convenient that
some chose to be discreetly absent.
Before yesterday's vote, the combined strength of the opposition in the
progressive block led by the former communist Party of the Democratic Left
(PDS) and the centre headed by the Popular Party (PPI) was 152 against the
government's 156.
The debate produced few surprises with the parties defending already well
publicised views. However, Mr Berlusconi went some way to reassure trade
unions that he would respect a wage and productivity agreement signed with
the employers and government last July.
</TEXT>
