<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / World Stock Markets: Emerging markets: IFC weekly investable
price indices
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN PITT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Emerging markets continue to suffer setbacks, with Greece the latest
casualty, writes John Pitt.  After a rapid increase in interest rates as the
government struggled to defend the drachma, the country's equity market went
into reverse.  Shares fell a further 2 per cent yesterday, closing at the
lowest point this year and down 22 per cent since the start of the year.
Little wonder then that some commentators are highlighting potential growth
areas in others parts of the world.  Kleiman International Consultants notes
that and 'acceleration of planned economic liberalisation programmes has in
recent months reversed bourse stagnation throughout the Mediterranean
region'.  Kleiman says securities activity was picking up on the informal
Cyprus OTC market, and in Lebanon through the recent over-subscription to
Solidere, which plans to rebuild central Beirut.
