<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / Commodities and Agriculture: France outlines farm export
reform for EU
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
France yesterday served notice of its intention to increase its share of the
European market by becoming more competitive and Europe's share of the world
market by making more sparing use of subsidised food exports now constrained
by the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade.
Mr Jean Puech, the French agriculture minister, told the National Assembly
that his new ideas would be contained in a memorandum to go to Brussels and
France's European Union partners just before France takes over the EU
presidency for the first half of 1995.
In addition to a series of structural and financial changes to French
agriculture, Paris will be also suggesting that:
The EU should abolish export rebates on sales to richer countries or on
products like poultry where the subsidy is of marginal impact;
Concentrate cereal sales in the winter months when the world price generally
rises to nearer that of the EU, so that less subsidy is needed;
Exploit Gatt requirements that Europe increase other food producers'
'minimum access' to the European market by using these imports as a cheap
input material for re-export. One example is that the melting down of cheese
imports for re-export without subsidy;
Introduce differential pricing so that European farmers would only get
guaranteed prices on a percentage of their production, the rest of which
could exported without the benefit of subsidies.
