<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / Government Bonds: Treasuries mixed as fresh trading range
sought
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY and GRAHAM BOWLEY AND CONNER MIDDELMANN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
US Treasury bonds were mixed yesterday as the market sought to establish a
fresh trading range in the wake of the Federal Reserve's aggressive
tightening of monetary policy.
Late in the session, the benchmark 30-year government bond was down 3/32 at
87 21/32 , with the yield rising to 7.268 per cent. At the short end, the
two-year note gained  3/16 to 99 15/32 , to yield 5.773 per cent.
The pull-back at the long end of the maturity range reflected a modest
adjustment after the previous session's powerful rally.
On Tuesday, prices on the 30-year issue jumped nearly 2 points when the
central bank announced a decision to lift the Federal Funds and the discount
rate by 50 basis points each, to 4.25 per cent and 3.50 per cent
respectively.
In addition to easing traders' concern over inflation, the Fed removed the
cloud of uncertainty hanging over the market by strongly suggesting that no
further rate increases were likely until the end of the summer.
Although the market was generally encouraged by the Fed's action, there was
fresh concern over the continued weakness of the dollar, which failed to
gather strength against the yen and fell against D-mark on the foreign
exchange markets. Traders are worried about the failure of the currency to
respond to the Fed's rate increases because a weak dollar discourages
investment in US-denominated securities.
As a result the long bond failed to extend Tuesday's gains but finished well
off its lows reached in early afternoon.
UK gilts held on to initial gains despite a sharp fall early in the day
triggered by data showing an unexpected increase in average earnings.
Gilts rallied initially, fuelled by overnight gains in the US market
following the US Federal Reserve's decision to raise short-term interest
rates. But they fell back after the publication of a raft of economic data
and the minutes of the March 30 meeting between the chancellor and the
governor of the Bank of England.
Average earnings rose at an annual rate of 4 per cent in March, higher than
expected, and a sign of growing inflationary pressures. The Bank of England
has highlighted wage growth as one of the main risks to the UK inflation
outlook.
Other data however pointed to a more optimistic prospect for inflation.
Headline inflation increased at an annual rate of 2.6 per cent in April  -
which was below expectations - and the minutes of the meeting showed no
serious disagreement between the chancellor and the governor. Analysts said
it was significant that they had discussed the possibility of cutting
interest rates further and that neither had even mentioned raising rates.
This information caused the market to recover before it eased slightly in
later trading on profit-taking. The long gilt future was up  1/2 point at
105 29/32 in late trading.
French bonds put on a strong performance, boosted by hopes of an interest
rate cut at today's meeting of the central bank's monetary policy council.
Traders are hoping for a 10 basis points reduction in its 5 1/2 per cent
intervention rate.
Switching out of German into French bonds continued, causing the yield
spread of the benchmark 10-year OAT over its German counterpart to narrow
further to around 33 basis points, from 41 on Tuesday.
The June notional bond contract on Matif rose 1.12 point to 122.22.
Italian bonds also shone, spurred by hopes that the confidence vote in the
Senate for prime minister Mr Silvio Berlusconi's government would pass
successfully. While some traders said a positive vote for the government
would push prices even higher, Mr Andre de Silva, bond strategist at
PaineWebber in London, said such an outcome 'was already reflected in
(yesterday's) price action' and would lead to a knee-jerk reaction, at best.
The June BTP futures contract on Liffe rose about 0.90 point on the day to
113.40.
German bonds put on a lacklustre performance, despite the Bundesbank's
12-basis-point cut in its securities repurchase rate to 5.23 per cent.
Traders reported continued switching out of bunds into French, UK and US
bonds. Mr Carl Haeling, head of the futures and options group at Deutsche
Bank in Frankfurt, recommends short-term trading strategies, rather than
longer-term commitments.
'We still see upside potential, but just as many downside risks - any
rallies we'll get are more likely to be a continuation of the overall
sideways pattern rather than any sustained upwards trend in prices.'
</TEXT>
