<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / International Bonds: Fed decision on interest rates prompts
rush of new issues
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER JOHN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The decision by the US Federal Reserve to raise interest rates on Tuesday
removed a significant uncertainty from the Eurobond market yesterday and
encouraged the launch of a spate of issues in several currencies.
However, there was a feeling that a lot of unwanted bonds were still
cluttering up the system and until underwriters had cleared their books, the
rush of new supply would have to wait.
Credit Local de France, the triple-A rated French municipal financing
agency, came back to the market for the second day running to raise Pounds
150m via a 10-year bond priced to yield 37 basis points above the equivalent
gilt.
Joint lead manager Samuel Montagu said the decision to plump for sterling
had been prompted by good overseas and UK demand for the UK currency
following the US rate rise.
However, some syndicate managers said that the pricing on the bonds should
have been set around the 'low 40s'. When the paper started to trade, the
spread widened to 39 basis points over gilts.
Frequent borrower Eurofima, the Swiss-based group which funds the purchase
of railway rolling stock, launched its well-flagged French franc deal
yesterday, raising FFr1bn through an offering of 10-year paper priced to
yield 16 basis points above the equivalent French government bond. The bonds
were taken up principally by continental and Japanese investors. Lead
manager CCF said it was possible that the deal would be increased at a later
date.
Elsewhere, the Swiss franc sector was active with five deals amounting to
the equivalent of Dollars 420m. Dealers said at least four more deals were
in the pipeline, mainly from double-A and triple-A rated companies.
European Investment Bank set the ball rolling when it issued a SFr200m bond
maturing in June 2001. DSL Finance offered SFr100m of 10-year paper while
Abbey National Treasury Services made a private placement of SFr100m of
bonds maturing in December 1997. There were two further domestic deals by
German banks which were thought to be swapping the proceeds into D-Marks.
The Hungarian National Bank issued Sch1bn of seven-year paper while Bank
Austria offered DM250m of similarly dated paper with attached warrants
through Morgan Stanley.
</TEXT>
