<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / International Company News: Indian companies cleared to
return to euromarkets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEFAN WAGSTYL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW DELHI
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Indian companies, forced to postpone plans for euroissues following the
failure of the Dollars 1bn offering by Videsh Sanchar Nigam (VSNL), India's
international telecommunications carrier, are preparing to return to the
market.
The finance ministry has given preliminary approval to 12 companies to tap
the markets in the next three months.
They include Telco, the lorry and bus maker belonging to the Tata industrial
grouping, with a Dollars 300m deal; Bajaj Auto, the scooter and motorcycle
manufacturer (Dollars 160m); JK Synthetics, a plastics company (Dollars
100m); and Straw Products, a paper and board manufacturer (Dollars 100m).
These four groups alone aim to raise Dollars 660m, so the total for the
three months could reach Dollars 1bn.
Under guidelines announced this month, the ministry has powers to regulate
the flow of companies going to the market. Would-be issuers must seek
preliminary approval and then return to the ministry for final approval once
terms are set.
Investment bankers in Bombay said yesterday the prices of Global Depository
Receipts issued by Indian companies, which had fallen heavily before VSNL's
abortive issue, had recently recovered.
As well as the 12 companies approved for the coming three months, several
others which secured approval before the VSNL issue went to the market are
expected to resume their attempts to raise funds. Among them is Ballarpur
Paper, a papermaker and flagship company of the Delhi-based Thapar
industrial grouping.
Meanwhile, leading state-owned banks are about to secure permission to tap
the capital markets for the first time. A parliamentary bill allowing these
banks to raise private equity and dilute the government's 100 per cent stake
is expected to receive the president's assent and become law in the next few
days.
About six banks are expected to try to raise between Rs2bn and Rs3bn
(Dollars 95.7m) each in the next few months. They include some of the
best-performing state-owned banks, notably Punjab National Bank, Canara
Bank, Bank of Baroda and Oriental Bank of Commerce.
They will be following the State Bank of India, the largest publicly-owned
bank, which last year raised Rs32bn in stocks and bonds. SBI was able to go
to market without enabling legislation because its ownership structure was
different. SBI cut the state's shareholding from 98 per cent to 66 per cent.
</TEXT>
