FT  19 MAY 94 / International Company News: Merck buys into generic drugs
sector
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DANIEL GREEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Merck AG has become the latest German pharmaceuticals concern to buy into
the generic drugs business. It said yesterday it would buy 51 per cent of
the capital of Amerpharm, a generic drugs manufacturer controlled from the
Netherlands.
The price of the deal was not revealed. Merck said Amerpharm had sales of
Dollars 104m in 1993 and earnings before interest and taxes of Dollars 15m.
Generics manufacturers specialise in launching products whose patents have
expired. The business is growing quickly because of the number of
big-selling drugs whose patents are running out.
Mr Hans Langmann, Merck executive management president, said the company
might have to finance the acquisition through capital markets or
'equity-linked measures'.
Merck will be taking control of Amerpharm from the South African Tabatznic
family, which has a long association with the generics business. The family
would continue to hold a significant stake in the operation, said Merck.
