<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / International Company News: Maple Leaf Foods hit by higher
costs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Higher costs and unusually cold weather have been partly blamed for
first-quarter earnings at Maple Leaf Foods, Canada's biggest food processor,
down by 21 per cent.
Maple Leaf, which is 56 per cent-owned by the UK's Hillsdown Holdings, also
ascribed the setback to strong competitive pressures in some of its
businesses, notably bakeries and flour milling.
Net earnings dipped to CDollars 8m (USDollars 5.8m), or 10 cents a share,
from CDollars 10.2m, or 13 cents, a year earlier. Sales climbed to CDollars
659.9m from CDollars 632.4m.
The bottom line was also hit by a fall in interest income, to CDollars
870,000 from CDollars 2.9m, resulting from lower interest rates and smaller
cash balances.
Mr Brent Ballantyne, chief executive, predicted improved earnings for the
rest of the year. Businesses which posted improved first-quarter profits
included fresh pork and animal feed.
</TEXT>
