<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / International Company News: EDS and software group agree
licence deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Electronic Data Systems, the computing services company, and Computer
Associates, the provider of systems and application software, have ended a
28-month legal dispute and announced a software licensing agreement they
claim to be the largest.
Computer Associates sued EDS in 1991, alleging it had obtained unauthorised
access to its software and used it without paying fees to process data for
third parties.
The centrepiece of the agreement is a 12-year licence, renewable for a
further five years, giving EDS broad and flexible use of all current
Computer Associates products for itself and its customers throughout the
world. Where appropriate, EDS will standardise on Computer Associates
products at all its information processing centres.
EDS will become a value-added reseller of Computer Associates software. It
will initially have the right to resell Dollars 100m of CA-Unicenter, a
systems management package for the client/server market.
The two sides are discussing an agreement for Computer Associates to
outsource the information technology support for some of its administrative
and financial functions to EDS.
Both refused to put a value on the settlement. Mr Les Alberthal, chairman of
EDS, said the deal was unrelated to Monday's news that General Motors, which
owns EDS, was considering spinning it off to facilitate a possible merger
between EDS and Sprint, the telecommunications group.
Mr Alberthal said EDS had long believed an alliance with a leading software
group would be of benefit.
</TEXT>
