<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / International Company News: Canada media groups link in
satellite TV venture
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Several of Canada's biggest broadcast, cable-TV and telecommunications
companies have joined forces to develop a satellite-based TV service.
The proposed alliance is largely a response to the competitive threat from
DirectTv, the fledgling US service, nicknamed Deathstar, which aims to beam
as many as 500 TV channels directly into North American homes.
The new venture is a defensive move for the cable-TV operators, which have a
monopoly in their licence areas. Satellite services are expected to be far
more loosely regulated than cable-TV, and can be picked up by any household
with a receiving dish.
However, the consortium also includes BCE, holding company of Bell Canada,
the country's biggest telephone company. BCE has recently begun to broaden
its horizons in the multimedia sector. It is also the majority shareholder
of Telesat Canada, which operates Canada's communications satellites.
The other seven participants include Rogers Cablesystems, Canada's biggest
cable-TV operator; WIC Western International Communications, which is the
largest private broadcaster; and Cancom Satellite Communications, which
distributes TV signals by satellite to 2,500 cable systems, mostly in remote
rural areas.
The group plans to set up a national 'direct-to-home' (DTH) service within
the next 12 months. It will deliver pay-per-view - pay TV and other
programming in digitally-compressed form - to cable systems as well as to
DTH subscribers. The cost of setting up the service is estimated at CDollars
85m (USDollars 62m).
The plans also include a central authorisation facility which will enable
small cable-TV systems to offer pay-TV services to their subscribers.
A 5 per cent equity stake in the new venture has been left for outside
investors.
</TEXT>
<XX>
