FT  19 MAY 94 / International Company News: Oppenheim ahead 15% for year
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BERLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Sal. Oppenheim, Germany's largest private banking house, will increase its
dividend by DM3 to DM15 after announcing profits up 15 per cent in 1993.
Profits rose from DM39m to DM45m (Dollars 26.9m) last year, after the bank's
concentration on corporate finance, asset management and financial
engineering. Total business volume rose by 17 per cent to DM10.3bn and
credit volume rose from DM5.6bn to DM5.8bn.
All sectors of the bank recorded growth, but it was consolidating its
interests in banking stakes acquired last year. These include MeesPierson
bank in the Netherlands and Bank Oppenheim Pierson in Switzerland.
The bank has not been directly affected by the collapse of the property
empire of Mr Jurgen Schneider. However, a consortium including Rheinboden
Hypothekenbank, in which Oppenheim holds a 51 per cent stake, had lent Mr
Schneider DM125m.
Axel Springer, the media group, is to pay a DM12 dividend. The company,
which publishes the daily newspapers Bild and Die Welt, reported a rise in
group net profits from DM57m to DM71m last year.
