<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / International Company News: Married without a honeymoon -
Michael Lindemann and Quentin Peel talk to Krupp Hoesch chief Gerhard
Cromme, who insists that the merger came just in time
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL LINDEMANN and QUENTIN PEEL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Gerhard Cromme, chief executive of Krupp Hoesch, seems to be an
incorrigible optimist.
He has had to be, given the problems he has faced in the last two years,
consummating the marriage of Germany's second- and third-largest steelmakers
in the midst of the sharpest post-war recession in their main markets. He
never had a honeymoon.
The merged group is in the process of shedding at least 25,000 jobs, more
than one in four of its workforce. It had to shoulder a loss last year of
almost DM600m (Dollars 353m), and close one of its two main integrated steel
plants. It still carries a debt burden of almost DM5.8bn.
Mr Cromme insists the merger was an ideal industrial marriage, with
rationalisation and cost-saving possible in 70 per cent of operations. At
the same time, the depth of the 1993 downturn in steel, capital goods and
the motor industry, helped concentrate minds and accelerate the process, he
says.
'The merger came only just in time. The crisis in 1993 was so bad that both
Krupp and Hoesch alone would have had difficulties surviving in the same
form they are in today.'
The merger was confirmed in December 1992, and took a further six months to
begin putting into effect. It leaves the cumbersomely titled Fried. Krupp AG
Hoesch-Krupp with six broad divisions, ranging from its strengths in steel,
engineering and plant construction, to its expanding interests in trade and
services.
Mr Cromme singles out the automotive supplies division as a beneficiary,
because the joint operation can provide manufacturers with complete systems,
instead of individual parts. For example, it will for the first time supply
the complete front axle for the new Jaguar in the UK.
The cost savings from the merger are still working through, he says. The
combined data processing operation will be DM100m a year cheaper than the
separate operations, and DM60m of that has already been achieved.
The savings, above all in the group payroll, are an important factor behind
his forecast of returning to break-even this year. 'Turnover in 1994 will be
roughly the same as it was for the two companies in 1992, but we already
have 16,000 fewer people.'
It was not the merger which caused the real problems, he insists, but the
extent of the economic recession. And yet he believes that has been
beneficial for the industry.
'Everything that happened in 1993 brought the German steel industry for the
first time to the point of real rationalisation.' After a decade of
desultory and unsuccessful negotiations, Thyssen, the largest steelmaker,
and Krupp Hoesch are involved in the process of streamlining their
operations.
The outline of the plan, agreed last December, is for Thyssen to take
majority control in two areas - tinplate and electrical strip - and Krupp
Hoesch to lead in special steel flat products. The three areas make up 30
per cent of Krupp Hoesch's steel output.
Krupp's interest in special steels will be reinforced if it is successful in
its joint bid with three Italian partners - Riva, Falck, and Tadfin - for
AST, the special steels division of Ilva, the Italian state-owned steel
company.
'That means that in steel we will continue to develop those areas where we
see the chance of a competitive future,' Mr Cromme says.
At the same time, the closure of the Krupp steel plant at Rheinhausen,
cutting crude steel capacity by 4m tonnes, has left the group with 'a
virtual equilibrium' between all its parts of the steel-making process - and
no incentive to make any further large capacity cuts, he says.
Mr Cromme says he has no intention of seeking debt relief along the lines of
his competitor, Klockner, and in spite of the heavy debt burden. 'We will
have no Chapter 11 here.'
The overall debt burden did not increase last year and remained constant at
almost DM5.8bn. Mr Cromme denies plans for further large disposals to reduce
the debt burden, but says it would be cut by good cash flow.
The company's heavy capital investment programme has been curtailed, and the
money normally ploughed into investment will go to pay off some of that
debt.
Mr Cromme is optimistic about Germany's efforts to remain competitive as an
investment location. 'We have solved more problems in Germany in the past
year than many sceptics thought we could,' he says.
He believes the D-Mark will regain some of its competitiveness against the
dollar and other European currencies in the coming months.
The future for Krupp Hoesch rests heavily on its international markets, and
investing close to them, he says.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Fried Krupp AG Krupp Hoesch Stahl.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>DEZ  Germany, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P3312 Blast Furnaces and Steel Mills.
    P3731 Ship Building and Repairing.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
