<PROFILE>_AN-EESCVAFGFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940519
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / International Company News: Ready and eager for the next
phase - The growth of DCC, which makes its market debut today
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM COONE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
According to Mr Jim Flavin, the founder and chief executive of DCC, the
Irish industrial holding company which makes its debut on the London and
Dublin Stock Exchanges today, 'it is the end of the beginning'.
At its flotation price of IPounds 2.50 the company will have a market
capitalisation of IPounds 182m (Pounds 178m). It started out in 1976 as a
venture capital company with just IPounds 1m in equity and according to one
broking firm in Dublin, 'has achieved an annual 23 per cent compound return
for its shareholders since then'.
Evolving into an industrial holding company in 1990 and expanding rapidly
since, the flotation is the step that Mr Flavin hopes will enable DCC to
grow to a market capitalisation in excess of IPounds 1bn early in the next
decade.
'There is a sense of excitement here about the next phase' said Mr Flavin at
his headquarters in Dublin, where he heads a staff of 18 executives.
Together they run a group which includes snack foods manufacturing in
Ireland, waste oil recycling and natural gas distribution in the UK, and
health care services in the US.
Europe, however, is where DCC is planning its next phase of expansion.
Through its Printech subsidiary it is already a leading supplier of computer
manuals to the continental European market. Further expansion of that
business is under way following investment of IPounds 11m in plant and
machinery and the signing of large customers such as IBM, Apple, Digital and
Dell.
A computer products distribution division, with IPounds 70m turnover last
year, plans to expand through acquisitions in Europe, primarily in France
and Germany.
'Both divisions are becoming pan-European. US and Japanese companies
increasingly want to deal with a European-wide company rather than
individual companies in each country. We are developing that capacity,' he
said.
DCC's 11 per cent stake and a directorship in Fyffes also gives it a
substantial interest in the development of the European fruit distribution
business.
Mr Flavin said that the flotation, which is raising IPounds 6m in new
equity, is aimed primarily at giving DCC greater financial flexibility as it
plans its expansion on to the Continent. 'If you want to grow you have to
attract international investors,' he said.
The ones he has in mind are the European fund managers in the UK who he says
are now taking a much greater interest in Irish companies than they were a
few years ago.
No large rights issue is planned for the time being, however. Mr Flavin
points proudly to DCC's record of the past three years in which IPounds 114m
has been spent on capital investment and acquisitions without recourse to
shareholders, and yet the business still has net cash. About IPounds 25m has
been raised through the disposal of 18 non-core businesses in the past four
years, but Mr Flavin's secret is in cash flow.
'All our businesses are quite cash generative. It has been our strategy to
invest in cash-generative companies and which have strong positions in niche
markets,' he said.
The flotation will give DCC the flexibility to finance the next deals
through the issue of paper rather than by using cash, and which he expects
to be modest bolt-on acquisitions in the IPounds 5m to IPounds 15m range.
'We won't do anything which will unbalance the ethos of the company and we
are unlikely to make any acquisition larger than IPounds 50m,' he said.
A key part of that ethos is to keep management teams in place in the
companies acquired whenever possible. 'We are not hell-bent on taking
control . . . We seek to encourage and develop the businesses we are in. We
invest further, rather than slash costs and rake all the cash out.'
In most of the DCC subsidiaries, the management teams have retained a
significant equity participation, giving them a strong incentive to make the
businesses perform well.
Significantly, in four of DCC's six main subsidiaries the key executives are
also those companies' founders.
'Development of the businesses we are in is part and parcel of the group's
culture. We are long term in our thinking and believe that strong businesses
are built over the long haul,' Mr Flavin said.
Evidence of that is Mr Flavin's relationship with Fyffes. DCC first took a
stake in FII, an Irish fruit distributor run by the McCann family, in 1981.
He advised the McCanns on FII's flotation on the USM that year and later
advised them on the takeover of Fyffes in 1986. It is widely believed that
it was Mr Flavin who blocked the Dole bid for Fyffes last year.
If Dole were to return with a better offer Mr Flavin says he is unlikely to
be interested. 'Big businesses are built through constancy. We have a
long-term perspective on Fyffes and we are there to stay,' he said.
But while Fyffes will continue to have a role in DCC as the largest of its
associated holdings, Mr Flavin said that controlled subsidiaries would be
the main profit centres of the group. 'I do not anticipate that controlled
subsidiaries will contribute less than 80 per cent of group profits in the
future,' he said. At present they contribute 76 per cent.
He plans to keep DCC diversified across four or five divisions and not to
borrow heavily to finance acquisitions or investment. 'We like to manage
risk by spread and financial prudence . . . I would be uncomfortable to have
interest cover less than five,' he said.
That financial caution - mirrored incidentally by Fyffes' own aversion to
debt - has brought DCC to the market with a strong balance sheet, no net
debt, and total net assets of IPounds 101m for the year ending March 1994.
Pre-tax profits of IPounds 22.2m last year translate to earnings per share
of 19.6p, which at the flotation price gives an historic p/e of 12.8. Its
prospective p/e is about 11.4.
According to Goodbody stockbrokers in Dublin: 'For a company with DCC's
quality, financial strength and potential for growth, we believe its opening
multiple is very undemanding.'
The meritocratic Mr Flavin, who told reporters last week 'I was not born
with a silver spoon in my mouth,' could not wish for a better accolade to
mark the end of his beginning.
</TEXT>
