<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / UK Company News: National Power seeks clarification
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
National Power indicated yesterday that an early sale of power plants was
unlikely as it revealed profits for 1993-94.
Mr John Baker, chief executive, said that although a quick disposal was
possible, everything pointed to potential buyers and the company itself
waiting for clarification on three key issues.
These were the flotation of the government's 40 per cent share in the
company, probably next February, a review of emission standards by the
government's pollution inspectorate and a long-term review by the power
industry of the electricity trading pool.
National Power agreed a deal in February with the electricity regulator by
which it would endeavour to sell 3,000MW of capacity.
Mr Baker said the company was reviewing a range of options including assets
swaps with overseas companies, sales of individual stations and a demerger
involving several plants.
Mr Baker said it would be difficult to effect a subst-antial change to the
company ahead of the flotation of the government's stake next year.
Meanwhile, National Power is to ask its shareholders at the forthcoming
annual meeting for approval to buy back up to 10 per cent of its shares.
Buying back shares is likely to be an increasing trend in the power industry
among companies with low debt. National Power finished the year with gearing
of 13 per cent.
However, Mr Brian Birkenhead, finance director, said the buy-back was just
an option. Seeking permission from shareholders did not mean the company
intended to take it up. There were no immediate plans for a buy-back.
The company is also considering taking part in an auction this spring by the
government in which companies will be given the chance to buy back their
debt. National Power's government debt is Pounds 350m.
</TEXT>
<XX>
