<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / UK Company News: IBM UK moves into outsourcing business
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BOLGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
International Business Machines UK yesterday presented itself in the
unlikely role of championing the trend towards 'minimalist companies' -
organisations which contract out their non-core activities.
The UK market for contracting out, or outsourcing, business services is
worth Pounds 7.1bn a year, according to an independent report commissioned
by IBM, which said the Pounds 337m current value of outsourced activities
represented only a small fraction of the true market.
The UK subsidiary of the global computing giant has responded by putting
staff into two new specialist businesses, Financial Administration Services
and Business Administration Services.
They will offer to manage for external customers functions such as payroll,
vehicle fleet management, document design and accounts - the principal
activities currently outsourced.
About 550 of IBM UK's workforce of 11,000 come under the new businesses,
which until now have been providing these services within IBM. New staff
will be taken on as and when external contracts are won.
Mr Peter Cruttenden, director of finance and planning, said: 'We were
prompted by our own customers to investigate the outsourcing market after
receiving approaches from them to use our administration services.
Outsourcing is the way forward for organisations which need to concentrate
on their core businesses.'
IBM said last month that the group had returned to profitability after three
years of heavy losses and retrenchment.
Asked about IBM's credentials to advise other companies, Mr Cruttenden said:
'We have been through a character-forming experience in recent years. Our
track record speaks for itself. No other company has had to deal with such
technological change in an economic ice age.'
IBM UK's workforce had been cut by about 45 per cent over the past
three-and-a-half years, but the administrative side had shrunk by about 60
per cent.
Mr Cruttenden said IBM UK's exposure in this venture was low-risk, as
outsourcing was still a relatively embryonic market. He said the UK example
was being closely watched by other parts of IBM.
The report says growth of outsourcing is forecast to be 12 per cent this
year, increasing to 19 per cent in 1995. Outsourcing: The Future of
Administration. Available, price Pounds 25, from IBM UK, PO Box 41, North
Harbour, Portsmouth, PO6 3AU.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>International Business Machines UK.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P7379 Computer Related Services, NEC.
    P7376 Computer Facilities Management.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>TECH  Services &amp; Services use.
</TP>
