<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / UK Company News: Expansion fired with the personal touch -
How Denby has rejected the limits of technology in favour of its craft-led
image
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The view has been obscured deliberately by a row of trees, but it is hard to
ignore the open-cast mine opposite the Denby Pottery factory in Derbyshire.
Here, Joseph Bourne, Denby's 19th century founder, first extracted the raw
materials to make his ginger beer bottles and butter churns.
Denby, which now manufactures brightly-glazed table and cookware, has come a
long way since the factory was established in 1809. It has survived several
near fatal upheavals but one of them cost it its independence as a public
company in 1981.
Today, the company announces the price at which it will ask investors to
back its second attempt to survive as a public company and its plans for
international expansion.
The management, which bought into the group following the collapse of its
parent Coloroll in 1990, is confident that past mistakes will not be
repeated.
There is a sense of deja vu as Denby's management watches its larger
colleagues in the industry consider applying their brand names to products
such as glass and textiles.
Denby's unhappy foray into similar areas in the US in the 1970s left it
reeling under heavy stock losses, and eventually led to takeovers, initially
by Crown House, the engineering company, and then by Coloroll.
Denby is now taking a different view to others in the industry, and not just
on product development where it plans to stick with producing its glazed
stoneware.
Unlike some of the larger, more prestigious manufacturers, Denby has
eschewed the latest developments in technology. Mr Stephen Riley, managing
director, says emphatically that Denby intends to remain a craft-based
company. He proudly states that some 23 pairs of hands will have dealt with
a single Denby mug, and there are no plans for change.
Manufacturers such as Wedgwood and Royal Doulton have used technology to
reduce substantially the labour costs of producing fine china.
Whereas plates used to be made by individual 'throwers' using wet clay
pressed by a hand-driven machine, the process can now be fully automated.
Grains of dust are molded into plates by a high pressure press. Many
manufacturers have also introduced automated glazing machines, where cups
and plates pirouette through a spray tunnel before being fired.
Denby still retains its army of human 'dippers and rinsers' to meet the
particular demands imposed by its distinctive combination of
highly-volatile, coloured glazes.
Their skill lies in rinsing the inside of a vessel with one colour of glaze
and dipping the outside up to the edge in another. This must be done
repeatedly to the same thickness - just one-thousandth of an inch out and
the glaze will change colour completely in the firing.
Industry insiders also argue that the most modern technology limits
flexibility for smaller manufacturers. Once you introduce integrated flow
lines, and highly automated machinery, it becomes less easy to switch
between products to meet demand.
'All you do is create a very inflexible situation where you become a slave
to the machine,' says Mr Kevin Farrell, director of the British Ceramic
Confederation, the industry body.
Mr Richard Booth, Denby's production director, insists the company is not
complacent about technological improvements. However, initial attempts to
use some types of automation have convinced him that Denby is best served by
the more tried and tested methods.
Denby is seeking to turn this 'crafty' element to its advantage, as the
trend shifts towards more informal dining habits. But it has not been the
first to spot the opportunities this provides. Even the likes of Royal
Doulton have announced their intention to introduce more casual ranges.
If such a player decides to enter the market in full force, smaller
manufacturers, like Denby, could face increasing competition.
'With all their factories and spare capacity, they could make a serious
impact,' says one manufacturer. This is where smaller companies will have to
capitalise on image and brand. For Denby, that means selling its unique
glazing skills and rounded shapes.
'I don't think Royal Doulton, or even we, would be able to make that
transition overnight,' says Mr George Hesp, managing director of Portmeirion
Potteries.
While Denby makes the most of its niche in the UK, it must move quickly to
build exports. Compared to similar companies, such as Portmeirion, which
exports more than 50 per cent of sales, Denby's record of 20 per cent is
poor.
The company intends to move rapidly into the US, the world's largest market.
The key is distribution.
'If you want growth in the US, you have got to be in department stores,'
says Mr Hesp.
By securing 15 of the leading chains, Denby is moving down the right path.
The US, so far, appears to be responding to Denby's message. Sales have
doubled in the last two years and are set to double again in 1994. Yet it is
still early days.
'A lot of companies think if you can sell there you can make a fortune,'
says Mr Hesp, who has spent 13 years building up Portmeirion's successful US
business. 'The road to hell is paved with people who thought that and ended
up bust.'
Mr Riley is not expecting any quick fix. 'We are giving ourselves another
four years to get anywhere close to Portmeirion's level,' he says.
He is confident that Denby's efforts to identify itself with a craft-led
image and narrow product range, will carry the group successfully in what
promises to be a competitive market. 'You have got to specialise first, and
then spread your wings worldwide,' he says. 'There is no option anymore.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Denby Group.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P3262 Vitreous China Table and Kitchenware.
    P3269 Pottery Products, NEC.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
