<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / UK Company News: Parkdean Leisure buys site for Pounds 2.4m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAGGIE URRY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Parkdean Leisure, the caravan park operator which floated last autumn, has
made its first acquisition as a public company.
It is paying Pounds 2.4m cash to the Marsh family for the Cherry Tree in
Burgh, Norfolk, close to its existing Summerfields site near Great Yarmouth.
Although acquisitions had been foreshadowed, the deal is larger than
expected. Mr Graham Wilson, managing director, said that whereas earlier
acquisitions had been of sites needing development, the park already had
'cracking facilities'. Further it had planning consents over an adjacent 10
acres to take another 150 units, expanding from the current 350 units.
The assets being bought had been valued at Pounds 2.4m. Pre-tax profits in
the latest financial year, to end-November, were Pounds 120,000 on turnover
of Pounds 1.42m. Parkdean said margins should improve as the Cherry Tree
park benefited from its supplier discounts and cost controls.
The site trades for a shorter season than Parkdean's other sites, Mr Wilson
said, and could be added to the group's central marketing operation with
little extra cost.
Buying it now would give the group the benefit of current year trading, he
said, and enable Parkdean to assess the site in time to print its 1995
brochure.
The acquisition will be funded by debt, taking gearing to about 30 per cent
at the year end, Mr Wilson said.
The group repeated its view of cautious optimism for the current year with
Easter satisfactory, but reservations for the peak season were following the
trend for later holiday bookings.
</TEXT>
