<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / National Power drives annual payout up 18%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
National Power, the UK's biggest electricity generator, yesterday shrugged
off a sharp decline in market share to increase its dividend by a higher
than expected 18 per cent. Pre-tax profits for the year to March 27 advanced
9 per cent to Pounds 632m, excluding a Pounds 45m exceptional gain.
The announcement sets the tone for what is likely to be an impressive
results season for electricity companies in England and Wales.
PowerGen, the other large generator, is expected to at least match its
rival's dividend growth when it unveils results on June 9. The regional
distribution companies may be slightly more restrained ahead of a regulatory
review of their prices in the summer, but are expected to increase dividends
by well into double figures in percentage terms.
National Power increased its final dividend to 8.75p (7.3p) to make a total
of 12.5p, against 10.6p. It confirmed plans to reduce dividend cover from
three times earnings to 2.5 times. Earnings per share before exceptionals
were 37.3p, against 32.9p.
Analysts upgraded forecasts for this year's dividend with, for example,
Kleinwort Benson pencilling in 14.6p instead of 14.4p, and SG Warburg
Securities moving to 14.5p from 14.3p.
Mr John Baker, chief executive, said the effect of the recent cap on prices
in the electricity trading pool would be 'less than material'.
National Power's pre-tax profits of Pounds 677m (Pounds 580m) included a
Pounds 45m exceptional gain related to pensions. Turnover fell 16 per cent
to Pounds 3.64bn (Pounds 4.35bn).
The company said it had reduced coal stocks by 7m tonnes to 12m tonnes and
cut jobs in the UK from 7,400 to fewer than 6,000.
It was about to start work on its fourth and largest combined cycle gas
station at Didcot, Oxfordshire. The 1,400MW project is likely to be followed
by a fifth at Staythorpe, Nottinghamshire, which would take the company's
CCGT capacity to 5,000MW by the end of the decade.
National Power emphasised its plans for overseas expansion following moves
last year into the US and Portugal. American National Power contributed
Pounds 1m after interest. Mr Baker said overseas profits would be more than
10 per cent of the group total by the end of the decade.
Last year UK market share fell from 41 to 35 per cent. The company expects
the level to stabilise at about 30 per cent.
Lex, Page 24;
Awaiting clarification, Page 26
