<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / British Gas ventures out of the comfort zone: A shift in
international plans
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT CORZINE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The sale of British Gas's 53 per cent share of Bow Valley, the Canadian oil
and gas company, for Pounds 348m is the latest evidence of a radical shift
in international strategy in one of the world's largest integrated gas
companies.
The Bow Valley sale comes just six months after British Gas announced its
intention to sell an 85 per cent stake in Consumers Gas - the main
distributor of natural gas to the domestic market of Toronto - to
Interprovincial Pipe Line System for CDollars 1.2bn (Pounds 570m).
Regulatory approval for that sale is expected this summer.
The two sales effectively end what some executives termed the 'commonwealth'
phase of the company's internationalisation. It was characterised by a focus
on countries such as Canada and New Zealand, where a shared language and
common legal system offered a high 'comfort factor' to a company just
emerging from privatisation in 1986, and seeking to reduce dependence on the
regulated British market.
Critics, however, claimed that in practice it meant British Gas paying
'first division prices for second division assets'.
For some the wisdom of the strategy seemed to be borne out by British Gas's
abortive attempt to enter Spain, a fast-growing market but one in which
national companies were determined to remain dominant. But the strategy's
weakness was that it offered few growth opportunities and little scope to
add value to the operations, the main explanation for the sale last year of
Consumers.
In addition, the Canadian businesses tied up large amounts of capital when
opportunities to apply the company's expertise were opening up in
high-growth regions such as Asia.
Mr Cedric Browne, chief executive, yesterday confirmed that the Bow Valley
sale 'forms part of the review of our activities. It is consistent with the
policy of focusing on international markets where we see the greatest growth
potential.'
The new international emphasis will be spelled out in detail in the
company's strategic review, expected to be completed within the next few
months. It is likely to include a shake-up of British Gas's international
structure, which is divided between exploration and production of gas and
oil, and Global Gas, which focuses on downstream operations such as
pipelines, distribution and power generation.
It is also expected to re-affirm its intention to become the world's first
'gas major', operating in much the same way as the oil majors. But it is
likely to put a priority on developing gas-related businesses in regions
where it sees the highest growth potential.
These include Asia, where it is involved in gas-fired power generation
projects in Indonesia and Malaysia and a planned gas distribution system for
Bombay.
The southern cone of Latin America will probably be another priority area.
British Gas already has 29 per cent of MetroGas, the Buenos Aires gas
distribution network, and a 45 per cent shareholding in a power generation
project. It is also part of a consortium studying the feasibility of piping
gas from Argentina over the Andes mountains to Chile.
The company is known to be keen to expand its role in building, owning and
operating gas-fired power plants, a sector which is expected to grow
strongly. Earlier this week it took a 51 per cent stake in the US-based Gas
Ventures Advisers, a company it helped set up in 1991 to identify investment
opportunities in large-scale power projects.
Europe remains a desirable area for expansion, but the dominance of state
monopolies offers limited scope outside the emerging markets of central and
eastern Europe.
                            *      *      *
MAIN OVERSEAS STAKES:
29 percent of MetroGas, distribution, Buenos Aires, Argentina. Pounds 55m in
1992.  Also Central Dock Sud, power generation. Pounds 16m in 1993
36.5 per cent of Natural Gas Clearinghouse, gas marketing, Houston, Texas,
Pounds 39m in 1992.
25 per cent of a gas distribution company in Leipzig and 5 per cent of an
eastern German transmission concern.  Pounds 12m in 1991.
Ballylumford power station, Northern Ireland, Pounds 130m in 1992.
MAIN INVESTMENTS IN EXPLORATION AND PRODUCTION:
Miskar Field, off Tunisia.  Reserves estimated at 1 trillion cu ft. Total
Pounds 497m.
Karachaganak oil and gas field, Kazakhstan.  Reserves estimated at 20
trillion cu ft.  With AGIP of Italy.  Up to Pounds 5bn.
Dolphin field, off Trinidad.  Reserves of 2-3 trillion cu ft. Partnership
with Texaco.
</TEXT>
