<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / Court fines Ralph Lauren for copying rival's design: Yves
Saint-Laurent claims victory is important step for fashion world
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Yves Saint-Laurent, the French fashion house, yesterday set a new trend in
the industry by winning FFr2m (Pounds 230,000) damages in a Paris commercial
court after suing Ralph Lauren, the leading US fashion designer, for copying
one of its dress designs.
It is commonplace in the fashion trade for leading designers such as
Saint-Laurent and Ralph Lauren, to sue counterfeiters, or 'knock-off
merchants', at the lower end of the business. But this is the first case of
its kind involving two such prestigious names.
The case, conducted with all the drama of the fashion world, concerns a
black tuxedo dress sold in 1992 by Ralph Lauren's boutiques which
Saint-Laurent claimed was copied from one of his 1970 designs.
Mr Pierre Berge, chairman of Saint-Laurent, was fined FFr500,000 yesterday
by the same court after Ralph Lauren complained about allegedly defamatory
remarks he made concerning the case in Women's Wear Daily, the US fashion
trade magazine. Ms Francine Summa, Saint-Laurent's lawyer, said after the
hearing that Mr Berge 'would have been better off keeping his mouth shut'.
Yet the Saint-Laurent camp's disappointment at that defeat was dwarfed by
its glee over its triumph in the main case. 'We're very satisfied with the
outcome,' said Mr Christophe Girard, company secretary. 'It's an important
step for us and the entire industry.'
The drama of the tuxedo dress began in late 1992 when Saint-Laurent's
lawyers spotted a magazine picture of a Ralph Lauren dress which was similar
to the 1970 design that the French designer had reinterpreted for his autumn
1992 collections.
Counterfeiting is a serious problem for the leading fashion houses of Paris,
Milan and New York, all of which have assembled heavyweight legal teams to
crack down on illegal copies of their designs and trademarks. Saint-Laurent
spends around FFr50m a year fighting counterfeiting. Chanel, another French
house, is believed to spend FFr30m.
However, the black tuxedo case is the first to have raised the sensitive
subject of designer 'copy-catting' in the law courts. Until now, designers
have balked at taking legal action over such issues because of the
difficulty of proving that one design was actually copied from another.
Ms Madeleine Cotelle, the judge in the black tuxedo case, summoned models
wearing the Saint-Laurent and Lauren designs to her courtroom so she could
inspect them.
Ralph Lauren declined to comment on yesterday's ruling. It said it would
wait until the judge's report is published later today before deciding
whether to appeal.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Yves Saint-Laurent Groupe.
    Polo Ralph Lauren Corp.
</CO>
