<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / The Lex Column: National Power
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
International diversification by privatised UK utilities has received a bad
name. That is why National Power is rather coy about its overseas investment
plans. Though its public goal is to invest Pounds 1bn in international
expansion by the end of the decade, the management's true ambitions are more
extensive. The group would, for example, be prepared to spend Pounds 500m on
a foreign privatisation in addition to the Pounds 1bn, which is earmarked
for green field site investments.
The group's financial strength will permit such investment levels. Net cash
inflow from operations - Pounds 832m during the last financial year - will
rise as economic recovery gathers pace and yet more costs are squeezed out
of the business. Meanwhile, capital expenditure in the UK will bob around at
the current level of Pounds 436m. Without foreign investments, National
Power's gearing of 13 per cent would soon turn into a cash pile. Even if the
whole Pounds 1bn was spent by 1998 and dividends are raised as envisaged,
gearing would still be modest.
Shareholders may feel they would do better if the pay-out was increased
faster than planned or the company bought back its own shares. But it would
be a mistake to tar National Power with the same brush as other utilities
such as BT and British Gas. Its international strategy is more focused. The
opportunities in global power generation look fairly attractive. Moreover,
National Power can already boast one success: American National Power has
contributed to earnings after financing costs in its first year within the
group.
</TEXT>
