<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / The Lex Column: Bass
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
After all that effort Mr Ian Prosser of Bass must be crying into his beer.
Despite his determination to gain market share, beer volume was down
slightly at the interim stage and the company's share of the overall market
went up by only 0.3 percentage points. The cost was a drop in brewing
profits of nearly 7 per cent. Despite a series of one-off factors, there is
no mistaking the remorseless pressure on margins.
The company's response has been to continue cutting costs and to reduce in
relative terms the resources allocated to brewing. Free-trade loans are
being scaled back and brewing is receiving less capital expenditure. But
given the company's position in the market it seems condemned to see out the
beer price war. While Allied-Lyons shares rose 1 per cent yesterday on the
growing conviction that beer need not form part of its long-term strategy,
those of Bass fell nearly 2 per cent on the realisation that as market
leader, it cannot afford to pull out.
That move may be overdone simply on the basis that Bass had already fallen
nearly 5 per cent against the sector so far this month. At least hotels are
doing better, though the extent of the franchise operation limits their
gearing to recovery. Government competition rules give Bass some scope to
expand its pub estate and any sale of the Britvic soft drinks business could
provide the resources further to improve its quality. Brewing looks set to
remain a drag for some time, though. With earnings and dividend growth both
in single figures, there is no reason why its shares should out-perform.
</TEXT>
