<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / The Lex Column: Sizing up the Fed
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Not long ago a half point rise in US interest rates would have provided
secure support for the dollar. The currency's weakness yesterday shows the
Federal Reserve is caught in a painful vice. It might have hoped that the
prospect of a hiatus in rate rises would calm the bond market. Yet on the
other side of the Atlantic financial markets are starting to take note of
Germany's incipient recovery. Notwithstanding yesterday's cut in the
Bundesbank's repurchase rate, the trough in German rates is now expected
earlier. The prospective growth and interest rate differential has moved
back in favour of the D-Mark.
A weak dollar, though, is hardly a tonic for US bonds. Coupled with the fear
that the Fed may still tighten further if the recovery remains robust, that
thought was enough to reverse the initial satisfaction with which markets
greeted Tuesday night's apparently decisive move. There can be no certainty
that US rates have stopped rising until the economy has clearly slowed. Even
then higher short-term rates may be needed to prop up the dollar and
encourage overseas funds back into Treasury bonds.
Such a prospect holds little comfort for global equities which remain in the
shadow of bonds. Only in continental Europe, which is further behind in the
cycle, is there much support left to come from earnings recovery. The UK
market must be feeling increasingly uncomfortable after yesterday's earnings
data. The Fed's example shows how difficult it is for central banks to
manage the turn in rates.
</TEXT>
