<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / Leading Article: Privatise the Post Office
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Even Baroness Thatcher baulked at the idea in the 1980s, yet the case for
privatising the UK Post Office is now overwhelming. Sensitive social and
political issues are at stake. But by comparison with those involved in
transferring the water and telecommunications industries into the private
sector, they are far from difficult to resolve, while the potential benefits
are considerable.
By international standards the Royal Mail has an impressive performance
record. It none the less suffers from the worst afflictions of the old
nationalised industries. Its capital spending and pricing are subject to
detailed ministerial control. It is milked as a cash cow by the government
with little regard to the long-term health of the business. This year it has
been set an arbitrary target to pay the government Pounds 230m, a sum higher
than the Post Office's current post-tax profit and nearly twice as much as a
reasonable dividend payment. Meanwhile, capital investment languishes and
the price of stamps is higher than it need otherwise have been.
Restrictions on the Post Office competing with the private sector, and
engaging in overseas ventures, threaten its future as anything more than a
house-to-house deliverer of paper protected by monopoly. The Dutch postal
service is about to be privatised; it is at the forefront of new
communications technologies and is selling hard in the UK, alongside a host
of private operators. The distinction between mail, telecoms and computing
is already blurred; within a few years it will be archaic.
Commercial freedom
To flourish, the Post Office needs entrepreneurial and commercial freedom.
In theory, that could be guaranteed within the state sector; in practice the
UK has never managed to make such a half-way house habitable. Privatisation
is the sensible way forward - accompanied by an obligation to deliver
letters daily across the country; by a continued monopoly over deliveries up
to a certain weight or value; by a regulator to protect consumer interests;
and by accounting separation to prevent the Post Office subsidising
non-monopoly operations from monopoly revenues.
To reassure consumers, the government might retain a 51 per cent stake in
the company and nominate a number of directors. The crucial decision is to
proceed to market; the proportion of the share capital to be floated is of
secondary importance. If the privatisation of BT is any guide, consumers
will soon be better off, not worse off. And not just as a result of
technology: there are nearly twice as many pay phones as a decade ago, and
they now work.
Understandable concern
That leaves the thorny issue of post offices - the 'counters' division of
the Royal Mail. There is understandable concern at the prospect of wholesale
closures among the UK's 20,000 post offices, the bulk of them sub-post
offices run as subsidised private businesses under contract.
Sub-post offices remain vital for rural communities and for benefits
recipients without bank accounts. In the short term, therefore, subsidies
should continue - both those in the form of cash paid to the franchisees,
and those in the form of agency work protected by the government (notably
benefits payments). Yet the point of principle is clear: post offices should
service social needs. As ever more pensioners and benefits recipients come
to possess their own bank accounts, the losers from a decision not to credit
payments directly into bank accounts will be taxpayers and the recipients
themselves.
However, only the faint-hearted should suppose that small post offices can
survive by subsidy alone. With privatisation should go a bonfire of the
senseless controls which forbid post offices from offering banking and other
private sector services under contract. In partnership with a bank, the
Dutch post office's outlets transact mortgages, offer banking, travel and
recruitment services, and more besides.
Britain's post offices could do a thriving private trade, particularly in
rural areas without banks or other services. If supermarkets are free to
sell stamps bearing the Queen's head, there is no earthly reason why post
offices should not be able to sell concert tickets and issue cash from bank
accounts.
</TEXT>
<XX>
