<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / Leading Article: Derivatives in the dock
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Legislators in the US Congress have long been worried that trading in
derivative financial instruments such as swaps, futures and options might
confront them with another financial crisis to match the hugely expensive
savings and loan fiasco. Yesterday's report on derivatives from the General
Accounting Office (GAO) will no doubt strengthen their resolve to control
such trading. Yet the report's conclusion that there is a need for
substantial tightening of the regulatory system in relation to derivatives
runs counter to the more reassuring verdict of an authoritative, earlier
report by the Group of 30, an influential banking think-tank. Are the
politicians overreacting?
The dramatic growth in derivatives trading and the losses recently recorded
by such companies as Metallgesellschaft Kashima Oil, Procter &amp; Gamble and
Atlantic Richfield are unquestionably eye-catching. Yet the risks involved
in these novel financial instruments are the same, in principle, as those in
conventional banking such as credit risk, market risk or liquidity risk. The
differences are of degree.
Derivative instruments are intrinsically leveraged: a small movement in the
underlying cash market can produce a big change in the value of the
derivative. The mathematical complexity of the more exotic instruments calls
for heavy expenditure by banks and companies on appropriate systems and
skills.
Lack of transparency
Properly used, derivatives are a highly effective tool to manage and control
risk. But as the GAO rightly observes, they can be used to assume risk,
notably in proprietary trading, as well as to reduce it. While most central
bankers argue that the probability of a systemic shock is low, they cannot
deny that there is a lack of transparency in the system. The fastest growth
is in over-the-counter trade, not in organised markets. Accounting standards
have been slow to capture the impact of derivative activity both on and off
the balance sheet.
An essential discipline in the system consists of marking derivative
exposures to market value on a daily basis. Yet many of the contracts are
customised for individual institutions and valued on the basis of computer
models incorporating assumptions of varying boldness about the future
relationship between interest rates, currencies and markets. Since the
assumptions rely on past correlations, they can prove wrong.
Such complexity can make a nonsense of traditional checks and balances.
Losses incurred by a leading trader at Kidder Peabody, for example, went
unnoticed by his fellow traders, the back office, senior management and
auditors. Too often the trader's pay is related to a performance period
shorter than the duration of the derivative contracts. Most players in the
game are relying heavily on the monitoring provided by credit rating
agencies and regulators, who are not infallible.
Cross-infection
The threat to the global banking system stems from the possibility that in
this opaque trading world banks will make poor credit assessments of
counterparties who take lethal trading risks. The GAO emphasises that, in an
increasingly integrated and concentrated market, the investment banks' and
insurers' mis-assessment of risk in derivatives could be as dangerous for
the system as that of the commercial banks. Also that cross-infection in a
global market will be hard to contain.
Anything other than a global approach to regulation will be less than fully
effective. The thrust of supervision should thus continue to be chiefly
through the Basle-based Bank for International Settlements, whose capital
adequacy regime will need constant upgrading in the light of experience of
instruments that are still relatively untested. Yet it is hard to argue with
the GAO's assertion that there are gaps in the domestic US system, in terms
of both data and oversight, which need to be plugged.
The GAO also raises a legitimate concern in questioning whether the present
level of proprietary trading is appropriate in a deposit-insured banking
system subject to a high degree of moral hazard. A comprehensive and
consistent regulatory approach is probably beyond the art of the possible.
But in the absence of that, a piecemeal approach is better than nothing at
all.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
