<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / Favourites of the fraudsters
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Illicit refunds. By pretending to channel food outside the EU while selling
it inside the Union, fraudsters can both gain an export subsidy and
capitalise on higher EU food prices. A favourite method is to forge customs
documents saying food is going to eastern Europe while selling it, for
instance, in Belgium.
Meat carousels. Frozen meat can be shipped between several different
countries to maximise refunds. One shipment of east European beef recently
went from Italy to Malta, back to Italy and then to Austria, with the
refunds gained twice.
Mayonnaise madness. Similar scams work for processed foods such as
mayonnaise or chocolate biscuits. By transporting the items several times in
and out of the Union, traders may be able to over-claim on export refunds
for the raw ingredients such as sugar.
Switched labels. With different categories of food being given different
export subsidies, traders may incorrectly describe specific foodstuffs to
claim higher refunds. This has happened, for instance, with cheese labelled
as Gouda when it was lower-quality cheese ineligible for a refund.
Shrunken stores. Crooks can capitalise on the 'intervention' payments made
to take foodstuffs off the European market. Fraudsters appear to have gained
Ecu200m (Pounds 153m) by invoicing for invisible wheat supposedly put in
Italy's intervention store.
Crop capers. With many crops grown in Europe eligible for subsidies, farmers
may inflate figures for the amount of land under cultivation with a
particular crop. This practice is believed to have been rife in the Greek
cotton industry.
Animal antics. Farmers may be tempted to give higher numbers for their
livestock than exist to claim larger subsidies. The Commission is attempting
to counter this with a computerised database of European cows.
Crooked roads. Substantial sums earmarked for infrastructure programmes may
have been diverted to fraudsters through false invoicing or money being paid
out for projects which never finished.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>QRZ  European Economic Community (EC).
</CN>
