<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / A labyrinth of loopholes: There will be no easy victory in
the EU's war against fraud in the payment of subsidies and grants
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
To many people, the European Union represents not fraternal partnership, but
fingers in the till. Now, as the fraud bill mounts, Europe is getting tough.
At a meeting in Brussels of EU finance ministers this week, Mr Peter
Schmidhuber, the Union's budget commissioner, spelt out measures to stem the
flow of cash being wasted through fraud and other financial irregularities.
This is officially put at Ecu343m (Pounds 264m) last year, 63 per cent up on
1992, but is thought by many experts to be at least 10 times higher at about
5 per cent of the EU's annual Ecu70bn budget.
The full extent of the financial deception is difficult to calculate. But
the evident scale of the problem - often the result of loopholes in
labyrinthine EU spending rules - is triggering mounting concern in finance
ministries across Europe.
Nowhere is the angst felt more keenly than in Germany, the largest
contributor to EU funds. Reacting to public concern in this election year
that large amounts of this money are being wasted, Mr Theo Waigel, Germany's
finance minister, has signalled that Bonn will take a tough line on EU fraud
when it takes over the Union's presidency on July 1.
Mr Per Brix Knudsen, a tough-talking Dane who heads Uclaf, the Commission's
anti-fraud unit, sums up Brussels thinking: 'The image that the European
Union is prone to fraud is used increasingly to discredit Union policies. We
must put more effort into protecting the EU's financial interests.'
Mr Knudsen is spearheading efforts to reduce the losses, including a
doubling in the staff of Uclaf (the word is a French acronym) from 50 to 100
by the end of the year. He is setting up a telephone hotline on which
members of the public across Europe can report instances of fraud in
confidence. The Commission is also on course to finalise by June 1 a package
of 'administrative sanctions' which would empower member states to impose
fines on companies and individuals suspected of misappropriating EU cash
before there has been any resort to court proceedings.
Mr Knudsen is not alone in his efforts. The Luxembourg-based Court of
Auditors, the EU's main financial watchdog, has acquired new powers to take
legal action against the Commission and member states if it thinks they are
failing to act against fraud. Although he admits he faces an uphill
struggle, Mr Andre Middelhoek, the Dutch president of the court, promises to
be 'blunt and undiplomatic' in attributing responsibility. 'None of the
member states are keen enough' to tackle fraud, he says.
Instrumental in bringing the problem to the attention of member states has
been Professor Klaus Tiedemann, a criminologist at Freiburg University in
Germany who has studied pan-European abuse of government money for 20 years.
According to Prof Tiedemann, between 7 per cent and 10 per cent of the
Union's budget is wasted through fraud and improper exploitation of
loopholes. He bases his figures on detailed inquiries into sectors such as
agricultural goods, iron and steel, and social funds - all of which receive
EU subsidies and other funding. Prof Tiedemann admits his overall figure is
a 'guesstimate', but it is one viewed as broadly correct by other experts.
Commission staff admit the amount of fraud is higher than the published
figure, but say the full extent is impossible to assess accurately.
According to Uclaf, EU frauds worth Ecu976m were reported between 1990 and
1993. Of this, nearly half - Ecu446m - involved funds spent in Italy.
Germany accounted for Ecu204m, France Ecu97m, Britain Ecu85m, Belgium
Ecu32m, Greece Ecu29m and the Netherlands Ecu25m.
The reason most commonly given for the scale of the problem is the EU's
complex rules for administering subsidies, especially to farmers. This
funding accounts for half the budget despite attempts to reform the Common
Agricultural Policy.
With an estimated 3m farm-related cash transactions a year eligible either
for a direct payment to a farmer or an 'export refund' to a company
processing or transporting food, the opportunities for financial abuse are
immense. Various methods are used, some sophisticated, others touching on
farce (see box).
For instance, prosecutors in Rotterdam have started proceedings against a
gang of six arrested last year on suspicion of routing 120 lorry loads of
sugar, supposedly meant for Croatia and Slovenia, to Italy. By forging
customs documents, the gang - based in France, Italy and the Netherlands -
allegedly dodged duties worth about Ecu1.8m.
In the UK, two brothers, both farmers, inflated the number of sheep they
owned from 18 to 180, so gaining a higher EU subsidy. By repeatedly
pretending to be each other, the brothers sidestepped for some time
inquiries from the UK's Ministry of Agriculture. Ultimately they were taken
to court and fined a total of Pounds 6,000.
In another case, two cattle dealers based in Northern Ireland were jailed in
1992 for having made about Pounds 20m from smuggling 22,000 cattle backwards
and forwards across the border into the Republic of Ireland. They arranged
the transfers to tie in with shifts in the pound/punt exchange rate and so
exploit EU subsidies linked to currency movements.
More recently, the Italian authorities arrested a gang in southern Italy for
allegedly defrauding the EU of up to Ecu200m by gaining payment for wheat
which they claimed was in EU commodity warehouses but which, it appears, may
not have existed. The case is in the early stages of prosecution.
In another case, fraudsters in Rome and Naples are alleged by the Commission
to have claimed Ecu22m over several years by pretending to arrange
non-existent training programmes.
Many observers cite the lack of incentives (such as a significant financial
reward) for member states to report irregularities as a second reason why
fraud is rife. In some cases, there may even be disincentives to report
irregularities: EU subsidies, whether gained legally or not, may be playing
an important part in stimulating the economies of poorer regions.
A third reason, according to Mr Malcolm Levitt, a former EU official who is
now European adviser at Barclays Bank, is that the Commission has a
'collegial' culture with too few people taking responsibility for financial
controls.
As to which countries are most lax on fighting fraud, Commission officials
have been reluctant to assign blame. However, the mood in Brussels is
beginning to change, with a growing inclination to name countries suspected
of being less than diligent in this area. In the vanguard of this trend is
Germany, the EU's biggest paymaster with a net contribution in 1992 of
DM22bn (Pounds 8.8bn), a figure likely to grow to DM30bn by 1997, according
to Bundesbank forecasts.
With the country facing a DM112bn budget deficit this year (about 3.5 per
cent of gross domestic product), Chancellor Helmut Kohl's coalition
government is under pressure to tackle any waste of money by Brussels. In
this, Bonn has found allies in Netherlands and Denmark, as well as the UK
government. Mr Waigel discussed the need to raise awareness of EU fraud with
Mr Kenneth Clarke, the UK chancellor, last month.
While German government officials are reluctant to name those countries most
prone to fraud, Prof Tiedemann says 'empirical studies over the past decade
have shown southern member states to be more inclined to fraud than those in
the north'. Mr Peter Price, a British Tory member of the European Parliament
and a former chairman of its budgetry control committee, singles out Italy
and Greece.
Such observations, though echoing fraud experts, touch a nerve with the
countries named. An Italian government official responds that Italy takes
'an extremely serious' view of fraud, while a Greek government official
says: 'These comments are not borne out by statistics.'
A less restrained approach to discussing the problem is one way of
highlighting it. As for practical steps, Mr Schmidhuber is pressing for
closer co-operation between the Commission's fraud unit, Uclaf, and national
police and customs forces. Many of the 50 newcomers to Uclaf will be former
police or customs officers skilled in tracking international criminals. The
unit is currently co-ordinating investigations into between 30 and 70
large-scale European frauds.
Over the next few years, Uclaf may be helped by a shift in the pattern of EU
farm payments. By the end of the decade, according to Mr Brian Gardner, of
the Brussels-based farm consultancy EPA Associates, 80 per cent of the
payments - twice the current proportion - will go straight to farmers, and
only 20 per cent to companies processing or transporting food. He believes
the new system should be easier for the police because keeping track of
payments to fixed establishments such as farms should be simpler than
tracking payments to companies moving goods around Europe.
Despite these initiatives and the assertive mood in Brussels, the anti-fraud
effort faces several constraints. Today's enthusiasm may quickly give way to
ennui. One sceptic is Ms Annemarie Goedmakers, a Dutch socialist MEP and
member of the budgetry control committee, who says Brussels is putting on a
'big show' of talking tough about fraud but has not been resolute enough in
tackling it.
Other sceptics doubt the Court of Auditors has a suitably efficient
structure to identify the main perpetrators of fraud. Court policies are set
by 12 officials - one from each member state - who meet each Thursday, and
who may have different degrees of enthusiasm about following up specific
instances of alleged fraud. The court's reports (which never name parties
allegedly involved in fraud) are felt by some observers to lack the cutting
edge of, for instance, the General Accounting Office in Washington, which
monitors US government spending.
In addition, many frauds are inherently complex and difficult to prosecute -
especially given the current lack of harmony in anti-fraud legislation
across the EU. At present only about 10 per cent of the EU frauds reported
each year end up in the courts, and few observers expect the figure to rise
significantly.
All these difficulties suggest the EU's fraud fight is likely to be won only
slowly. Few insiders think there are merits in devising grandiose
initiatives - such as a pan-European police squad concerned with fraud  -
which could lead to a duplication of efforts and antagonise member states.
As EU officials contemplate what to do about fraud, the uncomfortable
thought occurs that the planned enlargement of the Union - Austria, Finland,
Norway and Sweden are lined up for entry next year - may make matters still
worse. The entry of these nations, whatever their commitment to fighting
fraud, will increase the complexity of the methods needed to decide and
supervise EU subsidies. Unless effective action is agreed soon to combat
irregular payments, what one observer calls the 'black hole' down which
money is now disappearing could soon develop into a chasm.
</TEXT>
