<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / Observer: Out of Africa
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Things don't get better for the African Development Bank. Weighed down by
arrears, its recent AGM ended in a shambles. Now the regional development
bank has lost its treasurer, Kofi Bucknor, to Lehman Brothers.
A skilled negotiator and a fine ambassador for the bank, Bucknor apparently
became disenchanted when he was not made chief financial officer - a post
that has been vacant for some time - and for which he seemed perfectly well
qualified.
'So he has auctioned himself to the highest bidder,' as one banker put it -
even if Bucknor, a scion of one of Ghana's leading families, is not exactly
short of a bob or two. Moving to London, he will head up Lehman's African
investment banking operation.
James Ranaivoson, a Madagascan who previously worked for the Caisse des
Depots, the state-controlled French financial institution, is his most
likely replacement. With the AfDB suffering losses that could imperil its
very survival, the new man won't be bored.
