<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / Observer: Party pals
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The death of John Smith has not quelled talk of a leadership crisis in the
Tory party. Michael Heseltine's odds have lengthened sharply and Kenneth
Clarke's reputation remains in the doldrums. Indeed, the prospect of young
Tony Blair taking Labour into the next election has added to the Tory
turmoil.
Current wisdom has it that if Labour opts for Blair, then Michael Portillo's
chances will be greatly improved. Portillo is three weeks younger than Blair
and he has served in the cabinet, for what that's worth.
But another name is now being floated by MPs on the centre-left of the party
who can't abide Portillo's Euro-scepticism. Stephen Dorrell, 42, tipped to
enter the cabinet in the summer reshuffle, is being promoted as the man most
likely to beat the fresh-faced Blair.
Only problem is that most voters would find it hard to distinguish one
ex-public schoolboy from the other. The social democrat Blair and the
One-Nation Tory Dorrell tend to agree with each other more often than they
do with rivals in their own parties.
