<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / Letters to the Editor: Emphasis on Russian inflation
misplaced
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr JEFF SCHUBERT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, As an economist and business analyst I spent a large proportion of 1992
and 1993 in Russia examining business opportunities. In April this year I
was asked by a major international bank to return to Russia and undertake a
detailed examination of a Russian regional bank.
The Russian bank was a well-run commercial entity, but there were two
significant problems in analysing its financial position and its general
business operations. The first was inflation which had rendered much of the
accounting information almost meaningless. The other was the bank's poor and
doubtful debt position, partly inherited from its days as part of a larger
state-owned bank, which was barely provisioned for.
Of these two problems, inflation was by far the easiest to account for. In
considering the future of this bank and its suitability for foreign equity
investment, I was more concerned about the ability of the bank's clients to
keep producing and selling goods and thus service the debt.
The clients' position echoed my experience in 1993 when I investigated the
possibility of investing in a Russian wool mill, supplying it with wool and
selling the resultant fabric in Russia. Inflation made estimation of
production costs and selling prices difficult. However, it was not inflation
that ultimately prevented the project from going ahead, but the potential
foreign investors' fears that the weakening economy would mean insufficient
demand for the fabric.
In my experience, the preoccupation of such institutions as the IMF and of
many Russian officials with reducing inflation is misplaced. The inability
of Russian enterprises to pay their debts and keep producing is the greatest
risk to the economy, the reform process and foreign investment.
Jeff Schubert,
137 Macquarie St,
Sydney,
Australia
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>AUZ  Australia.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
