<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / Letters to the Editor: The value of valid tests
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr HERBERT M. GREENBERG
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, I read with great interest your Recruitment article, 'Laying down the
laws of selection' (May 4). There are three kinds of psychological tests
that should not be used by industry for selecting new personnel or
evaluating existing employees. These are tests that have been constructed to
appear psychological, but have no validity; computer-produced tests that
have no relevance to job functions; and tests developed for clinical use.
None of these has real value in predicting job performance.
There are, on the other hand, good psychological tests that have proven
ability in predicting performance. Such tests will have a sound theoretical
basis, have developed a valid database over the long term, and will have
been periodically adjusted to account for changing business cultures. Also,
they will be evaluated by professional occupational psychologists matching
the test results to the functional requirements of the specific job.
It is management's responsibility to invest extra effort to select only the
valid tests. Not using scientifically proven and valid psychological tests
to help make those all-important hiring, promotion or job-shift decisions is
like refusing to use a word processor in favour of the traditional quill
pen.
Herbert M. Greenberg,
Caliper Managementi,
741 Mt. Lucas Road,
Princeton, New Jersey
</TEXT>
<XX>
