<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / Letters to the Editor: Fall in prep boarders due to parental
preference
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr CHARLES GREGSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, While John Authers is correct that cost is a major factor in the
decline in numbers of boarders at independent schools, reported by ISIS last
month ('Sums don't add up', May 13), another equally important factor is the
increasing reluctance of parents to send their children (particularly in the
seven-to-13 age group) to boarding schools. This accounts for the small rise
in day pupils and the large drop in boarder numbers revealed by the ISIS
report.
Furthermore, there is a shortage, certainly in London, of independent day
schools with good facilities. The small increase in day pupils may therefore
be a function of supply rather than lack of demand. A drop in fees by
boarding preparatory schools and a substantial improvement in the economy
will then not halt the decline in the number of children attending boarding
preparatory schools.
Charles Gregson,
30 Norland Square,
London W11 4PU
</TEXT>
