<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / Letters to the Editor: Rethink needed on investment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr CHRIS OUTRAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Hanson's decision to increase its investment pay-back period highlights
the need for a much more sophisticated approach to investment by many UK
companies.
UK companies typically demand excessively high internal investment returns -
often twice the real cost of capital. We have found that those with the
lowest discount rates and good financial control of their business have seen
the greatest growth in profitability and shareholder value. Conversely,
those with the highest rates frequently face competitive problems in large
parts of their portfolios as profitable growth opportunities are
under-exploited and rivals are allowed to attack positions of strength.
For many American companies, investment appraisal techniques and hurdle
rates are a fundamental, explicitly-stated part of their communicated
strategy. This contrasts with the reluctance of UK companies to talk about
investment strategy in other than the most general and generic terms. Costs
of capital, discount rates and investment criteria need to be reviewed
regularly by the chief executive, the CFO and the board, with key underlying
assumptions clearly set out and debated, not delegated to 'technicians'
within the finance function.
Hanson's announcement recognises this, but may also signal a more general
shift by companies from an acquisition and short-term cashflow-focused
environment to one that needs to be more reliant on investment-driven
organic growth. The challenge will be to convince the investment community
that such companies possess the management style and skills required to
succeed in this new world.
Chris Outram,
chairman,
OC&amp;C Strategy Consultants,
One Embankment Place,
Villiers Street,
London WC2N 6NN
</TEXT>
