<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / Letters to the Editor: Objective about BS5750
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From TF DOUGHERTY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
I have been intrigued by the recent interest in BS5750 in your pages, and I
would like to offer the following advice.
Those considering BS5750 should be aware of any benefit likely to accrue to
their customers.
If the customer is not going to perceive any noticeable difference, then
don't bother - there will undoubtedly be other more deserving challenges.
If you believe the customer is going to benefit, you must decide 'by how
much' and fix a means of measurement, to determine what you intend to
achieve and so you will know when you have got there. At this point, you can
identify a positive impact upon the bottom line - all well and good - and
you certainly should think about the cost of developing, implementing and
maintaining the system.
All too often BS5750 fails or disappoints because 'the business' doesn't
approach the task objectively.
Remember, BS5750 is not a quality system: you can have one of those without
the standard.
If you are employing a consultancy 'worth its salt', it will ensure that you
understand the standard before taking a fee. It can then help you to decide
whether or not it is worth going for.
TF Dougherty Associates,
3 Apple Tree Close,
Kidderminster,
Worcs DY10 2SZ
</TEXT>
