FT  19 MAY 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
If we worked out how much money we paid in to building societies for our
mortgages most of us would presumably abandon the system and go for rented
accommodation, or try to raise the money some other way. Taking Liberties
looks into a new wave of re-possessions and tells how building societies are
refusing to honour promises of a multi-million pound mortgage rescue scheme
(8.00 BBC2). Can it really be a good idea for BBC2 to be showing The Lost
Steptoes? It is not the poor technical quality that prompts the question but
the high quality of the writing. It makes today's comedies look so
hopelessly inferior. This week a pregnant woman arrives at the rag and bone
yard claiming that Harold is the father of her child (8.30). True Stories
comes up with yet another of those documentaries in which the programme
makers fail to get an interview with their subject and then try to turn the
absence into a virtue. Today's absentee is Margaret Thatcher who was
followed on her US book promotion tour but avoided and ignored the cameras
at every turn (9.30 C4).
