<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / Arts: Francoise Pollet - Recital
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD FAIRMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A first-class French soprano is like a rare wine. There are historically
very few of them and after a period with none at all, a thirst grows for a
voice that has the characteristic French quality and flavour.
For some years the lack of top French female singers reached drought
proportions, which has made the arrival of Francoise Pollet all the more
welcome. Her operatic career began in Germany in the early 1980s. From the
range of repertoire that she now has under her belt (Strauss's Marschallin,
Wagner's Sieglinde and Berlioz's Dido) it is clear that she is as near as
any French singer has come to being a successor to the much-loved Regine
Crespin.
Her soprano has amplitude, but is still feminine, not a
helmet-and-spear-carrying warrior Valkyrie of a voice. To judge from her
recital at the Wigmore Hall on Wednesday she has less sheer power on board
than Crespin did at her last London appearances there, but Pollet naturally
has youth and flexibility on her side. In Debussy's Baudelaire songs she had
no trouble settling into that sensuous, hedonistic world, where 'sounds and
perfumes turn in the evening air'.
The heavily-scented warmth of her voice is ideally suited to this music,
while Roger Vignoles managed to combine clarity and deep sensuality in the
accompaniments. In her second Debussy group and some of the Wolf it was the
pianist, rather than the singer, who was looking for variety. Once Pollet
has relaxed, sinking into velvety, warmly rounded singing, she is reluctant
to stir herself; throughout a good part of this recital the dynamic range
was unvaried, the words did not tell.
A pair of big songs in the second half will have roused anybody who was
pleasantly slumbering: Wolf's 'Kennst du das Land' and Brahms's 'Von ewiger
Liebe' were conceived on a large scale and Pollet was generous with them,
unstinting in her outpouring of voice. But it was the final group of Duparc
songs that showed the singer back with the repertoire that she could make
her own. In the words of Baudelaire, what Pollet affords are three classic
French qualities: 'luxe, calme, et volupte'.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>FRZ  France, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P7929 Entertainers and Entertainment Groups.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>PEOP  People.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
