<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / Technology: Another try at networks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEOF WHEELWRIGHT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
After a lukewarm reception for Windows NT, which Microsoft hoped would
expand its dominance of desktop computing to the broader field of network
computers, the company will soon release a new version - codenamed Daytona.
This will be a significant improvement on the original version of NT,
introduced last year, which has achieved only modest success in the
client/server market. Demand has been 'much slower than we or anybody
expected,' says Robert Palmer, chief executive of Digital Equipment, one of
NT's strongest supporters in the computer industry.
Daytona will address customer criticisms of the original Windows NT, says
Greg Lobdell, Microsoft's product manager for advanced systems. In
particular, it will reduce the amount of computer memory required. The new
version will also improve the performance of both the desktop and server
versions.
Daytona will enable Microsoft to target the workstation software market,
going head-to-head with Unix, the 'open systems' operating system now owned
by Novell, and the various implementations of Unix developed by Sun
Microsystems, Hewlett-Packard and others.
Lobdell acknowledges that with its first version of Windows NT, Microsoft
failed to position the product clearly: 'Windows NT was the answer, but no
one knew what the question was.' But with the launch of Daytona, Microsoft
will be able to define more clearly the product's role, he says.
The new version has been heavily influenced by feedback from customers. They
criticised the size and performance of the original desktop version of NT
and its poor connectivity to other computers. The performance of standard
Windows applications, and in particular the new Microsoft Office
applications, was deemed too slow.
As well as addressing these problems, Microsoft promises several
improvements in the performance of Windows NT on network 'servers'.
</TEXT>
