<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / Management (Marketing and Advertising): Tequila refines its
image - Mexico's distillers are divided over whether to take their drink
upmarket
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAMIAN FRASER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A battle is raging in Mexico over how to make and market tequila, the potent
cactus-based spirit which Mexicans take neat and often, and with which
Americans make margaritas and other cocktails.
The quarrel is between those who want to produce a high-cost tequila and
market it as a luxury drink akin to cognac or malt whisky, and those who
want to sell it cheaply in bulk around the world. At stake is not just the
future of Mexico's national drink, but an increasingly lucrative export
market.
Tequila was first fermented from the sugar of the blue agave plant that
grows in the valley of Tequila, near the city of Guadalajara, and until
recently was consumed almost entirely in Mexico. But in the last decade
exports have grown healthily, rising from 28.5m litres in 1983 to 47.3m
litres in 1993. Now more than two-thirds of production is exported.
The sudden popularity has led to growing international interest in the
industry. In 1991, International Distillers &amp; Vintners, part of Grand
Metropolitan, took a 45 per cent interest in Grupo Cuervo, the industry
leader. In March Allied-Lyons took control of Sauza Tequila, the second
largest tequila company, when it bought Domecq of Spain. United Distillers,
part of Guinness, has marketing rights with Herradura, a niche producer.
The quarrel in the industry centres on whether sugar cane or equivalents can
be substituted for agave in the fermentation of tequila. Agave takes about
10 years to ripen and must be picked by hand, making it an increasingly
expensive raw material. Bulk producers generally sell tequila fermented from
a mixture of sugar cane (or an equivalent) and agave. Government regulations
currently allow producers to use 51 per cent agave and 49 per cent sugar
cane.
Some of the lesser-known low-cost producers do not meet even this
requirement, according to the Tequila chamber of commerce. These bandit
producers sell their tequila to intermediaries, usually in the United
States, who bottle and brand the drink.
Guillermo Romo, the combative head of Herradura, is leading the fight
against cheap tequila. His tequila is made exclusively from agave, uses
natural rather than artificial yeast, and does not use chemicals that speed
up fermentation. Its premium image has made it one of the fastest-growing
tequilas in Mexico, although it exports little.
Romo wants laws - or enforcement of existing ones - that would require
tequila to be made with 100 per cent agave, and that would prohibit tequila
being sold on to intermediaries who bottle and brand the product. In the
long run, he says, branding and bottling on site is the only way Mexico can
make money out of tequila, and guarantee quality standards.
'Nature's most precious gift to Mexico is the agave,' he says. 'Our
inferiority to the Europeans made us believe we could not produce a superior
product, which is not true.'
Romo successfully blocked all tequila exports in February, after he claimed
that existing law, when interpreted correctly, prohibits unbranded tequila
exports. Since then, exports have been permitted, while Romo's case works
its way through Mexico's courts.
Romo took control of the Tequila chamber of commerce this year, which is
broadly backing his case. Mr Luis Margain, the head of the chamber and legal
director at Herradura, says low-quality unbranded tequila 'will threaten the
rule of national origin of tequila (which makes production exclusive to the
region of Tequila) as it becomes a cheap, commodity product'. He says the
fact that Spain and the Philippines are now making tequila show the dangers.
The industry heavyweights, Jose Cuervo and Sauza, which together account for
the majority of production, say that any abrupt change to the current
regulations would be extremely costly. They argue there is not enough agave
to meet current tequila demand, and prices would rocket if the regulations
were changed.
Furthermore, Sauza and Jose Cuervo believe cheaper tequilas do not damage
the drink's image. Both have several tequila brands and distinguish between
100 per cent and mixed agave products, and between tequilas of different
ages. 'What we have to have is two tequilas living side by side. One for
mixers like margarita and one for high-quality neat products,' says Jorge
Berrueta of Sauza.
There are also powerful interests in favour of non-branded exports. Jorge
Camacho, former head of the Tequila chamber and a Jose Cuervo employer, says
outlawing unbranded exports unilaterally would be unfair to American
companies that have invested heavily in marketing their own brands.
But Romo's fierce attack on the adulteraters of tequila is shaking up the
industry. The large producers appear to favour an eventual prohibition of
non-branded exports, and have set up a regulatory council to verify whether
tequila meets the 51 per cent agave requirement and whether tequila
described as a certain age is indeed that age.
Camacho, who heads the regulatory council, believes that as much as 30 per
cent of commercial tequila does not meet the 51 per cent agave requirement.
He admits that 'if the industry does not respect the norms, then we could
lose our claim as a distinctive product and all of us would suffer'.
</TEXT>
