<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / People: Hughes promoted to Mothercare
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Storehouse is filling the gap left by the departure of Mothercare chief
executive Ann Iverson with Simon Hughes, presently logistics director at
BHS.
Iverson, recruited to Storehouse by former group chief executive David
Dworkin, is leaving next month to join Melville, one of the largest
diversified retailers in the US, as head of Kay-Bee, Melville's toys
division.
Hughes, 45, beat other internal as well as external candidates to the post.
Storehouse said it felt an internal appointment was appropriate in order to
promote stability and continuity in a company which has seen a string of
departures by senior executives in recent years.
He is already known inside Mothercare, as he is heading a project looking at
whether to integrate its distribution chain with that of BHS, which he
reorganised.
Hughes, a father of two teenage daughters, says his style may be different
from that of his predecessor, although the 'open' culture will not change.
'Ann went to Mothercare when it needed to be turned round,' he says. 'I am
going when the need is to build on the work that has been done. My job is to
get all the parts working together.'
Hughes adds that a priority is to ensure the sales staff are 'emotionally
involved' in their jobs, and in the Mothercare brand. 'The service and
emotion has to be there. That's when the brand comes to life.'
Otherwise, his main tasks will be to complete the conversion of the stores
to a new design, and overhauling the supply chain.
Hughes graduated from London University and worked for British Rail before
joining shoe retailers C &amp; J Clark, and then Chaussures Ravel.
He joined BHS in 1985 as a merchandise controller and was appointed to the
board in 1990. His existing responsibilities will be divided between other
BHS directors when he moves to Mothercare.
</TEXT>
