<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / Political Notebook: Economic policy will define Labour's
future
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
There is nothing like a leadership battle. The blend of ideological conflict
and personal rivalries produces a unique chemistry. It is raw politics.
So Labour MPs are looking forward to the party's impending contest with
relish and trepidation. Relish because power is what motivates them - even
the humblest backbench MP has had to fight to get to Westminster.
Trepidation because the forces unleashed in such struggles are difficult to
control.
It is no discredit to Labour that preparations for John Smith's funeral
tomorrow have been accompanied by frenetic behind-the-scenes activity to
choose a successor. Politics abhors a vacuum. But Mr Smith would have
expected his colleagues to show the party has grown up: that it can conduct
its arguments without re-igniting the vicious factionalism of the past.
So far that has been the case. One or two animosities are visible. To say
that Mr Gordon Brown and Mr Robin Cook are not close friends is to be guilty
of serious understatement. But by and large there is little of the corrosive
malice which infected Labour during the late 1970s and early 1980s.
Mr Neil Kinnock, who shifted decisively the party's centre of gravity during
the 1980s, deserves much credit. Mr Smith healed many of the wounds
inflicted during that process.
But if the debate is now more mature, it has not gone away. Labour has still
to decide its future. The left, renamed traditionalists, has not
disappeared. The leadership contest will be a decisive test of the strength
of the modernisers.
The battleground will be the economy. It always is.
Mr Gordon Brown, vying for the modernisers' candidacy with Mr Tony Blair,
has done more than he has been thanked for to prepare the ground for a
credible economic strategy. Either man - and for now Mr Blair is well ahead
 -will build on the foundations.
The tax and spending pledges made at the last general election have been
dropped. Mr Brown has established that his party can no longer tax for the
sake of it. Nationalisation has been removed from Labour's vocabularly.
The new emphasis on private-sector infrastructure projects has implications
far wider than the provision of the odd high-speed rail link. Messrs Brown
and Blair are out to shift the focus from an historic obsession with
ownership to securing agreement on the objectives of policy. Making the
economy work well is more important to the unemployed than soaking the very
rich.
In spite of constant harrying from disgruntled union bosses, Mr Brown has
managed also to switch attention to the supply side of the economy.
Macroeconomic policy has ceased to be seen in terms of crude demand
management. Instead a stable macro-economic framework is offered as an
anchor for education, training and investment policies which would increase
productive capacity.
This fundamental emphasis on the ends, not means, is at the heart of the
modernisers' project. It has an application far beyond economic policy. It
would undercut, for example, Labour's traditional commitment to uniformity
and universality in welfare provision or state education.
But the left has become impatient. Mr Smith gave them a commitment to full
employment and to a national minimum wage. Neither Mr Brown nor Mr Blair
could easily abandon the pledges. But traditionalists now want more. The
battle lines have become blurred - but the constituencies represented by Mr
John Prescott and, to a lesser extent, Mr Cook want an ambitiously
expansionist strategy.
A Labour government should pull the macroeconomic levers to deliver faster
growth. Higher output and incomes and a fall in the jobless total would then
square the eternal circle between tax and spending.
Mr Prescott is unimpressed by his rivals' respect for Treasury spending and
borrowing rules or for their willingness to play by the government's
exchange rate rules. Look what happened when Labour backed the Tories on
membership of the European exchange rate mechanism. Mr Cook is no friend of
the City. He sees the potential for an interventionist role in fighting the
British disease of short-termism.
The left wants Labour to lift its sights and inspire the electorate.
Promising to run the economy by Tory rules will not deliver a Labour
government. And should not the unions, the social partners, have a bigger
say?
Other important arguments will have to be played out over the next few
weeks: over the party's institutional links with the unions, over Europe,
over the welfare state.
But the issue which will define the contest is the economy. The party's
choice as leader will in turn define the ground on which it fights, and wins
or loses, the general election.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
