<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / Council spending on IT attacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Local authorities in England and Wales are spending almost twice as much as
they need to on information technology, the Audit Commission claims in a
report published today.
Annual spending of Pounds 290m on IT central functions such as the council
tax and the payroll could be cut by Pounds 130m, according to the
government's public spending watchdog. It says savings of Pounds 50m are
available in the short term. These are the biggest proportionate public
sector savings the commission has identified since it was set up 10 years
ago.
The report says that local government reorganisation, intended to take place
in 1996 and 1997, could add to costs with the increase in tasks. Failure to
prepare for the changes has put services 'at risk'.
The commission looked at seven core functions which require broadly
comparable information technology sys-tems for all councils: council tax,
national non-domestic rates, housing repairs, housing rents, housing
benefits, payroll and payments. Some authorities paid twice as much for
these systems as others.
The report does not cover the Pounds 210m that councils spend on information
technology for services such as planning and education, because these are
harder to compare and quantify.
Mr Bob Chilton, director of local government studies for the commission,
said that substantial savings could also be made in these areas. 'The
overriding issue is that users must take control,' he said. 'Providers have
dominated, and users have found it difficult to negotiate price or content.
Users have treated IT as a free good, because it's not on their budget.'
Many systems are under-utilised, or include functions that are never used,
he said, and most councils still treated IT as a separate central function.
The commission wants decisions on IT spending delegated to users, such as
education departments and direct service organisations.
It believes that compulsory competitive tendering for councils' IT
departments, which will be enforced for English metropolitan councils next
year, could help.
This will force individual departments to outline precise specifications of
their needs, it says, and eliminate waste.
Local authority organisations accepted the report's findings, which they
said would help to identify overspending. The Labour-controlled Association
of County Councils said, however, that the 'significant upheaval and cost'
of reorganisation would jeopardise any benefits.
High Risk/High Potential: An Executive Report on the Management of
Information Technology in Local Government. HMSO. Pounds 6.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
