<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / Tories rapped by Halifax chief
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The chief executive of Halifax building society yesterday attacked the
government's housing policy and called for new forms of subsidy to promote
choice.
In a speech that contrasted Tory commitment to choice with the absence of
policies likely to achieve this in housing, Mr Mike Blackburn, Halifax
chief, argued there was a need for a better-targeted subsidy for
owner-occupation; more support for the private rented sector; and a mix of
subsidies for people on lower incomes.
He said support for people on lower incomes should be available both to
those buying and renting.
Addressing the annual Building Society Association conference in Birmingham,
Mr Blackburn said the government should not reduce mortgage tax relief any
further unless it was replaced with a subsidy that was more closely directed
to particular needs.
He cited the example of other countries that targeted tax relief by making
it available for a limited time only, or to families with children.
It was not satisfactory for the government to try to create a level playing
field by withdrawing all subsidies.
'It may have a certain simplicity and rightwing intellectual appeal, but it
is not a way of managing housing policy in an advanced country - in many
ways it is an abdication by government of its responsibilities for housing
policy,' said Mr Blackburn.
The kickstart needed to assist the private rented sector could be directed
either at encouraging the small landlord or promoting investment by
institutional funds through some form of tax-free investment trust.
He also criticised cuts made in the housing association grant and the
apparent short-term approach of government policymaking.
Mr Blackburn's approach was backed by Mr Tim Melville-Ross, chief executive
of Nationwide, the second-largest society.
Ms Sheila McKechnie, director of Shelter, the housing charity, also attacked
the government for its 'irresponsible policy' of promoting home ownership
across all classes, and called for changes in the tax and benefit systems.
</TEXT>
