<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / Company anger at results penalties
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Companies House, the government's corporate information depository, is still
receiving more than 1,000 calls a week about its late-filing penalty regime,
Andrew Jack writes.
It has handled 65,000 disputes since the regime was introduced in July 1992,
Mr David Durham, chief executive, told the Commons committee on the
parliamentary commissioner for administration.
Mr Durham admitted that the volume of calls and letters was greater than the
levels he had anticipated.
Mr William Reed, the parliamentary commissioner - or ombudsman - said he had
completed examinations of two cases concerning Companies House in 1993 and a
further six were still under investigation.
His report on one case - which led to Companies House paying compensation
and costs of Pounds 2,500 - referred to 'a chain of errors' from the agency.
Mr James Pawsey, Conservative chairman of the committee, said: 'There seems
to be a serious problem. This is an extraordinary number of complaints.'
Following changes to company law in 1989, Companies House began imposing
fines with a minimum of Pounds 100 for businesses failing to file their
annual accounts on time.
To date, 164,000 penalties have been imposed on companies, generating fines
of Pounds 33m, which are remitted to the Treasury. The annual administrative
cost of running the late penalty regime is Pounds 1.3m.
</TEXT>
