<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / Checklist for pension buyers issued by SIB
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Checklists to help people thinking of buying personal pensions were
published yesterday by the Securities and Investments Board, the City's
chief watchdog, as part of its efforts to improve standards in this area of
business.
Two factsheets which list questions and issues that potential investors
should raise with sales agents or financial advisers will be given wide
distribution through outlets such as Citizens' Advice Bureaux and public
libraries by the end of the month.
They will also be publicised through the Trades Union Congress and the
Confederation of British Industry. These organisations are being asked to
make their members aware of the checklists.
Sample copies have been sent to all members of the National Association of
Pension Funds and to all public-sector pension schemes. Some 500,000 have
been printed so far.
One factsheet covers the position of people who are thinking of opting out
of - or not joining - a pension scheme for which they are eligible with an
employer. The other deals with people who are thinking of transferring a
lump sum from the pension scheme of a former employer.
The fact that the regulator is taking these steps directly to try to ensure
that customers take well-informed decisions suggests that it doubts whether
the life insurance industry can convey this information clearly and
effectively to potential customers.
The intensive programme that the regulators have undertaken relating to the
sale of personal pensions follows a pilot study published last December.
This suggested that the vast majority of pensions transfer cases did not
meet regulatory requirements. The survey led to widespread public unease
about personal pensions business, which appears to have been reflected in
the sales of pension transfers in the first three months of this year.
More than 500,000 people are estimated to have bought pension transfers,
while the number to have opted out of an existing occupational scheme is
thought to be much lower. Regulators believe that the guidance has to
address both types of investment because a decision to opt out of an
occupational scheme may make someone worse off in retirement.
Each factsheet focuses first on basic questions for customers to address in
considering the pension scheme they might leave. These include finding out
whether the scheme is based on final salary or on purchasing particular
benefits; and whether they realise that in leaving the scheme they might
give up some of the benefits for which they are eligible.
It goes on to a checklist of questions which potential investors should make
sure their financial adviser has answered. It also advises customers to
check what commission they will pay to the sales agent or adviser, and
specifically urges them to shop around.
The paper dealing with opting out also contains a clear warning that such a
decision is highly likely to be a bad one. 'You will nearly always be better
off if you stay in, or join, your employer's pension scheme,' it warns.
The next stage of the regulatory work on pension transfers will be the
issuing of guidance on how to deal with cases where a customer has suffered
as a result of following poor advice to transfer or opt out of an employer's
scheme. This is due to be published in July.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
