<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / Dorrell critical of high dividends
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Dividend payouts by British companies may have become too high and too
inflexible, Mr Stephen Dorrell, the financial secretary to the Treasury,
said yesterday in a speech to the council of the Confederation of British
Industry.
Mr Dorrell, who is conducting a review of savings and the movement of funds
through the economy, said that in the early 1980s companies were
distributing between 20 per cent and 25 per cent of their after-tax earnings
in dividends. This 'payout ratio' rose to more than 50 per cent by 1990 and
to more than 60 per cent in both 1991 and 1992.
'A long-term rise in dividend payout ratios necessarily implies reduced
availability to a business of its retained earnings, and greater reliance on
its ability to raise new capital from the markets,' said Mr Dorrell.
'It undeniably increases the cost of capital if the system requires a
business to employ professionals to secure access to capital which it has
just distributed.'
Mr Dorrell added that the system may inhibit the ability of smaller
companies to obtain capital, since they feel the same pressure to
distribute, but face disproportionately greater costs when raising new
capital. He said that the inflexibility of dividend payouts had disturbed
the balance of risk between shareholders and other capital providers.
Surprisingly little capital was provided in the form of term debt or
preference shares, Mr Dorrell said, and both businesses and investors might
benefit from a broader range of financing instruments.
However, he ruled out specific dividend controls and added that tax changes
would not be made until the government could 'first identify the improvement
we seek and secondly establish that tax changes are the best means of
achieving it'. He added: 'Neither of those two conditions have yet been
established.'
Lex, Page 24
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
