<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / Clarke's subtle differences with George
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, and Mr Eddie George, the governor of the
Bank of England, agreed at their meeting on March 30 that a further cut in
interest rates might be warranted if the economy weakened and inflationary
pressures remained subdued.
But the official minutes of the meeting, released yesterday, show a nuanced
difference in their approach to lower rates, with Mr Clarke more supportive
of an eventual easing of borrowing costs than Mr George.
The meeting, which by all accounts was short, took place at a time of rising
long-term bond rates and turbulence on financial markets which overshadowed
evidence of continuing steady non-inflationary growth in Britain. It ended
with Mr Clarke concluding that 'it was not appropriate to change interest
rates at the moment, in particular because of current market volatility'.
According to the minutes, Mr George came to the conclusion that the latest
evidence did not justify a further cut in interest rates from the 5.25 per
cent base rate set in February.
The governor said it remained 'possible that a further cut would be
warranted in the future if there were hard evidence of activity turning out
weaker than expected and inflation projections were revised down'.
But he added: 'It would also be very unwise to consider an interest-rate cut
in current market conditions.' Mr Clarke agreed that market volatility was
an important factor and that a move on interest rates could put the
credibility of monetary policy at risk.
'However, he felt that the markets had overreacted to events' and that
'there was no evidence in recent data of a deterioration in the prospect for
inflation'.
The minutes show the chancellor taking a subtly different approach to Mr
George by setting less tough inflation conditions for a rate cut and
worrying about any delay in tackling a possible economic slowdown.
Mr Clarke 'felt that if activity weakened and inflationary pressures
remained subdued, there might be a case for a further cut in interest rates.
'He was also concerned that waiting for cast-iron evidence of a slowdown in
activity before moving interest rates would risk delaying too long.'
By showing broad agreement, the latest minutes supported Mr Clarke's denial
this week of a clash between himself and Mr George. Instead, they give a
picture of two men who relish intelligent debate over economic policy
issues.
As the chancellor told the Confederation of British Industry dinner on
Tuesday night: 'I share the same aim of low inflation and sound money. I
decide, but we discuss and seek to agree.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
